{"title_page": "Beatriz Cortez", "text_new": "'''Beatriz Cortez''' is a Los Angeles-based artist and scholar from [[El Salvador]].<ref name=\"Cortez1\">{{cite news |last=Miranda |first=Carolina |date=May 10, 2019 |title=The steely art of Beatriz Cortez imagines otherworldly utopias at Craft Contemporary |url=https://www.latimes.com/entertainment/arts/miranda/la-et-cam-beatriz-cortez-craft-contemporary-20190510-story.html |work=Los Angeles Times |location= |access-date=May 10, 2019 }}</ref> <ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/artanddesign/2019/feb/20/latin-american-art-museums-boston-new-york|title='Representation does matter': the rise of Latin American art in museums|last=Sayej|first=Nadja|date=2019-02-20|work=The Guardian|access-date=2019-03-09|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> In 2017, Cortez was featured in a science fiction-themed exhibit at [[University of California, Riverside]],<ref>{{cite news |last=Finkel |first=Jori |date=August 25, 2017 |title=For Latino Artists in Sci-Fi Show, Everyone\u2019s an Alien |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/08/25/arts/design/science-fiction-artists-university-of-california-riverside-pacific-standard-time.html |work=New York Times |location= |access-date=May 20, 2019 }}</ref> and in 2018, her work was shown in the ''Made in L.A.'' group artist exhibition at the [[Hammer Museum]] in Los Angeles. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://bombmagazine.org/articles/simultaneities-beatriz-cortez-interviewed/|title=Simultaneities: Beatriz Cortez Interviewed by Rafa Esparza - BOMB Magazine|website=bombmagazine.org|access-date=2019-03-09}}</ref> She holds a [[Doctor of Philosophy|Ph.D]] in Latin American Literature from [[Arizona State University]]. She also earned an [[Master of Fine Arts|M.F.A.]] from the [[California Institute of the Arts]]. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://hammer.ucla.edu/exhibitions/2018/made-in-la-2018/beatriz-cortez/|title=Beatriz Cortez - Hammer Museum|website=The Hammer Museum|language=en|access-date=2019-03-09}}</ref> Her architectural designs were exhibited at [[Craft and Folk Art Museum|Craft Contemporary]] in a show entitled Trinidad/Joy Station, which was her first major solo museum exhibition. <ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.cafam.org/exhibitions/|title=Craft Contemporary|website=www.cafam.org|access-date=2019-03-09}}</ref> Cortez currently teaches in the Central American Studies department at [[California State University, Northridge]].<ref name=\"Cortez1\" />  According to Cortez's, her work explores \"simultaneity, life in different temporalities and different versions of modernity, particularly in relation to memory and loss in the after math of war and the experience of migration\". <ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://beatrizcortez.com/bio/|title=Bio|date=2012-01-25|website=BEATRIZ CORTEZ|language=en|access-date=2019-06-06}}</ref> Cortez has been honored with the 2018 Rema Hort Mann Foundation Fellowship for Emerging Artists, the 2017 Artist Community Engagement Grant, and the 2016 California Community Foundation Fellowship for Visual Artists.<ref name=\":1\" /> Beatriz Cortez is represented by Commonwealth and Council, Los Angeles.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://commonwealthandcouncil.com/us|title=Commonwealth and Council / Us|website=Commonwealth and Council|language=en|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref> \n\n== Selected Works of Art ==\n\n=== ''Tzolk'in'' ===\nOne of Cortez's most popular works is a sculpture called ''Tzolk'in''. Cortez created two identical sculptures in two separate locations. One was located at the [[Hammer Museum]], part of the ''Made in L.A. 2018'' installation. The other sculpture was by the Los Angeles river as a site specific, independent public art sculpture. The reason for the drastically different locations was to highlight the different realities that exist within the same cities. Both of the sculptures were facing each other, even though they were twenty miles apart, the reason for this is to reference the bond that the two sculptures have to each other which is comparable to the \"bond that binds two entities of the same kind across space and time.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.lamag.com/culturefiles/4th-wall-ar-art/|title=A Local Artist's App is Using A.R. to Virtually 'Install' Artworks in Unlikely Locations|last=Martin|first=Brittany|date=2018-08-14|website=Los Angeles Magazine|language=en-US|access-date=2019-06-06}}</ref>\" \n\nThere are technically three different sculptures of ''Tzolk'in'' in the world. Cortez recreated a virtual sculpture in order to honor the death of Claudia Gomez Gonzales, who was murdered by an American Customs and Border Protection agent, near the [[Rio Grande|Rio Grande River]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2018/jun/02/guatemala-texas-rio-bravo-border-claudia-gomez|title='Claudia was a good girl. Why did they kill her?' From a Guatemalan village to death in Texas|last=Lakhani|first=Nina|date=2018-06-02|work=The Guardian|access-date=2019-06-06|last2=Dart|first2=Tom|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> Cortez was able to create the virtual ''Tzolk'in'' by partnering with [[Nancy Baker Cahill]]'s app 4th Wall. If the users of the app go to the site on the Rio Grande River and hold their phone up, they will be able to see the virtual sculpture.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== Selected Exhibitions ==\nCortez has had solo exhibitions at the Craft Contemporary Museum, Los Angeles (2019); Clockshop, Los Angeles (2018); Vincent Price Art Museum, Los Angeles (2016); Monte Vista Projects, Los Angeles (2016); Centro Cultural de Espa\u00f1a de El Salvador (2014); and Museo Municipal Tecle\u00f1o (MUTE), El Salvador (2012). Selected group exhibitions have included her work at Tina Kim Gallery, New York (2018); Hammer Museum, Los Angeles (2018); BANK/MABSOCIETY, Shanghai, China (2017); Ballroom Marfa, Marfa, Texas (2017); Whitney Museum of American Art, New York (2017); Centro Cultural Metropolitano, Quito, Ecuador (2016); and Los Angeles Contemporary Exhibitions (2016). Cortez has received an Emergency Grant from the Foundation of Contemporary Arts (2019), the Rema Hort Mann Foundation Emerging Artist Grant (2018), the Artist Community Engagement Grant (2017), and the California Community Foundation Fellowship for Visual Artists (2016).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://beatrizcortez.com/bio/|title=Bio|date=2012-01-25|website=BEATRIZ CORTEZ|language=en|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref>\n\n=== ''Trinidad / Joy Station'' (2019) ===\n''Trinidad / Joy Station'' was on view in from January 27 \u2013 May 12, 2019 at [https://www.craftcontemporary.org/ Craft Contemporary] in Los Angeles.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.craftcontemporary.org/exhibitions/beatriz-cortez/|title=Beatriz Cortez: Trinidad / Joy Station \u2013 Craft Contemporary|website=www.craftcontemporary.org|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref> In this exhibition Cortez imagined a future communal life that combines upon geodesic dome architecture or post-war utopian communities in the United States with the collective living practices of the ancient Maya in what is present-day El Salvador.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.craftcontemporary.org/exhibitions/beatriz-cortez/|title=Beatriz Cortez: Trinidad / Joy Station \u2013 Craft Contemporary|website=www.craftcontemporary.org|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref> The installation speaks to notions of speculative thought, nomadism, and Spinozian Joy.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://beatrizcortez.com/trinidad-joy-station/|title=Trinidad: Joy Station|date=2019-03-16|website=BEATRIZ CORTEZ|language=en|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref> \n\n== Collections ==\nCortez's work is featured in the following collections: El Paso Museum of Art (El Paso, Texas), Ford Foundation (New York, NY), Mario Cader-Fench Collection (Miami, Florida), and Museo Comunitario Kaqjay (Patzic\u00eda, Guatemala).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://beatrizcortez.com/cv/|title=CV|date=2012-01-25|website=BEATRIZ CORTEZ|language=en|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref> \n\n== Awards and Fellowships ==\nAwards, grants, and fellowships Cortez has received include: Artadia Los Angeles Award (2020), Inaugural Frieze LIFEWTR Sculpture Prize (2019), Emergency Grant. Foundation for Contemporary Arts (2019), Rema Hort Mann Foundation Grant for Emerging Artists (2018), The Main Museum Artist-in-Residence, Los Angeles (2018), Artist Community Engagement Grant in Los Angeles (2017), California Community Foundation Fellowship for Visual Artists (2016-2017), The Reef, Artist-in-Residence (2015-2016), Cerritos College Art + TECH Artist-in-Residence (2015), ''Guatemala despu\u00e9s'': \u00a0Investigaci\u00f3n art\u00edstica, intercambio y enlace p\u00fablico en lugares de memoria y transformaci\u00f3n. (''Guatemala afterwards'': Artistic research, exchange, and public engagement in sites of memory and transformation). \u201cVida y memoria\u201d (\u201cLife and Memory\u201d), proyecto colectivo con Kaqjay Moloj (collaborative project with the Kaqjay Moloj collective). Site specific: Patzic\u00eda, Guatemala. Ciudad imaginaci\u00f3n & the New School in New York City (2014-2015), and Walt Disney Company Foundation Scholarship, California Institute of the Arts (2013-2015). <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://beatrizcortez.com/cv/|title=CV|date=2012-01-25|website=BEATRIZ CORTEZ|language=en|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref>\n\n== Notes ==\n<references />\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Cortez, Beatriz}}\n[[Category:American artists]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Salvadoran emigrants to the United States]]\n{{ElSalvador-bio-stub}}\n", "text_old": "'''Beatriz Cortez''' is a Los Angeles-based artist and scholar from [[El Salvador]].<ref name=\"Cortez1\">{{cite news |last=Miranda |first=Carolina |date=May 10, 2019 |title=The steely art of Beatriz Cortez imagines otherworldly utopias at Craft Contemporary |url=https://www.latimes.com/entertainment/arts/miranda/la-et-cam-beatriz-cortez-craft-contemporary-20190510-story.html |work=Los Angeles Times |location= |access-date=May 10, 2019 }}</ref> <ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/artanddesign/2019/feb/20/latin-american-art-museums-boston-new-york|title='Representation does matter': the rise of Latin American art in museums|last=Sayej|first=Nadja|date=2019-02-20|work=The Guardian|access-date=2019-03-09|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> In 2017, Cortez was featured in a science fiction-themed exhibit at [[University of California, Riverside]],<ref>{{cite news |last=Finkel |first=Jori |date=August 25, 2017 |title=For Latino Artists in Sci-Fi Show, Everyone\u2019s an Alien |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/08/25/arts/design/science-fiction-artists-university-of-california-riverside-pacific-standard-time.html |work=New York Times |location= |access-date=May 20, 2019 }}</ref> and in 2018, her work was shown in the ''Made in L.A.'' group artist exhibition at the [[Hammer Museum]] in Los Angeles. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://bombmagazine.org/articles/simultaneities-beatriz-cortez-interviewed/|title=Simultaneities: Beatriz Cortez Interviewed by Rafa Esparza - BOMB Magazine|website=bombmagazine.org|access-date=2019-03-09}}</ref> She holds a [[Doctor of Philosophy|Ph.D]] in Latin American Literature from [[Arizona State University]]. She also earned an [[Master of Fine Arts|M.F.A.]] from the [[California Institute of the Arts]]. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://hammer.ucla.edu/exhibitions/2018/made-in-la-2018/beatriz-cortez/|title=Beatriz Cortez - Hammer Museum|website=The Hammer Museum|language=en|access-date=2019-03-09}}</ref> Her architectural designs were exhibited at [[Craft and Folk Art Museum|Craft Contemporary]] in a show entitled Trinidad/Joy Station, which was her first major solo museum exhibition. <ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.cafam.org/exhibitions/|title=Craft Contemporary|website=www.cafam.org|access-date=2019-03-09}}</ref> Cortez currently teaches in the Central American Studies department at [[California State University, Northridge]].<ref name=\"Cortez1\" />  According to Cortez's website, her work is all about exploring \"simultaneity, life in different temporalities and different versions of modernity, particularly in relation to memory and loss in the after math of war and the experience of migration\". <ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://beatrizcortez.com/bio/|title=Bio|date=2012-01-25|website=BEATRIZ CORTEZ|language=en|access-date=2019-06-06}}</ref> Cortez has been honored with the 2018 Rema Hort Mann Foundation Fellowship for Emerging Artists, the 2017 Artist Community Engagement Grant, and the 2016 California Community Foundation Fellowship for Visual Artists.<ref name=\":1\" /> Beatriz Cortez is represented by Commonwealth and Council, Los Angeles.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://commonwealthandcouncil.com/us|title=Commonwealth and Council / Us|website=Commonwealth and Council|language=en|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref> \n\n== Selected Works of Art ==\n\n=== ''Tzolk'in'' ===\nOne of Cortez's most popular works is a sculpture called ''Tzolk'in''. Cortez created two identical sculptures in two separate locations. One was located at the [[Hammer Museum]], part of the ''Made in L.A. 2018'' installation. The other sculpture was by the Los Angeles river as a site specific, independent public art sculpture. The reason for the drastically different locations was to highlight the different realities that exist within the same cities. Both of the sculptures were facing each other, even though they were twenty miles apart, the reason for this is to reference the bond that the two sculptures have to each other which is comparable to the \"bond that binds two entities of the same kind across space and time.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.lamag.com/culturefiles/4th-wall-ar-art/|title=A Local Artist's App is Using A.R. to Virtually 'Install' Artworks in Unlikely Locations|last=Martin|first=Brittany|date=2018-08-14|website=Los Angeles Magazine|language=en-US|access-date=2019-06-06}}</ref>\" \n\nThere are technically three different sculptures of ''Tzolk'in'' in the world. Cortez recreated a virtual sculpture in order to honor the death of Claudia Gomez Gonzales, who was murdered by an American Customs and Border Protection agent, near the [[Rio Grande|Rio Grande River]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2018/jun/02/guatemala-texas-rio-bravo-border-claudia-gomez|title='Claudia was a good girl. Why did they kill her?' From a Guatemalan village to death in Texas|last=Lakhani|first=Nina|date=2018-06-02|work=The Guardian|access-date=2019-06-06|last2=Dart|first2=Tom|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> Cortez was able to create the virtual ''Tzolk'in'' by partnering with [[Nancy Baker Cahill]]'s app 4th Wall. If the users of the app go to the site on the Rio Grande River and hold their phone up, they will be able to see the virtual sculpture.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== Selected Exhibitions ==\nCortez has had solo exhibitions at the Craft Contemporary Museum, Los Angeles (2019); Clockshop, Los Angeles (2018); Vincent Price Art Museum, Los Angeles (2016); Monte Vista Projects, Los Angeles (2016); Centro Cultural de Espa\u00f1a de El Salvador (2014); and Museo Municipal Tecle\u00f1o (MUTE), El Salvador (2012). Selected group exhibitions have included her work at Tina Kim Gallery, New York (2018); Hammer Museum, Los Angeles (2018); BANK/MABSOCIETY, Shanghai, China (2017); Ballroom Marfa, Marfa, Texas (2017); Whitney Museum of American Art, New York (2017); Centro Cultural Metropolitano, Quito, Ecuador (2016); and Los Angeles Contemporary Exhibitions (2016). Cortez has received an Emergency Grant from the Foundation of Contemporary Arts (2019), the Rema Hort Mann Foundation Emerging Artist Grant (2018), the Artist Community Engagement Grant (2017), and the California Community Foundation Fellowship for Visual Artists (2016).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://beatrizcortez.com/bio/|title=Bio|date=2012-01-25|website=BEATRIZ CORTEZ|language=en|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref>\n\n=== ''Trinidad / Joy Station'' (2019) ===\n''Trinidad / Joy Station'' was on view in from January 27 \u2013 May 12, 2019 at [https://www.craftcontemporary.org/ Craft Contemporary] in Los Angeles.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.craftcontemporary.org/exhibitions/beatriz-cortez/|title=Beatriz Cortez: Trinidad / Joy Station \u2013 Craft Contemporary|website=www.craftcontemporary.org|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref> In this exhibition Cortez imagined a future communal life that combines upon geodesic dome architecture or post-war utopian communities in the United States with the collective living practices of the ancient Maya in what is present-day El Salvador.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.craftcontemporary.org/exhibitions/beatriz-cortez/|title=Beatriz Cortez: Trinidad / Joy Station \u2013 Craft Contemporary|website=www.craftcontemporary.org|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref> The installation speaks to notions of speculative thought, nomadism, and Spinozian Joy.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://beatrizcortez.com/trinidad-joy-station/|title=Trinidad: Joy Station|date=2019-03-16|website=BEATRIZ CORTEZ|language=en|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref> \n\n== Collections ==\nCortez's work is featured in the following collections: El Paso Museum of Art (El Paso, Texas), Ford Foundation (New York, NY), Mario Cader-Fench Collection (Miami, Florida), and Museo Comunitario Kaqjay (Patzic\u00eda, Guatemala).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://beatrizcortez.com/cv/|title=CV|date=2012-01-25|website=BEATRIZ CORTEZ|language=en|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref> \n\n== Awards and Fellowships ==\nAwards, grants, and fellowships Cortez has received include: Artadia Los Angeles Award (2020), Inaugural Frieze LIFEWTR Sculpture Prize (2019), Emergency Grant. Foundation for Contemporary Arts (2019), Rema Hort Mann Foundation Grant for Emerging Artists (2018), The Main Museum Artist-in-Residence, Los Angeles (2018), Artist Community Engagement Grant in Los Angeles (2017), California Community Foundation Fellowship for Visual Artists (2016-2017), The Reef, Artist-in-Residence (2015-2016), Cerritos College Art + TECH Artist-in-Residence (2015), ''Guatemala despu\u00e9s'': \u00a0Investigaci\u00f3n art\u00edstica, intercambio y enlace p\u00fablico en lugares de memoria y transformaci\u00f3n. (''Guatemala afterwards'': Artistic research, exchange, and public engagement in sites of memory and transformation). \u201cVida y memoria\u201d (\u201cLife and Memory\u201d), proyecto colectivo con Kaqjay Moloj (collaborative project with the Kaqjay Moloj collective). Site specific: Patzic\u00eda, Guatemala. Ciudad imaginaci\u00f3n & the New School in New York City (2014-2015), and Walt Disney Company Foundation Scholarship, California Institute of the Arts (2013-2015). <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://beatrizcortez.com/cv/|title=CV|date=2012-01-25|website=BEATRIZ CORTEZ|language=en|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref>\n\n== Notes ==\n<references />\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Cortez, Beatriz}}\n[[Category:American artists]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Salvadoran emigrants to the United States]]\n{{ElSalvador-bio-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Ylrove", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Beatriz_Cortez"}
{"title_page": "Hugo Dittberner", "text_new": "{{short description|German writer|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2014}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name        = Hugo Dittberner\n| image       = \n| caption     = \n| birth_date  = 16 November 1944\n| birth_place = [[Gieboldehausen]], Germany\n| death_date  = \n| death_place = \n| education   = \n| occupation  = Writer\n| spouse      = \n| domestic_partner =\n| children    = \n| nationality = German\n| credits     = \n}}\n'''Hugo Dittberner''' (born [[Gieboldehausen]] 16 November 1944) is a German writer.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://portal.dnb.de/opac.htm;jsessionid=CCA16B6926B6783CB973345F1EB92D29.prod-worker0?method=moveDown&currentResultId=%22115782605%22%26any&categoryId=persons|title=DNB, Katalog der Deutschen Nationalbibliothek|work=Katalog der Deutschen Nationalbibliothek|accessdate=18 September 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Early years==\nHugo Dittberner is the son of an accountant. Between 1956 and 1965 Dittberner attended a boarding school in [[Bad Nenndorf]].   After successfully completing his schooling he moved on to [[G\u00f6ttingen University]] where he studied [[German studies|German literature and linguistics]], history and philosophy, graduating in 1972.   He taught briefly at [[Karlsruhe University]] before settling to the life of a freelance writer.{{citation needed|date=September 2014}}\n\n<div style=\"float: right; margin: 0 0 0.5em 1em; width: 50.5em; text-align: centre; font-size: 0.86em; font-family: lucida grande, sans-serif; line-height: normal;\">\n<div style=\"border: 1px solid #999999; background: #ffffff; text-align: center; padding: 1em 1em; text-align: center;\">''' Hugo Dittberner published works'''\n<div style=\"border: 1px solid #999999; background: #ffffff; text-align: left; padding: 1em 1em; text-align: centre;\">\n\n* ''Donnervogel'', G\u00f6ttingen 1973 (together with Jens Wilke)\n* ''Pasjes'', Bergen, Holland 1973\n* ''Rutschbahn'', Kassel 1973\n* ''Die fr\u00fchen Romane Heinrich Manns'', G\u00f6ttingen 1974\n* ''Heinrich Mann'', Frankfurt am Main 1974\n* ''Das Internat'', Darmstadt [u. a.] 1974\n* ''Der Bi\u00df ins Gras'', K\u00f6ln 1976\n* ''Kurzurlaub'', Darmstadt [u. a.] 1976\n* ''Drau\u00dfen im Dorf'', Reinbek bei Hamburg 1978\n* ''Jacobs Sieg'', Reinbek bei Hamburg 1979\n* ''Ruhe hinter Gardinen'', Reinbek bei Hamburg 1980\n* ''Die gebratenen Tauben'', Reinbek bei Hamburg 1981\n* ''Drei Tage Unordnung'', Bielefeld 1983\n* ''Der Tisch unter den Wolken'', G\u00f6ttingen 1986\n* ''Wie man Provinzen erobert'', Reinbek bei Hamburg 1986\n* ''Die W\u00f6rter, der Wind'', Bergen, Holland 1988\n* ''Geschichte einiger Leser'', Z\u00fcrich 1990\n* ''Im Lehm'', Bergen, Holland 1992\n* ''Das letzte fliegende Wei\u00df'', Bergen 1992\n* ''\u00dcber Wohlt\u00e4ter'', Z\u00fcrich 1992\n* ''Das letzte fliegende Wei\u00df'', Cologne 1994\n* ''Wolken und V\u00f6gel und Menschentr\u00e4nen'', G\u00f6ttingen 1995\n* ''Was ich sagen k\u00f6nnte'', Stuttgart 1996\n* ''Wasser-Elegien'', zu Klampen Verlag, Springe 1997\n* ''Arche nova'', G\u00f6ttingen 1998\n* ''Versuch zu r\u00fchmen'', Darmstadt 1999\n* ''Vor den Pferdeweiden'', Bergen, Holland 1999\n* ''Morgen\u00fcbungen'', M\u00fcnchen 2000\n* ''Das \u00e4lteste Testament'', zu Klampen Verlag, Springe 2007\n* ''Das Seevokabularium''. Wallstein-Verlag, G\u00f6ttingen 2010, {{ISBN|978-3-8353-0631-8}}\n</div></div></div>\n\n==Middle years==\nDittberner has produced a number of volumes of poetry along with numerous novels and short stories.   His colloquial poetry style marked him as part of the [[:de:Neue Subjektivit\u00e4t|\"New Subjectivity\"]] movement in the 1970s.   Both his poetry and his prose works deal with issues of daily life, frequently reflecting the interpersonal problems and relationship issues affecting members of the [[Protests of 1968|\"'68 generation\"]]\n\nBetween 1974 and 2000 Dittberner was a member of the [[:de:Verband deutscher Schriftsteller|Verband deutscher Schriftsteller (VS/ ''German Writers' Union'')]].   He is a member of the German section of [[PEN International]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pen-deutschland.de/en/pen-zentrum-deutschland/mitglieder/|title=Members \u2013 PEN-Zentrum Deutschland|work=PEN-Zentrum Deutschland|accessdate=18 September 2014}}</ref> and of the [[Mainz]] based [[Akademie der Wissenschaften und der Literatur]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.adwmainz.de/mitglieder/profil/dr-phil-hugo-dittberner.html|title=Dr. phil. Hugo Dittberner  : Akademie der Wissenschaften und der Literatur \u2013 Mainz|publisher=|accessdate=18 September 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn 1979 he was the recipient of the Award of the Cultural Committee of German Industry.<ref name=zuklampen>{{cite web|url=http://www.zuklampen.de/autoren/item/Hugo_Dittberner-41.html|title=Hugo Dittberner|publisher=|accessdate=18 September 2014}}</ref> This was followed in 1981 by a [[Villa Massimo]] stipendium.<ref name=zuklampen/>\n\nIn 1984 he won the [[:de:Nieders\u00e4chsischer Staatspreis|Lower Saxony State Prize (writers)]] and in 1994 the [[:de:Berliner Literaturpreis|Berlin Literature prize]].<ref name=zuklampen/> In 1997 Dittberner was awarded a [[Worpswede]] Artistic Stipendium, and in 2001 a Cultural Stipendium from the [[:de:K\u00fcnstlerhaus Edenkoben|Cultural Centre]] in [[Edenkoben]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kuenstlerhaus-edenkoben.de/gremien/beirat/ehemalige-mitglieder.html|title=Ehemalige Mitglieder|publisher=|accessdate=18 September 2014}}</ref> Further awards and prizes followed.\n\n==Official recognition==\nIn 2005 the [[Lower Saxony|state government]] [[Lower Saxony Order of Merit|honoured him]] with the [[:de:Verdienstkreuz|Order of Merit]]\n\n{{clear}}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Dittberner, Hugo}}\n[[Category:1944 births]]\n[[Category:People from Lower Saxony]]\n[[Category:20th-century German poets]]\n[[Category:21st-century German poets]]\n[[Category:21st-century German male writers]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:German male poets]]\n[[Category:German-language poets]]\n[[Category:20th-century German male writers]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|German writer|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2014}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name        = Hugo Dittberner\n| image       = \n| caption     = \n| birth_date  = 16 November 1944\n| birth_place = [[Gieboldehausen]], Germany\n| death_date  = \n| death_place = \n| education   = \n| occupation  = Writer\n| spouse      = \n| domestic_partner =\n| children    = \n| nationality = German\n| credits     = \n}}\n'''Hugo Dittberner''' (born [[Gieboldehausen]] 16 November 1944) is a German writer.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://portal.dnb.de/opac.htm;jsessionid=CCA16B6926B6783CB973345F1EB92D29.prod-worker0?method=moveDown&currentResultId=%22115782605%22%26any&categoryId=persons|title=DNB, Katalog der Deutschen Nationalbibliothek|work=Katalog der Deutschen Nationalbibliothek|accessdate=18 September 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Early years==\nHugo Dittberner is the son of an accountant. Between 1956 and 1965 Dittberner attended a boarding school in [[Bad Nenndorf]].   After successfully completing his schooling he moved on to [[G\u00f6ttingen University]] where he studied [[German studies|German literature and linguistics]], history and philosophy, graduating in 1972.   He taught briefly at [[Karlsruhe University]] before settling to the life of a freelance writer.{{citation needed|date=September 2014}}\n\n<div style=\"float: right; margin: 0 0 0.5em 1em; width: 50.5em; text-align: centre; font-size: 0.86em; font-family: lucida grande, sans-serif; line-height: normal;\">\n<div style=\"border: 1px solid #999999; background: #ffffff; text-align: center; padding: 1em 1em; text-align: center;\">''' Hugo Dittberner published works'''\n<div style=\"border: 1px solid #999999; background: #ffffff; text-align: left; padding: 1em 1em; text-align: centre;\">\n\n* ''Donnervogel'', G\u00f6ttingen 1973 (together with Jens Wilke)\n* ''Pasjes'', Bergen, Holland 1973\n* ''Rutschbahn'', Kassel 1973\n* ''Die fr\u00fchen Romane Heinrich Manns'', G\u00f6ttingen 1974\n* ''Heinrich Mann'', Frankfurt am Main 1974\n* ''Das Internat'', Darmstadt [u. a.] 1974\n* ''Der Bi\u00df ins Gras'', K\u00f6ln 1976\n* ''Kurzurlaub'', Darmstadt [u. a.] 1976\n* ''Drau\u00dfen im Dorf'', Reinbek bei Hamburg 1978\n* ''Jacobs Sieg'', Reinbek bei Hamburg 1979\n* ''Ruhe hinter Gardinen'', Reinbek bei Hamburg 1980\n* ''Die gebratenen Tauben'', Reinbek bei Hamburg 1981\n* ''Drei Tage Unordnung'', Bielefeld 1983\n* ''Der Tisch unter den Wolken'', G\u00f6ttingen 1986\n* ''Wie man Provinzen erobert'', Reinbek bei Hamburg 1986\n* ''Die W\u00f6rter, der Wind'', Bergen, Holland 1988\n* ''Geschichte einiger Leser'', Z\u00fcrich 1990\n* ''Im Lehm'', Bergen, Holland 1992\n* ''Das letzte fliegende Wei\u00df'', Bergen 1992\n* ''\u00dcber Wohlt\u00e4ter'', Z\u00fcrich 1992\n* ''Das letzte fliegende Wei\u00df'', Cologne 1994\n* ''Wolken und V\u00f6gel und Menschentr\u00e4nen'', G\u00f6ttingen 1995\n* ''Was ich sagen k\u00f6nnte'', Stuttgart 1996\n* ''Wasser-Elegien'', zu Klampen Verlag, Springe 1997\n* ''Arche nova'', G\u00f6ttingen 1998\n* ''Versuch zu r\u00fchmen'', Darmstadt 1999\n* ''Vor den Pferdeweiden'', Bergen, Holland 1999\n* ''Morgen\u00fcbungen'', M\u00fcnchen 2000\n* ''Das \u00e4lteste Testament'', zu Klampen Verlag, Springe 2007\n* ''Das Seevokabularium''. Wallstein-Verlag, G\u00f6ttingen 2010, {{ISBN|978-3-8353-0631-8}}\n</div></div></div>\n\n==Middle years==\nDittberner has produced a number of volumes of poetry along with numerous novels and short stories.   His colloquial poetry style marked him as part of the [[:de:Neue Subjektivit\u00e4t|\"New Subjectivity\"]] movement in the 1970s.   Both his poetry and his prose works deal with issues of daily life, frequently reflecting the interpersonal problems and relationship issues affecting members of the [[Protests of 1968|\"'68 generation\"]]\n\nBetween 1974 and 2000 Dittberner was a member of the [[:de:Verband deutscher Schriftsteller|Verband deutscher Schriftsteller (VS/ ''German Writers' Union'')]].   He is a member of the German section of [[PEN International]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pen-deutschland.de/en/pen-zentrum-deutschland/mitglieder/|title=Members \u2013 PEN-Zentrum Deutschland|work=PEN-Zentrum Deutschland|accessdate=18 September 2014}}</ref> and of the [[Mainz]] based [[Akademie der Wissenschaften und der Literatur]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.adwmainz.de/mitglieder/profil/dr-phil-hugo-dittberner.html|title=Dr. phil. Hugo Dittberner  : Akademie der Wissenschaften und der Literatur \u2013 Mainz|publisher=|accessdate=18 September 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn 1979 he was the recipient of the Award of the Cultural Committee of German Industry.<ref name=zuklampen>{{cite web|url=http://www.zuklampen.de/autoren/item/Hugo_Dittberner-41.html|title=Hugo Dittberner|publisher=|accessdate=18 September 2014}}</ref> This was followed in 1981 by a [[Villa Massimo]] stipendium.<ref name=zuklampen/>\n\nIn 1984 he won the [[:de:Nieders\u00e4chsischer Staatspreis|Lower Saxony State Prize (writers)]] and in 1994 the [[:de:Berliner Literaturpreis|Berlin Literature prize]].<ref name=zuklampen/> In 1997 Dittberner was awarded a [[Worpswede]] Artistic Stipendium, and in 2001 a Cultural Stipendium from the [[:de:K\u00fcnstlerhaus Edenkoben|Cultural Centre]] in [[Edenkoben]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kuenstlerhaus-edenkoben.de/gremien/beirat/ehemalige-mitglieder.html|title=Ehemalige Mitglieder|publisher=|accessdate=18 September 2014}}</ref> Further awards and prizes followed.\n\n==Official recognition==\nIn 2005 the [[Lower Saxony|state government]] [[Lower Saxony Order of Merit|honoured him]] with the [[:de:Verdienstkreuz|Order of Merit]]\n\n{{clear}}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Dittberner, Hugo}}\n[[Category:1944 births]]\n[[Category:People from Lower Saxony]]\n[[Category:20th-century German poets]]\n[[Category:21st-century German poets]]\n[[Category:21st-century male writers]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:German male poets]]\n[[Category:German-language poets]]\n[[Category:20th-century German male writers]]\n", "name_user": "Bearcat", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eReferences:recat", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hugo_Dittberner"}
{"title_page": "Horst Tomayer", "text_new": "[[File:Tomayerperrad.jpg|thumb|Horst Tomayer. Still frame from ''Cycling to Liberation'' (2009)]]\n'''Horst Tomayer''' (1 November 1938, Asch, [[Reichsgau Sudetenland|Sudetenland]] (now [[A\u0161]], [[Czech Republic]]) \u2013 13 December 2013, [[Hamburg]], [[Germany]]<ref>[http://www.neues-deutschland.de/artikel/918024.horst-tomayer-ist-tot.html \u201eHorst Tomayer ist tot\u201c], ''Neues Deutschland'', 14.</ref>) was a German poet, columnist, and actor. His column, ''Tomayers ehrliches Tagebuch'', was published from 1982 to 2013 in the monthly magazine [[Konkret]].\n\n== Life ==\nAfter an apprenticeship as an insurance salesman, Tomayer was \"a war veteran, pavement painter, IM, Niete 'at the MfS, trainee at [[Wolfgang Neuss]], with columnist [[Stefan Aust]] of St. Pauli news and actors in many soap operas'\".<ref>[https://www.titanic-magazin.de/shop/index.php?action=showdetails&from=list&pageNr=1&productId=4354da2c90b74& \u201eHorst Tomayer live: Interessieren Sie sich f\u00fcr Sexualit\u00e4t?]</ref>\n\nIn the 1970s, Tomayer worked at the Berlin Extra Service and was the author of numerous radio contributions, especially in the [[Westdeutscher Rundfunk]]-based ''Kritisches Tagebuch''. As an employee of the monthly magazine Konkret, he led numerous covert telephone conversations with high officials, entrepreneurs and dignitaries in the 1980s, and, as a \"typical Bavarian\" reactionary, he produced astonishing expressions, which then appeared in the magazine. He talked with [[Ernst J\u00fcnger]], among other things, with the voice of [[Luis Trenker]], which he mentioned in his later published notebooks - until the end did not know that it was a joke of Tomayer.<ref>{{citation\n  |title=Personalien: Horst Tomayer \n  |url=http://www.spiegel.de/spiegel/print/d-9287746.html\n  |author=\n  |work=[[Der Spiegel]]\n  |year=1993\n  |volume=\n  |issue=38\n  |series=20 September 1993\n  |pages=286\n  |quote=\n}}</ref>\n\nTomayer's column, ''Tomayer's ehrliches Tagebuch'', was published until shortly before his death in the German column Konkret. Along with publisher [[Hermann L. Gremliza]], he joined as a performing artist in the series \"''Sehr gemischtes Doppel''\".\n\nIn 1990, the [[Federal Constitutional Court]] ruled that Tomayer's parody of the German anthem [[Deutschlandlied]], had to be regarded as satire and thus art. Tomayer had been previously accused of denigrating the state and its symbols with the lines \"German Turks, German Pershings / German Big Mac, German Punk / Shall In the World / Your Old Beautiful Sound\".<ref>http://www.servat.unibe.ch/dfr/bv081298.html</ref>\n\nTomayer also continued to play side roles in television and cinema films, including the [[Otto Waalkes]] films, in film series such as ''[[Tierarzt Dr. Engel]]'', ''The King of B\u00e4renbach'' and ''[[Kir Royal \u2013 Aus dem Leben eines Klatschreporters|Kir Royal]]'', in the two \"7 Dwarfs\" films, ''[[7 Dwarves \u2013 Men Alone in the Wood|Men Alone in the Wood]]'' and ''[[7 Zwerge \u2013 Der Wald ist nicht genug|Der Wald ist nicht genug]]'', as well as in [[Wenzel Storch]]'s film ''Die Reise ins Gl\u00fcck''. In 1994, he played the main role of Bruno Ringeltaub in the {{ill|Hans-Christoph Blumenberg|de}} film ''{{ill|Rotwang mu\u00df weg!|de}}''.\n\nHe died on 13 December 2013 following complications from cancer.<ref>[http://www.konkret-magazin.de/aktuelles/aus-aktuellem-anlass/aus-aktuellem-anlass-beitrag/items/konkret-trauert-um-horst-tomayer.html \u201eKonkret trauert um Horst Tomayer\u201c], ''Konkret'', 13.</ref>\n\n== Works ==\n* ''Neuss\u2019 Testament''. Mit [[Wolfgang Neuss]]. rororo 891, Rowohlt, Reinbek bei Hamburg 1966; NA: herausgegeben und dokumentiert von Volker K\u00fchn. Syndikat, Frankfurt am Main 1985, {{ISBN|3-434-46055-1}}.\n* ''Lachend in die 80er?''  VSA, Berlin 1976, {{ISBN|3-87975-091-2}}.\n* ''Tomayers deutsche Gespr\u00e4che''. Konkret, Hamburg 1987, {{ISBN|3-922144-37-3}}.\n* ''Endlich. Postrevolution\u00e4re Kunst im IV. Reich''. (Mit Ernst Kahl, Wiglaf Droste und [[Max Goldt]]). Neue Gesellschaft f\u00fcr Bildende Kunst, Berlin 1990, {{ISBN|3-926796-13-8}}.\n* ''Hirnverbranntes und Feinziseliertes''.  Zinnober, Hamburg 1990, {{ISBN|3-89315-008-0}}.\n* ''Die Stunde der M\u00e4nnertr\u00e4nen''. Tiamat, Berlin 1995, {{ISBN|3-923118-54-6}}.\n* ''Tomayers ehrliches Tagebuch''. Konkret, Hamburg 1996, {{ISBN|3-930786-07-9}}.\n* ''German Poems''. Nautilus, Hamburg 2002, {{ISBN|3-89401-341-9}}.\n\n== CDs ==\n* ''Interessieren Sie sich f\u00fcr Sexualit\u00e4t?'' [[Compact Disc Digital Audio|Audio-CD]], Live-Mitschnitte von Auftritten im Roten Salon Berlin, in Braunschweig und im Toten Salon am Hamburger [[Thalia Theater (Hamburg)|Thalia Theater]]. Bittermann, Berlin 2005, {{ISBN|3-89320-092-4}}.\n\n==DVD==\n* ''Das sehr gemischte Doppel. Getrennt dichten \u2013 vereint vortragen'' (mit [[Hermann L. Gremliza]]), {{ISBN|3-930786-48-6}}.\n\n== Fellows about Tomayer ==\n\n{{Zitat|Horst Tomayer hat sich um das deutsche Gedicht verdient gemacht.[[Robert Gernhardt]]<ref>''Konkret'' 12/1998, S. 60.</ref>}}\n\n<poem style=\"margin-left:2em;\">\n          ''Sportsgeist''\n\nHotte, H\u00fch! \u2013 wir Radelnden\nSind die sich selber Adelnden\nOb Sonne oder Regenschauer\nWir radeln gegen Bergsons Dauer\nDenn Da''sein'' hier auf Erden\nDas gibt\u2019s blo\u00df als Da''werden''\nBis zum Exit, bis zum Schlusse\n\u2013 S\u00fcffisante Sisyphusse\nSchon biste \u00fcber siebzig\nUnd sagst Dir selbst: Dett jiebt sich.\n:::::::[[Natias Neutert]]<ref>Natias Neutert: ''Sportsgeist.'' (f\u00fcr Hotte Tomayer) In: ''Konkret.'' 4/2012, S. 7 sowie in: ''Fahrradspa\u00df. Geschichten und Gedichte''. Ausgew\u00e4hlt von Alexander Kluy. Reclam Verlag, Stuttgart 2014, {{ISBN|978-3-15-010976-2}}, S.&nbsp;65.</ref>\n</poem>\n\n== External links ==\n* {{German National Library portal|122839048}}\n* {{IMDb name|0866535}}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Tomayer, Horst}}\n[[Category:1938 births]]\n[[Category:2013 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from A\u0161]]\n[[Category:People from Sudetenland]]\n[[Category:Sudeten German people]]\n[[Category:German essayists]]\n[[Category:German poets]]\n[[Category:German columnists]]\n[[Category:20th-century German writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century German writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century German male writers]]\n[[Category:German male actors]]\n[[Category:20th-century German male actors]]\n[[Category:21st-century German male actors]]\n[[Category:20th-century German male writers]]\n[[Category:German male non-fiction writers]]\n", "text_old": "[[File:Tomayerperrad.jpg|thumb|Horst Tomayer. Still frame from ''Cycling to Liberation'' (2009)]]\n'''Horst Tomayer''' (1 November 1938, Asch, [[Reichsgau Sudetenland|Sudetenland]] (now [[A\u0161]], [[Czech Republic]]) \u2013 13 December 2013, [[Hamburg]], [[Germany]]<ref>[http://www.neues-deutschland.de/artikel/918024.horst-tomayer-ist-tot.html \u201eHorst Tomayer ist tot\u201c], ''Neues Deutschland'', 14.</ref>) was a German poet, columnist, and actor. His column, ''Tomayers ehrliches Tagebuch'', was published from 1982 to 2013 in the monthly magazine [[Konkret]].\n\n== Life ==\nAfter an apprenticeship as an insurance salesman, Tomayer was \"a war veteran, pavement painter, IM, Niete 'at the MfS, trainee at [[Wolfgang Neuss]], with columnist [[Stefan Aust]] of St. Pauli news and actors in many soap operas'\".<ref>[https://www.titanic-magazin.de/shop/index.php?action=showdetails&from=list&pageNr=1&productId=4354da2c90b74& \u201eHorst Tomayer live: Interessieren Sie sich f\u00fcr Sexualit\u00e4t?]</ref>\n\nIn the 1970s, Tomayer worked at the Berlin Extra Service and was the author of numerous radio contributions, especially in the [[Westdeutscher Rundfunk]]-based ''Kritisches Tagebuch''. As an employee of the monthly magazine Konkret, he led numerous covert telephone conversations with high officials, entrepreneurs and dignitaries in the 1980s, and, as a \"typical Bavarian\" reactionary, he produced astonishing expressions, which then appeared in the magazine. He talked with [[Ernst J\u00fcnger]], among other things, with the voice of [[Luis Trenker]], which he mentioned in his later published notebooks - until the end did not know that it was a joke of Tomayer.<ref>{{citation\n  |title=Personalien: Horst Tomayer \n  |url=http://www.spiegel.de/spiegel/print/d-9287746.html\n  |author=\n  |work=[[Der Spiegel]]\n  |year=1993\n  |volume=\n  |issue=38\n  |series=20 September 1993\n  |pages=286\n  |quote=\n}}</ref>\n\nTomayer's column, ''Tomayer's ehrliches Tagebuch'', was published until shortly before his death in the German column Konkret. Along with publisher [[Hermann L. Gremliza]], he joined as a performing artist in the series \"''Sehr gemischtes Doppel''\".\n\nIn 1990, the [[Federal Constitutional Court]] ruled that Tomayer's parody of the German anthem [[Deutschlandlied]], had to be regarded as satire and thus art. Tomayer had been previously accused of denigrating the state and its symbols with the lines \"German Turks, German Pershings / German Big Mac, German Punk / Shall In the World / Your Old Beautiful Sound\".<ref>http://www.servat.unibe.ch/dfr/bv081298.html</ref>\n\nTomayer also continued to play side roles in television and cinema films, including the [[Otto Waalkes]] films, in film series such as ''[[Tierarzt Dr. Engel]]'', ''The King of B\u00e4renbach'' and ''[[Kir Royal \u2013 Aus dem Leben eines Klatschreporters|Kir Royal]]'', in the two \"7 Dwarfs\" films, ''[[7 Dwarves \u2013 Men Alone in the Wood|Men Alone in the Wood]]'' and ''[[7 Zwerge \u2013 Der Wald ist nicht genug|Der Wald ist nicht genug]]'', as well as in [[Wenzel Storch]]'s film ''Die Reise ins Gl\u00fcck''. In 1994, he played the main role of Bruno Ringeltaub in the {{ill|Hans-Christoph Blumenberg|de}} film ''{{ill|Rotwang mu\u00df weg!|de}}''.\n\nHe died on 13 December 2013 following complications from cancer.<ref>[http://www.konkret-magazin.de/aktuelles/aus-aktuellem-anlass/aus-aktuellem-anlass-beitrag/items/konkret-trauert-um-horst-tomayer.html \u201eKonkret trauert um Horst Tomayer\u201c], ''Konkret'', 13.</ref>\n\n== Works ==\n* ''Neuss\u2019 Testament''. Mit [[Wolfgang Neuss]]. rororo 891, Rowohlt, Reinbek bei Hamburg 1966; NA: herausgegeben und dokumentiert von Volker K\u00fchn. Syndikat, Frankfurt am Main 1985, {{ISBN|3-434-46055-1}}.\n* ''Lachend in die 80er?''  VSA, Berlin 1976, {{ISBN|3-87975-091-2}}.\n* ''Tomayers deutsche Gespr\u00e4che''. Konkret, Hamburg 1987, {{ISBN|3-922144-37-3}}.\n* ''Endlich. Postrevolution\u00e4re Kunst im IV. Reich''. (Mit Ernst Kahl, Wiglaf Droste und [[Max Goldt]]). Neue Gesellschaft f\u00fcr Bildende Kunst, Berlin 1990, {{ISBN|3-926796-13-8}}.\n* ''Hirnverbranntes und Feinziseliertes''.  Zinnober, Hamburg 1990, {{ISBN|3-89315-008-0}}.\n* ''Die Stunde der M\u00e4nnertr\u00e4nen''. Tiamat, Berlin 1995, {{ISBN|3-923118-54-6}}.\n* ''Tomayers ehrliches Tagebuch''. Konkret, Hamburg 1996, {{ISBN|3-930786-07-9}}.\n* ''German Poems''. Nautilus, Hamburg 2002, {{ISBN|3-89401-341-9}}.\n\n== CDs ==\n* ''Interessieren Sie sich f\u00fcr Sexualit\u00e4t?'' [[Compact Disc Digital Audio|Audio-CD]], Live-Mitschnitte von Auftritten im Roten Salon Berlin, in Braunschweig und im Toten Salon am Hamburger [[Thalia Theater (Hamburg)|Thalia Theater]]. Bittermann, Berlin 2005, {{ISBN|3-89320-092-4}}.\n\n==DVD==\n* ''Das sehr gemischte Doppel. Getrennt dichten \u2013 vereint vortragen'' (mit [[Hermann L. Gremliza]]), {{ISBN|3-930786-48-6}}.\n\n== Fellows about Tomayer ==\n\n{{Zitat|Horst Tomayer hat sich um das deutsche Gedicht verdient gemacht.[[Robert Gernhardt]]<ref>''Konkret'' 12/1998, S. 60.</ref>}}\n\n<poem style=\"margin-left:2em;\">\n          ''Sportsgeist''\n\nHotte, H\u00fch! \u2013 wir Radelnden\nSind die sich selber Adelnden\nOb Sonne oder Regenschauer\nWir radeln gegen Bergsons Dauer\nDenn Da''sein'' hier auf Erden\nDas gibt\u2019s blo\u00df als Da''werden''\nBis zum Exit, bis zum Schlusse\n\u2013 S\u00fcffisante Sisyphusse\nSchon biste \u00fcber siebzig\nUnd sagst Dir selbst: Dett jiebt sich.\n:::::::[[Natias Neutert]]<ref>Natias Neutert: ''Sportsgeist.'' (f\u00fcr Hotte Tomayer) In: ''Konkret.'' 4/2012, S. 7 sowie in: ''Fahrradspa\u00df. Geschichten und Gedichte''. Ausgew\u00e4hlt von Alexander Kluy. Reclam Verlag, Stuttgart 2014, {{ISBN|978-3-15-010976-2}}, S.&nbsp;65.</ref>\n</poem>\n\n== External links ==\n* {{German National Library portal|122839048}}\n* {{IMDb name|0866535}}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Tomayer, Horst}}\n[[Category:1938 births]]\n[[Category:2013 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from A\u0161]]\n[[Category:People from Sudetenland]]\n[[Category:Sudeten German people]]\n[[Category:German essayists]]\n[[Category:German poets]]\n[[Category:German columnists]]\n[[Category:20th-century German writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century German writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century male writers]]\n[[Category:German male actors]]\n[[Category:20th-century German male actors]]\n[[Category:21st-century German male actors]]\n[[Category:20th-century German male writers]]\n[[Category:German male non-fiction writers]]\n", "name_user": "Bearcat", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eReferences:recat", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Horst_Tomayer"}
{"title_page": "Herbert Wetterauer", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2019}}\n[[File:Martin Heidegger for WP.jpg|thumb|upright|Brush drawing by Herbert Wetterauer (Portrait of [[Martin Heidegger]], 2010)]]\n'''Herbert Wetterauer''' (born 21 April 1957 in [[Karlsruhe]], [[West Germany]]) is a German painter, sculptor and author. He is known for his paintings in ink and life-sized figures made of [[paperboard]], for which he developed his own technique.\n\nWetterauer studied German Language at the [[University of Karlsruhe]] and [[Fine Arts]] at the [[State Academy of Fine Arts Karlsruhe]]. For many years he was busy as a journalist, writing primary [[art critic]]s.\n\nIn 2009 his first novel named ''Stromness'' appeared,<ref>[http://www.schardtverlag.de/wetterauer-herbert-344.html The novel ''Stromness'' at Schardt Verlag]</ref> followed by the novels ''Du sollst nicht vertrauen''<ref>[https://www.amazon.co.uk/sollst-nicht-vertrauen-German-ebook/dp/B00BHERWDQ/ref=sr_1_1?s=books&ie=UTF8&qid=1361435208&sr=1-1 The novel ''Du sollst nicht vertrauen'' at Amazon UK]</ref> and ''tod.com''.<ref>[http://www.infoverlag.de/produkt.html/tod-com The novel ''tod.com'' at Info Verlag]</ref>\n\n==Exhibitions (selection)==\n* 2011: Presentation by the United Artists of Karlsruhe\n* 2008: One-Man-Show at the official art-shop-window (Kunstschaufenster ) of the City of Karlsruhe\n* 2001: K\u00fcnstlerhaus-Gallery Karlsruhe\n* 1995: Art-Collection Westermann, City-Gallery of [[Rastatt]]\n* 1993: First [[wikt:biennale|Biennale]] for Material- and Textile-Art, [[Bayreuth]] and [[Manchester]]\n* 1990: First prize in the poster-competition, 4th [[:de:Karlsruher K\u00fcnstlermesse|Karlsruher Art-Mass]]\n* 1983: One-Man-Show at the State Art Museum [[Baden-Baden]]\n* 1983: One-Man-Show at Gallery Forum Rotart Karlsruhe\n\n==Own publications==\n[[File:Skulptur massive kartonmasse.JPG|thumb|right|Sculpture made of massive [[paperboard]] by Herbert Wetterauer]]\n* ''Consumption-Christmas'', pferscha Nr. 3, Graz 1974\n* ''The Mechanic of [[Cartoon]]-Drawings'', Journal of Art Nr. 5, 1975\n* ''[[Katchina doll|Katchina]]'', Ketchup-Magazine Nr. 2, 1981\n* ''KiK-Magazine'' Nr. 9 \u2013 70, 1980\u20131983\n* ''The March of the Art-History'', Artist Nr. 38, 1999\n* ''Stromness'', Schardt Verlag, Oldenburg, 2009, {{ISBN|978-3-89841-487-6}}\n* ''The White Dog'' (Short story) in ''Neues Karlsruher Lesebuch'', Info Verlag, Karlsruhe, 2010, {{ISBN|978-3-88190-589-3}}\n* ''Du sollst nicht vertrauen'', E-Book, 2013; KDP-Paperback, 2019, {{ISBN|978-1-79794-316-9}}\n* ''tod.com'', Info Verlag, Karlsruhe 2013, {{ISBN|978-3-88190-747-7}}\n\n==Reporting==\n* Badisches Tagblatt, 22 September 1983\n* [[Kunstforum international]], Bd. 69, 1984 \n* Badische Neueste Nachrichten, 30 March 1989; 26 June 2010\n* Der Kurier, 5 April 1991, 29 April 2010; 25 June 2010\n* [[N\u00fcrnberger Nachrichten]], 21 May 1993\n* [[Het Nieuwsblad]] (NL), 9 October 1994\n* [[Eindhovens Dagblad]] (NL), 16 October 1994\n* Pfalz-Echo, 21 December 2009, 25 November 2013\n* RaumK, Nr. 89, March 2010\n* Die Rheinpfalz, 6 January 2010\n* Klappe auf, Issue May 2010\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons}}\n* [[:de:Herbert Wetterauer|Herbert Wetterauer on German Wikipedia]]\n* [http://herbertwetterauer.de/ Website of Herbert Wetterauer]\n* [http://www.kulturserver.de/-/kulturschaffende/detail/27870 Official Culture-Server of the Federal Republic of Germany]\n* [http://www.bbk-karlsruhe.de/kunstler/n-z// Website of the United Artists Karlsruhe]\n* [http://www.artports.com/kuenstler/kuenstler-detail.php?kunr=559&name=Wetterauer&vorname=Herbert/ International Index of Artists]\n* [http://300jahre300koepfe.de/2014-08-31/herbert-wetterauer-kuenstler-und-autor-ganzes-interview/ Interview with Herbert Wetterauer (German language)]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Wetterauer, Herbert}}\n[[Category:1957 births]]\n[[Category:People from Karlsruhe]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:20th-century German painters]]\n[[Category:German male painters]]\n[[Category:21st-century German painters]]\n[[Category:21st-century German novelists]]\n[[Category:20th-century German sculptors]]\n[[Category:German male sculptors]]\n[[Category:21st-century German sculptors]]\n[[Category:German male novelists]]\n[[Category:21st-century German male writers]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2019}}\n[[File:Martin Heidegger for WP.jpg|thumb|upright|Brush drawing by Herbert Wetterauer (Portrait of [[Martin Heidegger]], 2010)]]\n'''Herbert Wetterauer''' (born 21 April 1957 in [[Karlsruhe]], [[West Germany]]) is a German painter, sculptor and author. He is known for his paintings in ink and life-sized figures made of [[paperboard]], for which he developed his own technique.\n\nWetterauer studied German Language at the [[University of Karlsruhe]] and [[Fine Arts]] at the [[State Academy of Fine Arts Karlsruhe]]. For many years he was busy as a journalist, writing primary [[art critic]]s.\n\nIn 2009 his first novel named ''Stromness'' appeared,<ref>[http://www.schardtverlag.de/wetterauer-herbert-344.html The novel ''Stromness'' at Schardt Verlag]</ref> followed by the novels ''Du sollst nicht vertrauen''<ref>[https://www.amazon.co.uk/sollst-nicht-vertrauen-German-ebook/dp/B00BHERWDQ/ref=sr_1_1?s=books&ie=UTF8&qid=1361435208&sr=1-1 The novel ''Du sollst nicht vertrauen'' at Amazon UK]</ref> and ''tod.com''.<ref>[http://www.infoverlag.de/produkt.html/tod-com The novel ''tod.com'' at Info Verlag]</ref>\n\n==Exhibitions (selection)==\n* 2011: Presentation by the United Artists of Karlsruhe\n* 2008: One-Man-Show at the official art-shop-window (Kunstschaufenster ) of the City of Karlsruhe\n* 2001: K\u00fcnstlerhaus-Gallery Karlsruhe\n* 1995: Art-Collection Westermann, City-Gallery of [[Rastatt]]\n* 1993: First [[wikt:biennale|Biennale]] for Material- and Textile-Art, [[Bayreuth]] and [[Manchester]]\n* 1990: First prize in the poster-competition, 4th [