{"title_page": "Helmut Krausser", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2013}}\n{{BLP primary sources|date=October 2007}}\n'''Helmut Krausser'''<!--sic!--> (11 July 1964) is a German author, poet, playwright, composer and professional chess player who was born in [[Esslingen (district)|Esslingen]].\n\n==Biography==\nKrausser lives in [[Munich]] and [[Berlin]].<ref>{{cite web|URL=http://archive.new-books-in-german.com/english/1185/354/354/129002/design1.html|title=Helmut Krausser (Not Such Bad People)|work=archive.new-books-in-German.com|accessdate=24 June 2017}}</ref> He married Beatrice Renauer in 1991.\n\nIn 1993 he received the [[Toucan Prize]].\n\nAfter a few smaller novels his literary breakthrough arrived with ''Melodien oder Nachtr\u00e4ge zum quecksilbernen Zeitalter''. Since then, many of his books have been translated into multiple languages and plays of his have been performed all over the world.\n\nKrausser also composes classical music.\n\n==Works==\n\n===Novels, short stories and poems===\n* ''K\u00f6nige \u00fcber dem Ozean.'' Munich: Knaus, 1989\n* ''Spielgeld.'' Munich: Kirchheim, 1990\n* ''Fette Welt.'' Munich: List, 1992\n* ''Tageb\u00fccher Mai 1992 \u2013 April 2004.'' Munich: Belleville, 1992\u20132004, each year one month\n* ''Melodien oder Nachtr\u00e4ge zum quecksilbernen Zeitalter.'' Munich: List, 1993\n* ''Die Zerst\u00f6rung der europ\u00e4ischen St\u00e4dte.'' Munich: List, 1994\n* ''Thanatos.'' Munich: [[Luchterhand Literaturverlag|Luchterhand]], 1996\n* ''Der gro\u00dfe Bagarozy.'' Reinbek near [[Hamburg]]: Rowohlt, 1997\n** English: ''The Great Bagarozy'' Dedalus, 1998, transl. by [[Mike Mitchell (translator)|Mike Mitchell]]\n* ''Schweine und Elefanten.'' Reinbek near Hamburg: Rowohlt, 1999\n* ''Das Kaninchen, das den J\u00e4ger erschoss \u2013 und andere bizarre Todesf\u00e4lle.'' Reinbek near Hamburg: Rowohlt, 1999\n* ''Gedichte 79\u201399.'' Munich: Belleville, 1999\n* ''Schmerznovelle.'' Reinbek near Hamburg: Rowohlt, 2001\n* ''Wenn Gwendolin nachts schlafen ging.'' Munich: Kunstmann, 2002\n* ''UC (Ultrachronos).'' Reinbek near Hamburg: Rowohlt, 2003\n* ''Strom, Gedichte 99-03.'' Reinbek near Hamburg: Rowohlt, 2003\n* ''Die wilden Hunde von Pompeii.'' Reinbek near Hamburg: Rowohlt, September 2004\n* \"Eros.\" DuMont 2006\n* \"Plasma\" Gedichte DuMont 2007\n* \"Die kleinen G\u00e4rten des Maestro Puccini\"  DuMont 2008\n* ''Einsamkeit und Sex und Mitleid.''Dumont, August 2009\n* \"Zwei ungleiche Rivalen \u2013 Puccini und Franchetti\"  Bertelsmann 2010\n* ''Die letzten sch\u00f6nen Tage'' Dumont, Februar 2011<ref>{{cite web|URL=http://helmut-krausser.de|title=HELMUT KRAUSSER - Werkverzeichnis|work=helmut-krausser.de|accessdate=24 June 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Plays===\n* ''St\u00fccke 93-03.'' [[Frankfurt am Main]]: Fischer, 2003, includes:\n** ''Lederfresse''\n*** English: ''Leatherface'' Fischer, 1996, transl. by [[Tony Meech]]\n** ''Haltestelle Geister''\n** ''Denotation Babel''\n\n===Other===\nKrausser wrote several contributions and [[essay|article]]s in numerous newspapers and magazines. Furthermore, [[Gramophone record|records]] and [[radio play]]s of him were released. Two movies have been made from his novels to date (2004).\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{imdb name|0470334}}\n*[http://www.necessaryprose.com/bagarozy.htm Review of the English translation of The Great Bagarozy]\n*[http://www.rowohlt.de/autor/1499  bibliography all published works at rowohlt]\n*[http://www.hagestedt.de/portrait/d2Krausser.html Lutz Hagestedt: Helmut Krausser]\n*[http://www.freundefranchettis.com   page also in English. Krausser is very engaged in making the works of the forgotten (and forbidden) Jewish composer Alberto Franchetti popular again.]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Krausser, Helmut}}\n[[Category:1964 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Esslingen am Neckar]]\n[[Category:20th-century German novelists]]\n[[Category:21st-century German novelists]]\n[[Category:German poets]]\n[[Category:German male poets]]\n[[Category:German male novelists]]\n[[Category:German male dramatists and playwrights]]\n[[Category:20th-century German dramatists and playwrights]]\n[[Category:21st-century German dramatists and playwrights]]\n[[Category:German-language poets]]\n[[Category:20th-century German male writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century German male writers]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2013}}\n{{BLP primary sources|date=October 2007}}\n'''Helmut Krausser'''<!--sic!--> (11 July 1964) is a German author, poet, playwright, composer and professional chess player who was born in [[Esslingen (district)|Esslingen]].\n\n==Biography==\nKrausser lives in [[Munich]] and [[Berlin]].<ref>{{cite web|URL=http://archive.new-books-in-german.com/english/1185/354/354/129002/design1.html|title=Helmut Krausser (Not Such Bad People)|work=archive.new-books-in-German.com|accessdate=24 June 2017}}</ref> He married Beatrice Renauer in 1991.\n\nIn 1993 he received the [[Toucan Prize]].\n\nAfter a few smaller novels his literary breakthrough arrived with ''Melodien oder Nachtr\u00e4ge zum quecksilbernen Zeitalter''. Since then, many of his books have been translated into multiple languages and plays of his have been performed all over the world.\n\nKrausser also composes classical music.\n\n==Works==\n\n===Novels, short stories and poems===\n* ''K\u00f6nige \u00fcber dem Ozean.'' Munich: Knaus, 1989\n* ''Spielgeld.'' Munich: Kirchheim, 1990\n* ''Fette Welt.'' Munich: List, 1992\n* ''Tageb\u00fccher Mai 1992 \u2013 April 2004.'' Munich: Belleville, 1992\u20132004, each year one month\n* ''Melodien oder Nachtr\u00e4ge zum quecksilbernen Zeitalter.'' Munich: List, 1993\n* ''Die Zerst\u00f6rung der europ\u00e4ischen St\u00e4dte.'' Munich: List, 1994\n* ''Thanatos.'' Munich: [[Luchterhand Literaturverlag|Luchterhand]], 1996\n* ''Der gro\u00dfe Bagarozy.'' Reinbek near [[Hamburg]]: Rowohlt, 1997\n** English: ''The Great Bagarozy'' Dedalus, 1998, transl. by [[Mike Mitchell (translator)|Mike Mitchell]]\n* ''Schweine und Elefanten.'' Reinbek near Hamburg: Rowohlt, 1999\n* ''Das Kaninchen, das den J\u00e4ger erschoss \u2013 und andere bizarre Todesf\u00e4lle.'' Reinbek near Hamburg: Rowohlt, 1999\n* ''Gedichte 79\u201399.'' Munich: Belleville, 1999\n* ''Schmerznovelle.'' Reinbek near Hamburg: Rowohlt, 2001\n* ''Wenn Gwendolin nachts schlafen ging.'' Munich: Kunstmann, 2002\n* ''UC (Ultrachronos).'' Reinbek near Hamburg: Rowohlt, 2003\n* ''Strom, Gedichte 99-03.'' Reinbek near Hamburg: Rowohlt, 2003\n* ''Die wilden Hunde von Pompeii.'' Reinbek near Hamburg: Rowohlt, September 2004\n* \"Eros.\" DuMont 2006\n* \"Plasma\" Gedichte DuMont 2007\n* \"Die kleinen G\u00e4rten des Maestro Puccini\"  DuMont 2008\n* ''Einsamkeit und Sex und Mitleid.''Dumont, August 2009\n* \"Zwei ungleiche Rivalen \u2013 Puccini und Franchetti\"  Bertelsmann 2010\n* ''Die letzten sch\u00f6nen Tage'' Dumont, Februar 2011<ref>{{cite web|URL=http://helmut-krausser.de|title=HELMUT KRAUSSER - Werkverzeichnis|work=helmut-krausser.de|accessdate=24 June 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Plays===\n* ''St\u00fccke 93-03.'' [[Frankfurt am Main]]: Fischer, 2003, includes:\n** ''Lederfresse''\n*** English: ''Leatherface'' Fischer, 1996, transl. by [[Tony Meech]]\n** ''Haltestelle Geister''\n** ''Denotation Babel''\n\n===Other===\nKrausser wrote several contributions and [[essay|article]]s in numerous newspapers and magazines. Furthermore, [[Gramophone record|records]] and [[radio play]]s of him were released. Two movies have been made from his novels to date (2004).\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{imdb name|0470334}}\n*[http://www.necessaryprose.com/bagarozy.htm Review of the English translation of The Great Bagarozy]\n*[http://www.rowohlt.de/autor/1499  bibliography all published works at rowohlt]\n*[http://www.hagestedt.de/portrait/d2Krausser.html Lutz Hagestedt: Helmut Krausser]\n*[http://www.freundefranchettis.com   page also in English. Krausser is very engaged in making the works of the forgotten (and forbidden) Jewish composer Alberto Franchetti popular again.]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Krausser, Helmut}}\n[[Category:1964 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Esslingen am Neckar]]\n[[Category:20th-century German novelists]]\n[[Category:21st-century German novelists]]\n[[Category:German poets]]\n[[Category:German male poets]]\n[[Category:German male novelists]]\n[[Category:German male dramatists and playwrights]]\n[[Category:20th-century German dramatists and playwrights]]\n[[Category:21st-century German dramatists and playwrights]]\n[[Category:German-language poets]]\n[[Category:20th-century German male writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century male writers]]\n", "name_user": "Bearcat", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links:recat", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Helmut_Krausser"}
{"title_page": "Helmut Kohlenberger", "text_new": "'''Helmut Kohlenberger''' (born 1942 in [[V\u00edtkov (Opava District)|Wigstadtl]], [[Reichsgau Sudetenland]] , (now [[Czech Silesia]], [[Czech Republic]]) ) is a German philosopher, translator, editor and university lecturer at both the Universities of Vienna and Salzburg. He is the author of several works, including ''The European idea and Culture'', ''Theoretical issues of the Middle Ages'' and ''Modernism''.<ref name=\"WAIS\">[https://waisworld.org/go.jsp?id=02a&o=17847   World Association of International Studies - Profile of Helmut Kohlenberger]</ref>\n\n==Biography==\nKohlenberger was born in [[V\u00edtkov (Opava District)|Wigstadtl]], in the [[Reichsgau Sudetenland]] of [[Nazi Germany]] in 1942 but was schooled in postwar [[West Germany]].  He studied the history of philosophy in the German 19th-century tradition, [[Kant]] and [[Hegel]], at the [[University of T\u00fcbingen]]. He also worked with [[de./Friedrich Tenbruck|Friedrich Tenbruck]] on sociological questions in the [[Max Weber]] tradition.\n\nKohlenberger continued Medieval studies at the [[University of Bochum]] and then worked in the field of [[medieval philosophy]], the development of universities and the collapse of the Christian values in modern society.<ref name=\"WAIS\"/>\n\nHe joined [[Raymond Klibansky]] on the Oxford committee for Medieval studies and spent thirty years working on the [[UNESCO]] sponsored ''International Bibliography of Philosophy''.<ref name=\"WAIS\"/>\n\nHe was associated with [[Jan Patocka]] and the [[Charta 77]] movement in Prague in the 1960s and '70s.\n\nHe was an employee of the magazine ''Tumult'' which covered Transport Economics of Vienna & Munich.<ref name=\"WAIS\"/><ref>[[:de:Tumult (Zeitschrift)]]</ref>\n\nHe taught the [[History of Ideas]] at the [[University of Vienna]] from 1973-1987, plus working for Austrian Radio. Since the late 1980s he has taught at the [[University of Salzburg]] plus lecturing abroad, translating and participating on editorial boards. He translated texts by [[Andr\u00e9 Glucksmann]] from French into German, and was an editor of the magazine ''Stredni Europe'' (''Central Europe'').<ref name=\"WAIS\"/>\n\n==Publications==\n* ''Similitudo und Ratio'' (1972)\n* ''Die Wahrheit des Ganzen'' (1976)\n* ''Von der Notwendigkeit der Philosophie in der Gegenwart: Festschrift f\u00fcr Karl Ulmer zum 60.''(1976)\n* ''Cuando el jego va en serio'' (1991)\n* ''Gesellschaftstheorien in \u00d6sterreich'' (with R. Knoll, 1994)\n* ''Briefe \u00fcber Deutschland'' (1996)\n* ''25 Years (1969-1994) of Anselm Studies'' (Editor, 1996)\n* Reason, Action, and Experience: Essays in Honor of Raymond Klibansky, (Editor, 1998)\n* ''Von der Romantik zur \u00e4sthetischen Religion'' (Contributor, 2004)\n* ''Rechtsphilosophie : Vom Grundlagenfach zur Transdisziplinarit\u00e4t in den Rechts-, Wirtschafts- und Sozialwissenschaften. '' (Contributor 2010)\n* ''How the West was Won: Essays on the Literary Imagination, the Canon,'' (Contributor, The Monastic Challenge, 2010)\n* ''Proze\u00df, Spiel: Fragmente zum 2. Jahrtausend'' (with Willi Donner, 2013)\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Kohlenberger, Helmut}}\n[[Category:1942 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from V\u00edtkov]]\n[[Category:People from Sudetenland]]\n[[Category:Sudeten German people]]\n[[Category:German essayists]]\n[[Category:German philosophers]]\n[[Category:20th-century German writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century German writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century German male writers]]\n[[Category:20th-century essayists]]\n[[Category:21st-century essayists]]\n[[Category:20th-century German male writers]]\n[[Category:University of T\u00fcbingen alumni]]\n[[Category:German male non-fiction writers]]\n", "text_old": "'''Helmut Kohlenberger''' (born 1942 in [[V\u00edtkov (Opava District)|Wigstadtl]], [[Reichsgau Sudetenland]] , (now [[Czech Silesia]], [[Czech Republic]]) ) is a German philosopher, translator, editor and university lecturer at both the Universities of Vienna and Salzburg. He is the author of several works, including ''The European idea and Culture'', ''Theoretical issues of the Middle Ages'' and ''Modernism''.<ref name=\"WAIS\">[https://waisworld.org/go.jsp?id=02a&o=17847   World Association of International Studies - Profile of Helmut Kohlenberger]</ref>\n\n==Biography==\nKohlenberger was born in [[V\u00edtkov (Opava District)|Wigstadtl]], in the [[Reichsgau Sudetenland]] of [[Nazi Germany]] in 1942 but was schooled in postwar [[West Germany]].  He studied the history of philosophy in the German 19th-century tradition, [[Kant]] and [[Hegel]], at the [[University of T\u00fcbingen]]. He also worked with [[de./Friedrich Tenbruck|Friedrich Tenbruck]] on sociological questions in the [[Max Weber]] tradition.\n\nKohlenberger continued Medieval studies at the [[University of Bochum]] and then worked in the field of [[medieval philosophy]], the development of universities and the collapse of the Christian values in modern society.<ref name=\"WAIS\"/>\n\nHe joined [[Raymond Klibansky]] on the Oxford committee for Medieval studies and spent thirty years working on the [[UNESCO]] sponsored ''International Bibliography of Philosophy''.<ref name=\"WAIS\"/>\n\nHe was associated with [[Jan Patocka]] and the [[Charta 77]] movement in Prague in the 1960s and '70s.\n\nHe was an employee of the magazine ''Tumult'' which covered Transport Economics of Vienna & Munich.<ref name=\"WAIS\"/><ref>[[:de:Tumult (Zeitschrift)]]</ref>\n\nHe taught the [[History of Ideas]] at the [[University of Vienna]] from 1973-1987, plus working for Austrian Radio. Since the late 1980s he has taught at the [[University of Salzburg]] plus lecturing abroad, translating and participating on editorial boards. He translated texts by [[Andr\u00e9 Glucksmann]] from French into German, and was an editor of the magazine ''Stredni Europe'' (''Central Europe'').<ref name=\"WAIS\"/>\n\n==Publications==\n* ''Similitudo und Ratio'' (1972)\n* ''Die Wahrheit des Ganzen'' (1976)\n* ''Von der Notwendigkeit der Philosophie in der Gegenwart: Festschrift f\u00fcr Karl Ulmer zum 60.''(1976)\n* ''Cuando el jego va en serio'' (1991)\n* ''Gesellschaftstheorien in \u00d6sterreich'' (with R. Knoll, 1994)\n* ''Briefe \u00fcber Deutschland'' (1996)\n* ''25 Years (1969-1994) of Anselm Studies'' (Editor, 1996)\n* Reason, Action, and Experience: Essays in Honor of Raymond Klibansky, (Editor, 1998)\n* ''Von der Romantik zur \u00e4sthetischen Religion'' (Contributor, 2004)\n* ''Rechtsphilosophie : Vom Grundlagenfach zur Transdisziplinarit\u00e4t in den Rechts-, Wirtschafts- und Sozialwissenschaften. '' (Contributor 2010)\n* ''How the West was Won: Essays on the Literary Imagination, the Canon,'' (Contributor, The Monastic Challenge, 2010)\n* ''Proze\u00df, Spiel: Fragmente zum 2. Jahrtausend'' (with Willi Donner, 2013)\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Kohlenberger, Helmut}}\n[[Category:1942 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from V\u00edtkov]]\n[[Category:People from Sudetenland]]\n[[Category:Sudeten German people]]\n[[Category:German essayists]]\n[[Category:German philosophers]]\n[[Category:20th-century German writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century German writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century male writers]]\n[[Category:20th-century essayists]]\n[[Category:21st-century essayists]]\n[[Category:20th-century German male writers]]\n[[Category:University of T\u00fcbingen alumni]]\n[[Category:German male non-fiction writers]]\n", "name_user": "Bearcat", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eReferences:recat", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Helmut_Kohlenberger"}
{"title_page": "Hellmuth Karasek", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n|name        = Hellmuth Karasek\n|image       = Hellmuth Karasek 3821-2.jpg\n|image_size  = \n|caption     = in 2011\n|birth_name  = \n|birth_date  = 4 January 1934\n|birth_place = [[Brno]], [[Czechoslovakia]]<br />(now [[Czech Republic]])\n|death_date  = {{death date and age|2015|9|29|1934|1|4|df=yes}}\n|death_place = [[Hamburg]], Germany\n|occupation  = [[Journalist]], [[author]]\n|children    = 4<ref>{{cite news |last=Rosendorff |first=Kathrin |date=22 July 2019 |title=Laura Karasek - Pippi Langstrumpf und Hildegard Knef in einer Person |url=https://www.fr.de/panorama/leute/laura-karasek-pippi-langstrumpf-hildegard-knef-einer-person-zr-12844080.html |work=[[Frankfurter Rundschau]] |location=Frankfurt |language=de |access-date=8 March 2020}}</ref>\n|yearsactive = 1965\u20132015\n}}\n[[File:Hellmuth Karasek.jpg|thumb|Hellmuth Karasek (left) and Jens Rusch in 2006]]\n\n'''Hellmuth Karasek''' (4 January 1934 \u2013 29 September 2015) was a [[German people|German]] journalist, literary critic, novelist and the author of many books on literature and film. He was one of Germany's best-known [[feuilleton]]ists.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.zeit.de/kultur/literatur/2015-09/hellmuth-karasek-tot-nachruf|title=Hellmuth Karasek: Der gro\u00dfe Schw\u00e4rmer|first=David|last=Hugendick|date=30 September 2015|newspaper=[[Die Zeit]]|location=Hamburg|language=de|accessdate=8 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Life ==\nKarasek was born in the capital city of [[Moravia]], [[Brno]] ({{lang-de|Br\u00fcnn}}), which was then a part of [[Czechoslovakia]] (nowadays of the Czech Republic). Karasek attended the [[National Political Institutes of Education]] in [[Lubliniec|Loben]].<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.spiegel.de/geschichte/napolas-im-dritten-reich-hitlers-brutale-kaderschmieden-a-951094.html |title=Napolas im \"Dritten Reich\": Hitlers brutale Kaderschmieden - DER SPIEGEL - Geschichte |first=Thomas |last=Fritz |date=5 April 2013 |newspaper=[[Der Spiegel]] |location=Hamburg |language=de |accessdate=8 March 2020}}</ref> In 1944, when he was ten, his family [[Flight and expulsion of Germans from Poland during and after World War II|fled]] from [[Bielsko|Bielitz]] (today Bielsko in Poland) in the neighbouring German region of [[Silesia]] to [[Bernburg]] in [[Saxony-Anhalt]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.perlentaucher.de/buch/hellmuth-karasek/auf-der-flucht.html|title=Hellmuth Karasek: Auf der Flucht. Erinnerungen|website=www.perlentaucher.de}}</ref> After finishing his schooling in the early 1950s he moved from there&mdash;then part of [[East Germany]]&mdash;to [[West Germany]] and became a student at the [[University of T\u00fcbingen]], where he studied History, German and English language and literature.<ref name=\"Obituary Spiegel\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.spiegel.de/kultur/literatur/hellmuth-karasek-ist-tot-literaturkritiker-und-schriftsteller-gestorben-a-1055369.html|title=Hellmuth Karasek ist tot: Literaturkritiker und Schriftsteller gestorben - DER SPIEGEL - Kultur |date=30 September 2015 |newspaper=[[Der Spiegel]] |location=Hamburg |language=de |accessdate=8 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nAfter his graduation Karasek started working as a journalist, and in 1968 became the theatre critic of the weekly newspaper ''[[Die Zeit]]''. From 1974 until 1996 he wrote for the news magazine ''[[Der Spiegel]]'', where he worked as the chief editor of the feuilleton.<ref>{{cite news |last=Matussek |first=Matthias |date=30 September 2015 |title=Entschuldige mein Gestammel. Ich vermisse dich |url=https://www.welt.de/kultur/article147029168/Entschuldige-mein-Gestammel-Ich-vermisse-dich.html |work=[[Die Welt]] |location=Berlin |language=de |access-date=8 March 2020}}</ref> After his retirement from ''The Spiegel'' he wrote a novel named ''Das Magazin'' in which he criticised ''Der Spiegel''. He also worked in later years for newspapers like ''[[Die Welt]]'', ''[[Bild]]'', ''[[Berliner Morgenpost]]'' and ''[[Der Tagesspiegel]]''. He also wrote more than 20 books about his own life or literature and film, including monographs about [[Max Frisch]], [[Bertolt Brecht]] and his close friend [[Billy Wilder]]. Other projects included three plays under the nom de plume Daniel Doppler and a translation of [[Raymond Chandler]]'s [[The Lady in the Lake]]. In 1999, he was a member of the jury at the [[49th Berlin International Film Festival]].<ref name=\"Berlinale\">{{cite web |url=http://www.berlinale.de/en/archiv/jahresarchive/1999/04_jury_1999/04_Jury_1999.html |title=Berlinale: 1999 Juries |accessdate=28 January 2012 |work=berlinale.de}}</ref>\n\nKarasek was best known as one of the permanent members of the TV-literature review show ''{{ill|Das Literarische Quartett|de}}'', together with literary critic [[Marcel Reich-Ranicki]], between 1988 and 2001.<ref name=\"Obituary Spiegel\" /><ref>{{cite news |last=Lovenberg |first=Felicitas von |date=30 September 2015 |title=Der \u00fcbersch\u00e4umende Ausgleicher |url=https://www.faz.net/aktuell/feuilleton/buecher/themen/zum-tod-von-hellmuth-karasek-13831715.html |work=[[Frankfurter Allgemeine Zeitung]] |location=Frankfurt |language=de |access-date=8 March 2020}}</ref> He also frequently appeared on other German [[television]] shows, for example in [[quiz show]]s like ''Die 5-Millionen-SKL-Show''.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.ndr.de/kultur/buch/Hellmuth-Karasek-mehr-Liebhaber-als-Papst,karasek168.html |last=Weise |first=Katja |date=9 October 2015 |title=Hellmuth Karasek - mehr Liebhaber als Papst |language=de |website=www.ndr.de}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last= |first= |date=7 September 2014 |title=Hellmuth Karasek \"will nicht als Volldepp enden\" |url=https://www.abendzeitung-muenchen.de/inhalt.keine-quizshow-auftritte-mehr-hellmuth-karasek-will-nicht-als-volldepp-enden.0e8ecf67-bd49-49f5-96fe-c55b30d4fe25.html |work=[[Abendzeitung]] |location=Munich |language=de |access-date=8 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Awards==\n* 1973/74 [[Theodor Wolff Prize]]<ref>{{cite web |last= |first= |date=2020 |title=Preistr\u00e4ger der Jahre 1977 \u2013 1962 |url=https://www.bdzv.de/twp/preistraeger-preisverleihung/preisverleihung-weitere-jahre/preisverleihung-weitere-jahre0/preisverleihung-1962-1997/ |work=bdzv.de |location=Berlin |publisher=Theodor Wolff-Preis,  Kuratorium f\u00fcr den Journalistenpreis der deutschen Zeitungen |access-date=8 March 2020}}</ref>\n* 1991 [[Bavarian TV Awards]]<ref>{{cite web |last= |first= |date=16 January 2017 |title=Preistr\u00e4ger des Bayerischen Fernsehpreises 1989\u20132016 |url=https://www.stmwi.bayern.de/fileadmin/user_upload/stmwi/Themen/Wettbewerbe/Medienpreise/2017-01-16_Bayerische_Fernsehpreistraeger-1989-2016__2017-01_.pdf |work=stmwi.bayern.de |location=Munich |publisher=Bayerisches Staatsministerium f\u00fcr Wirtschaft und Medien, Energie und Technologie |access-date=7 March 2020}}</ref>\n* 1994 Commander's Cross of the [[Order of Merit of the Federal Republic of Germany]].<ref name=\"Obituary Spiegel\" />\n\n==Bibliography==\n*''[[Carl Sternheim]]'' (1965)\n*''[[Max Frisch]]'' (1966)\n*''Deutschland, deine Dichter'' (1970)\n*''[[Bertolt Brecht|Brecht]], der j\u00fcngste Fall eines Klassikers'' (1978)\n*''[[Billy Wilder]]'' (1992)\n*''Mein Kino'' (a personal list of the 100 best movies ever) (1994)\n*''Go West!'' (about the 1950s) (1996)\n*''Hand in Handy'' (about the [[mobile phone]] craze) (1997)\n*''Das Magazin'' (novel, 1998)\n*''Betrug'' (novel, 2001)\n*''Karambolagen. Begegnungen mit Zeitgenossen'' (2002)\n*''Auf der Flucht'' ([[memoir]], 2004)\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n*{{DNB portal|119370107}}\n*{{IMDb name|0438964}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Karasek, Hellmuth}}\n[[Category:1934 births]]\n[[Category:2015 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Brno]]\n[[Category:20th-century German novelists]]\n[[Category:21st-century German novelists]]\n[[Category:Czechoslovak people of German descent]]\n[[Category:German male novelists]]\n[[Category:German journalists]]\n[[Category:German male journalists]]\n[[Category:Moravian-German people]]\n[[Category:Naturalized citizens of Germany]]\n[[Category:University of T\u00fcbingen alumni]]\n[[Category:20th-century German male writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century German male writers]]\n[[Category:Der Spiegel people]]\n[[Category:ZDF people]]\n[[Category:Die Welt people]]\n[[Category:Bild people]]\n[[Category:Commanders Crosses of the Order of Merit of the Federal Republic of Germany]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox person\n|name        = Hellmuth Karasek\n|image       = Hellmuth Karasek 3821-2.jpg\n|image_size  = \n|caption     = in 2011\n|birth_name  = \n|birth_date  = 4 January 1934\n|birth_place = [[Brno]], [[Czechoslovakia]]<br />(now [[Czech Republic]])\n|death_date  = {{death date and age|2015|9|29|1934|1|4|df=yes}}\n|death_place = [[Hamburg]], Germany\n|occupation  = [[Journalist]], [[author]]\n|children    = 4<ref>{{cite news |last=Rosendorff |first=Kathrin |date=22 July 2019 |title=Laura Karasek - Pippi Langstrumpf und Hildegard Knef in einer Person |url=https://www.fr.de/panorama/leute/laura-karasek-pippi-langstrumpf-hildegard-knef-einer-person-zr-12844080.html |work=[[Frankfurter Rundschau]] |location=Frankfurt |language=de |access-date=8 March 2020}}</ref>\n|yearsactive = 1965\u20132015\n}}\n[[File:Hellmuth Karasek.jpg|thumb|Hellmuth Karasek (left) and Jens Rusch in 2006]]\n\n'''Hellmuth Karasek''' (4 January 1934 \u2013 29 September 2015) was a [[German people|German]] journalist, literary critic, novelist and the author of many books on literature and film. He was one of Germany's best-known [[feuilleton]]ists.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.zeit.de/kultur/literatur/2015-09/hellmuth-karasek-tot-nachruf|title=Hellmuth Karasek: Der gro\u00dfe Schw\u00e4rmer|first=David|last=Hugendick|date=30 September 2015|newspaper=[[Die Zeit]]|location=Hamburg|language=de|accessdate=8 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Life ==\nKarasek was born in the capital city of [[Moravia]], [[Brno]] ({{lang-de|Br\u00fcnn}}), which was then a part of [[Czechoslovakia]] (nowadays of the Czech Republic). Karasek attended the [[National Political Institutes of Education]] in [[Lubliniec|Loben]].<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.spiegel.de/geschichte/napolas-im-dritten-reich-hitlers-brutale-kaderschmieden-a-951094.html |title=Napolas im \"Dritten Reich\": Hitlers brutale Kaderschmieden - DER SPIEGEL - Geschichte |first=Thomas |last=Fritz |date=5 April 2013 |newspaper=[[Der Spiegel]] |location=Hamburg |language=de |accessdate=8 March 2020}}</ref> In 1944, when he was ten, his family [[Flight and expulsion of Germans from Poland during and after World War II|fled]] from [[Bielsko|Bielitz]] (today Bielsko in Poland) in the neighbouring German region of [[Silesia]] to [[Bernburg]] in [[Saxony-Anhalt]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.perlentaucher.de/buch/hellmuth-karasek/auf-der-flucht.html|title=Hellmuth Karasek: Auf der Flucht. Erinnerungen|website=www.perlentaucher.de}}</ref> After finishing his schooling in the early 1950s he moved from there&mdash;then part of [[East Germany]]&mdash;to [[West Germany]] and became a student at the [[University of T\u00fcbingen]], where he studied History, German and English language and literature.<ref name=\"Obituary Spiegel\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.spiegel.de/kultur/literatur/hellmuth-karasek-ist-tot-literaturkritiker-und-schriftsteller-gestorben-a-1055369.html|title=Hellmuth Karasek ist tot: Literaturkritiker und Schriftsteller gestorben - DER SPIEGEL - Kultur |date=30 September 2015 |newspaper=[[Der Spiegel]] |location=Hamburg |language=de |accessdate=8 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nAfter his graduation Karasek started working as a journalist, and in 1968 became the theatre critic of the weekly newspaper ''[[Die Zeit]]''. From 1974 until 1996 he wrote for the news magazine ''[[Der Spiegel]]'', where he worked as the chief editor of the feuilleton.<ref>{{cite news |last=Matussek |first=Matthias |date=30 September 2015 |title=Entschuldige mein Gestammel. Ich vermisse dich |url=https://www.welt.de/kultur/article147029168/Entschuldige-mein-Gestammel-Ich-vermisse-dich.html |work=[[Die Welt]] |location=Berlin |language=de |access-date=8 March 2020}}</ref> After his retirement from ''The Spiegel'' he wrote a novel named ''Das Magazin'' in which he criticised ''Der Spiegel''. He also worked in later years for newspapers like ''[[Die Welt]]'', ''[[Bild]]'', ''[[Berliner Morgenpost]]'' and ''[[Der Tagesspiegel]]''. He also wrote more than 20 books about his own life or literature and film, including monographs about [[Max Frisch]], [[Bertolt Brecht]] and his close friend [[Billy Wilder]]. Other projects included three plays under the nom de plume Daniel Doppler and a translation of [[Raymond Chandler]]'s [[The Lady in the Lake]]. In 1999, he was a member of the jury at the [[49th Berlin International Film Festival]].<ref name=\"Berlinale\">{{cite web |url=http://www.berlinale.de/en/archiv/jahresarchive/1999/04_jury_1999/04_Jury_1999.html |title=Berlinale: 1999 Juries |accessdate=28 January 2012 |work=berlinale.de}}</ref>\n\nKarasek was best known as one of the permanent members of the TV-literature review show ''{{ill|Das Literarische Quartett|de}}'', together with literary critic [[Marcel Reich-Ranicki]], between 1988 and 2001.<ref name=\"Obituary Spiegel\" /><ref>{{cite news |last=Lovenberg |first=Felicitas von |date=30 September 2015 |title=Der \u00fcbersch\u00e4umende Ausgleicher |url=https://www.faz.net/aktuell/feuilleton/buecher/themen/zum-tod-von-hellmuth-karasek-13831715.html |work=[[Frankfurter Allgemeine Zeitung]] |location=Frankfurt |language=de |access-date=8 March 2020}}</ref> He also frequently appeared on other German [[television]] shows, for example in [[quiz show]]s like ''Die 5-Millionen-SKL-Show''.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.ndr.de/kultur/buch/Hellmuth-Karasek-mehr-Liebhaber-als-Papst,karasek168.html |last=Weise |first=Katja |date=9 October 2015 |title=Hellmuth Karasek - mehr Liebhaber als Papst |language=de |website=www.ndr.de}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last= |first= |date=7 September 2014 |title=Hellmuth Karasek \"will nicht als Volldepp enden\" |url=https://www.abendzeitung-muenchen.de/inhalt.keine-quizshow-auftritte-mehr-hellmuth-karasek-will-nicht-als-volldepp-enden.0e8ecf67-bd49-49f5-96fe-c55b30d4fe25.html |work=[[Abendzeitung]] |location=Munich |language=de |access-date=8 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Awards==\n* 1973/74 [[Theodor Wolff Prize]]<ref>{{cite web |last= |first= |date=2020 |title=Preistr\u00e4ger der Jahre 1977 \u2013 1962 |url=https://www.bdzv.de/twp/preistraeger-preisverleihung/preisverleihung-weitere-jahre/preisverleihung-weitere-jahre0/preisverleihung-1962-1997/ |work=bdzv.de |location=Berlin |publisher=Theodor Wolff-Preis,  Kuratorium f\u00fcr den Journalistenpreis der deutschen Zeitungen |access-date=8 March 2020}}</ref>\n* 1991 [[Bavarian TV Awards]]<ref>{{cite web |last= |first= |date=16 January 2017 |title=Preistr\u00e4ger des Bayerischen Fernsehpreises 1989\u20132016 |url=https://www.stmwi.bayern.de/fileadmin/user_upload/stmwi/Themen/Wettbewerbe/Medienpreise/2017-01-16_Bayerische_Fernsehpreistraeger-1989-2016__2017-01_.pdf |work=stmwi.bayern.de |location=Munich |publisher=Bayerisches Staatsministerium f\u00fcr Wirtschaft und Medien, Energie und Technologie |access-date=7 March 2020}}</ref>\n* 1994 Commander's Cross of the [[Order of Merit of the Federal Republic of Germany]].<ref name=\"Obituary Spiegel\" />\n\n==Bibliography==\n*''[[Carl Sternheim]]'' (1965)\n*''[[Max Frisch]]'' (1966)\n*''Deutschland, deine Dichter'' (1970)\n*''[[Bertolt Brecht|Brecht]], der j\u00fcngste Fall eines Klassikers'' (1978)\n*''[[Billy Wilder]]'' (1992)\n*''Mein Kino'' (a personal list of the 100 best movies ever) (1994)\n*''Go West!'' (about the 1950s) (1996)\n*''Hand in Handy'' (about the [[mobile phone]] craze) (1997)\n*''Das Magazin'' (novel, 1998)\n*''Betrug'' (novel, 2001)\n*''Karambolagen. Begegnungen mit Zeitgenossen'' (2002)\n*''Auf der Flucht'' ([[memoir]], 2004)\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n*{{DNB portal|119370107}}\n*{{IMDb name|0438964}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Karasek, Hellmuth}}\n[[Category:1934 births]]\n[[Category:2015 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Brno]]\n[[Category:20th-century German novelists]]\n[[Category:21st-century German novelists]]\n[[Category:Czechoslovak people of German descent]]\n[[Category:German male novelists]]\n[[Category:German journalists]]\n[[Category:German male journalists]]\n[[Category:Moravian-German people]]\n[[Category:Naturalized citizens of Germany]]\n[[Category:University of T\u00fcbingen alumni]]\n[[Category:20th-century German male writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century male writers]]\n[[Category:Der Spiegel people]]\n[[Category:ZDF people]]\n[[Category:Die Welt people]]\n[[Category:Bild people]]\n[[Category:Commanders Crosses of the Order of Merit of the Federal Republic of Germany]]\n", "name_user": "Bearcat", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links:recat", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hellmuth_Karasek"}
{"title_page": "Sunday Best (Surfaces song)", "text_new": "{{Infobox song\n| name       = Sunday Best\n| type       = single\n| artist     = Surfaces\n| album      = Where the Light Is and Horizons\n| published  = January 8, 2019\n| released   = July 11, 2019 {{small|(music video)}}<br>March 2020 {{small|(airplay)}}\n| genre      =Pop\n| length     = 2:39\n| label      = {{hlist|TenThousand Projects|[[Caroline Records|Caroline]]}}\n| writer     = {{hlist|Forrest Frank|Colin Padalecki}}\n| producer   = {{hlist|Forrest Frank|Colin Padalecki}}\n| prev_title = Shine on Top\n| prev_year  = 2018\n| next_title = Palm Trees\n| next_year  = 2019\n| misc       = {{external music video|type=single|{{YouTube|83KqwEEGw4|\"Sunday Best\"}}}}\n}}\n\"'''Sunday Best'''\" is a song by American [[electro-pop]] duo Surfaces, composed of Forrest Frank and Colin Padalecki. The song was released by TenThousand Projects and [[Caroline Records]] on the duo's second album ''Where the Light Is'' on January 8, 2019. \"Sunday Best\" is Surfaces' first single from their third album, \"''Horizons\"''  on February 28, 2020. The song's music video was released on July 11, 2019 and it shows the duo turning a boring office to a party place.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.broadwayworld.com/bwwmusic/article/Surfaces-Shares-New-Music-Video-For-SUNDAY-BEST-20190711|title=Surfaces Shares New Music Video For SUNDAY BEST|date=July 11, 2019|website=[[BroadwayWorld]]|access-date=March 15, 2020}}</ref> The song is believed to have gained popularity in late February 2020 on the online-video sharing platform [[TikTok]] for it's lyric \"Feeling good, like I should\",<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/business/branding/8551350/flighthouse-republic-records-partner-tiktok-series-certified-superfan|title=Flighthouse and Republic Records Partner on New TikTok Series 'Certified Superfan'|last=Eggertsen|first=Chris|date=February 19, 2020|website=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|url-status=live|access-date=March 15, 2020}}</ref> before it was released for radio airplay in early March 2020.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200302133607/https://www.allaccess.com/top40-mainstream/future-releases|title=Top 40/M Future Releases|date=March 3, 2020|website=[[All Access]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200302133607/https://www.allaccess.com/top40-mainstream/future-releases|archive-date=March 2, 2020|access-date=March 15, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.top-charts.com/s/sunday-best-surfaces|title=Sunday Best by Surfaces|website=Top-Charts.com|access-date=March 15, 2020}}</ref> The song peaked in the Top 40 in Australia, Canada, Norway, Ireland, New Zealand and the United Kingdom, as well as the top 100 in the United States, Switzerland, Germany and Sweden. \n\n== Live performances ==\nSurfaces made their late-night television debut when they performed the song on ''[[Late Night with Seth Meyers]]'' on March 2, 2020.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://headlineplanet.com/home/2020/03/03/surfaces-perform-on-late-night-with-seth-meyers-first-look/|title=Surfaces Perform \"Sunday Best\" On \"Late Night With Seth Meyers\"|last=Cantor|first=Brian|date=March 3, 2020|website=Headline Planet|access-date=March 15, 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Charts ==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\"| Chart (2020)\n! scope=\"col\"| Peak<br />position\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| Australia ([[ARIA Charts|ARIA]])<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ariacharts.com.au/charts/singles-chart|title=ARIA Australian Top 50 Singles|publisher=[[Australian Recording Industry Association]]|date=March 30, 2020|accessdate=March 28, 2020}}</ref>\n| 12\n|-\n{{single chart|Austria|57|artist=Surfaces|song=Sunday Best|rowheader=true|accessdate=April 2, 2020}}\n|-\n{{single chart|Flanders|28|artist=Surfaces|song=Sunday Best|rowheader=true|accessdate=March 28, 2020}}\n|-\n{{single chart|Wallonia Tip|3|artist=Surfaces|song=Sunday Bes