cht Search Results - The European Library]\n*Works by Harald Specht in [https://www.google.de/search?tbs=bks:1&q=%22Harald+Specht%22&gws_rd=cr&ei=40plWNPzNsrlwQLTi5z4DQ \"Harald Specht\" - Google Search]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Specht, Harald}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1951 births]]\n[[Category:German male novelists]]\n[[Category:20th-century German novelists]]\n[[Category:20th-century German male writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century German novelists]]\n[[Category:21st-century male writers]]\n[[Category:People from K\u00f6then]]\n[[Category:Humboldt University of Berlin alumni]]\n[[Category:Otto von Guericke University Magdeburg faculty]]\n[[Category:German chemists]]\n[[Category:German food scientists]]\n[[Category:20th-century chemists]]\n[[Category:20th-century German scientists]]\n[[Category:21st-century chemists]]\n[[Category:21st-century German scientists]]\n", "name_user": "Bearcat", "label": "safe", "comment": "recat", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Harald_Specht"}
{"title_page": "Hans Neuenfels", "text_new": "[[File:Oliver Mark - Hans Neuenfels, Berlin 2006.jpg|thumb|Hans Neuenfels, 2006, by [[Oliver Mark]]]]\n'''Hans Neuenfels''' (born 31 May 1941) is a German [[writer]], [[poet]], [[film producer]], [[librettist]], [[theatre director]] and [[opera director]].\n\n== Biography ==\nBorn in [[Krefeld]], Neuenfels studied at the [[Max Reinhardt Seminar]] in Vienna in the 1960s, and in the 1970s he quickly established himself as a leading practitioner of German [[Regietheater]]. Being invited to prominent venues, such as the [[Burgtheater]], his productions were often controversially received, but he worked at the same time with well-known actors such as [[Klaus Maria Brandauer]], [[Bernhard Minetti]] and {{Interlanguage link multi|Anne Bennent|de}}.\n\nHis opera productions have often been accompanied by heated discussions and scandals. In particular his version of ''[[Aida]]'' in 1980 for Frankfurt, conducted by [[Michael Gielen]], in which he portrayed Verdi's Ethiopian slave as a cleaning woman in a contemporary setting, or his ''[[Die Fledermaus|Fledermaus]]'' in 2001 for the [[Salzburg Festival]], which provoked angry reactions and resentment.\n\nNeuenfels has been criticised for creating extremely sexually explicit opera scenes. [[Soprano]] [[Karita Mattila]] criticised him in 2000 for a Salzburg production of [[Wolfgang Amadeus Mozart|Mozart's]] ''[[Cos\u00ec fan tutte]]'' in which huge insects and background videos, some of them erotic, distracted attention from the singers; during Fiordiligi's fiery aria \"{{Lang|it|Come scoglio|italic=no}}\", Mattila arrived onstage walking two men, in leather and chains, as if they were dogs. She called that the worst experience and said she believed Neuenfels had crossed the line.<ref>{{cite web\n|url = https://www.nytimes.com/2000/10/13/arts/13MATT.html\n|title = Karita Mattila: A Soprano Takes a Dramatic Turn\n|accessdate = 2008-07-01\n|first = Anthony\n|last = Tommasini|authorlink=Anthony Tommasini\n|date = 13 October 2000\n|work = [[The New York Times]]}}</ref>\n\nLater, in December 2003, Neuenfels' production of Mozart's ''[[Idomeneo]]'' at the [[Deutsche Oper Berlin]] included a scene in which the title character staggers on stage carrying the severed heads of Neptune, Jesus, Buddha and Mohammed. After the police warned that the production might present a security risk, the opera house cancelled future performances, planned for September 2006. Following protests that the opera house was engaging in self-censorship, its manager, {{Interlanguage link multi|Kirsten Harms|de}}, rescheduled those performances for December 2006; see [[2006 Idomeneo controversy]].\n\nNeuenfels debuted in 2010 at the [[Bayreuth Festival]] with Wagner's ''[[Lohengrin (opera)|Lohengrin]]'', conducted by [[Andris Nelsons]]. This production set the opera in a laboratory and featured chorus members costumed as lab rats. The audience reaction at the premiere ranged from enthusiastic applause to irate booing.<ref name=\"Lohengrin Der Spiegel 2010\">[http://www.spiegel.de/kultur/musik/0,1518,708441,00.html \"Neuer 'Lohengrin' in Bayreuth: Wie man den Schwan rupft\"], ''[[Der Spiegel]]'', in German, 26 July 2010.</ref> According to ''[[Der Spiegel]]'', Neuenfels merely smiled and shrugged after taking his curtain calls.<ref name=\"Lohengrin Der Spiegel 2010\" />\n\n==Personal life==\nWhile studying in Vienna, Neuenfels became acquainted with Austrian actress [[Elisabeth Trissenaar]], whom he subsequently married. Their son, {{ill|Benedict Neuenfels|de}}, is a [[cinematographer]]. They live in Berlin and own a summer residence in [[Altaussee]].\n\n== Writings ==\n* Poems (1960)\n* ''Mundm\u00fcndig'' (1963)\n* ''Isaakaros'' (1991)\n* ''Neapel oder die Reise nach Stuttgart'' (2001)\n\n== Filmography ==\n* 1983: ''[[Penthesilea (Kleist)|Heinrich Penthesilea von Kleist]]''\n* 1983: ''Die Familie oder Schroffenstein''\n* 1984: ''Die Schw\u00e4rmer''\n* 1988: ''Europa und der zweite Apfel'' (TV)\n* 1990: ''Das Blinde Ohr der Oper''\n* 1999: ''[[Die Entf\u00fchrung aus dem Serail]]'' (TV)\n* 2001: ''[[Die Fledermaus]]'' (TV)\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb name|0626860}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Neuenfels, Hans}}\n[[Category:1941 births]]\n[[Category:20th-century German novelists]]\n[[Category:21st-century German novelists]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:German opera directors]]\n[[Category:Members of the Academy of the Arts, Berlin]]\n[[Category:People from Krefeld]]\n[[Category:German male novelists]]\n[[Category:20th-century German male writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century German male writers]]\n", "text_old": "[[File:Oliver Mark - Hans Neuenfels, Berlin 2006.jpg|thumb|Hans Neuenfels, 2006, by [[Oliver Mark]]]]\n'''Hans Neuenfels''' (born 31 May 1941) is a German [[writer]], [[poet]], [[film producer]], [[librettist]], [[theatre director]] and [[opera director]].\n\n== Biography ==\nBorn in [[Krefeld]], Neuenfels studied at the [[Max Reinhardt Seminar]] in Vienna in the 1960s, and in the 1970s he quickly established himself as a leading practitioner of German [[Regietheater]]. Being invited to prominent venues, such as the [[Burgtheater]], his productions were often controversially received, but he worked at the same time with well-known actors such as [[Klaus Maria Brandauer]], [[Bernhard Minetti]] and {{Interlanguage link multi|Anne Bennent|de}}.\n\nHis opera productions have often been accompanied by heated discussions and scandals. In particular his version of ''[[Aida]]'' in 1980 for Frankfurt, conducted by [[Michael Gielen]], in which he portrayed Verdi's Ethiopian slave as a cleaning woman in a contemporary setting, or his ''[[Die Fledermaus|Fledermaus]]'' in 2001 for the [[Salzburg Festival]], which provoked angry reactions and resentment.\n\nNeuenfels has been criticised for creating extremely sexually explicit opera scenes. [[Soprano]] [[Karita Mattila]] criticised him in 2000 for a Salzburg production of [[Wolfgang Amadeus Mozart|Mozart's]] ''[[Cos\u00ec fan tutte]]'' in which huge insects and background videos, some of them erotic, distracted attention from the singers; during Fiordiligi's fiery aria \"{{Lang|it|Come scoglio|italic=no}}\", Mattila arrived onstage walking two men, in leather and chains, as if they were dogs. She called that the worst experience and said she believed Neuenfels had crossed the line.<ref>{{cite web\n|url = https://www.nytimes.com/2000/10/13/arts/13MATT.html\n|title = Karita Mattila: A Soprano Takes a Dramatic Turn\n|accessdate = 2008-07-01\n|first = Anthony\n|last = Tommasini|authorlink=Anthony Tommasini\n|date = 13 October 2000\n|work = [[The New York Times]]}}</ref>\n\nLater, in December 2003, Neuenfels' production of Mozart's ''[[Idomeneo]]'' at the [[Deutsche Oper Berlin]] included a scene in which the title character staggers on stage carrying the severed heads of Neptune, Jesus, Buddha and Mohammed. After the police warned that the production might present a security risk, the opera house cancelled future performances, planned for September 2006. Following protests that the opera house was engaging in self-censorship, its manager, {{Interlanguage link multi|Kirsten Harms|de}}, rescheduled those performances for December 2006; see [[2006 Idomeneo controversy]].\n\nNeuenfels debuted in 2010 at the [[Bayreuth Festival]] with Wagner's ''[[Lohengrin (opera)|Lohengrin]]'', conducted by [[Andris Nelsons]]. This production set the opera in a laboratory and featured chorus members costumed as lab rats. The audience reaction at the premiere ranged from enthusiastic applause to irate booing.<ref name=\"Lohengrin Der Spiegel 2010\">[http://www.spiegel.de/kultur/musik/0,1518,708441,00.html \"Neuer 'Lohengrin' in Bayreuth: Wie man den Schwan rupft\"], ''[[Der Spiegel]]'', in German, 26 July 2010.</ref> According to ''[[Der Spiegel]]'', Neuenfels merely smiled and shrugged after taking his curtain calls.<ref name=\"Lohengrin Der Spiegel 2010\" />\n\n==Personal life==\nWhile studying in Vienna, Neuenfels became acquainted with Austrian actress [[Elisabeth Trissenaar]], whom he subsequently married. Their son, {{ill|Benedict Neuenfels|de}}, is a [[cinematographer]]. They live in Berlin and own a summer residence in [[Altaussee]].\n\n== Writings ==\n* Poems (1960)\n* ''Mundm\u00fcndig'' (1963)\n* ''Isaakaros'' (1991)\n* ''Neapel oder die Reise nach Stuttgart'' (2001)\n\n== Filmography ==\n* 1983: ''[[Penthesilea (Kleist)|Heinrich Penthesilea von Kleist]]''\n* 1983: ''Die Familie oder Schroffenstein''\n* 1984: ''Die Schw\u00e4rmer''\n* 1988: ''Europa und der zweite Apfel'' (TV)\n* 1990: ''Das Blinde Ohr der Oper''\n* 1999: ''[[Die Entf\u00fchrung aus dem Serail]]'' (TV)\n* 2001: ''[[Die Fledermaus]]'' (TV)\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb name|0626860}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Neuenfels, Hans}}\n[[Category:1941 births]]\n[[Category:20th-century German novelists]]\n[[Category:21st-century German novelists]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:German opera directors]]\n[[Category:Members of the Academy of the Arts, Berlin]]\n[[Category:People from Krefeld]]\n[[Category:German male novelists]]\n[[Category:20th-century German male writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century male writers]]\n", "name_user": "Bearcat", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links:recat", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hans_Neuenfels"}
{"title_page": "G\u00fcnter Grass", "text_new": "{{Infobox writer <!-- for more information see [[:Template:Infobox writer/doc]] -->\n| name         = G\u00fcnter Grass\n| image        = G\u00fcnter Grass auf dem Blauen Sofa.jpg\n| caption      = G\u00fcnter Grass in 2006\n|birth_name=G\u00fcnter Wilhelm Gra\u00df <ref name=\"birthname\">{{cite news|url=http://www.spiegel.de/spiegel/print/d-46171737.html|title=Zunge heraus|work=Der Spiegel|date=4 September 1963|quote=(...) wurde G\u00fcnter Wilhelm Gra\u00df am 16. Oktober 1927 geboren.}}</ref>\n| birth_date   = {{Birth date|1927|10|16|df=y}}\n| birth_place  = [[Wrzeszcz|Danzig-Langfuhr]],<br />[[Free City of Danzig]]\n| death_date   = {{Death date and age|2015|04|13|1927|10|16|df=y}}\n| death_place  = [[L\u00fcbeck]], Germany\n| occupation   = Novelist, poet, playwright, sculptor, graphic designer\n| language     = German\n| period       = 1956\u20132013\n| genre        =\n| subject      =\n| movement     = [[Vergangenheitsbew\u00e4ltigung]]\n| notableworks = {{plainlist|\n*''[[The Tin Drum]]'' (1959)\n*''[[Cat and Mouse (novella)|Cat and Mouse]]'' (1961)\n*''[[Dog Years (novel)|Dog Years]]'' (1963)\n*''[[Crabwalk]]'' (2002)\n*''[[What Must Be Said]]'' (2012)\n}}\n| awards       = {{awd|[[Georg B\u00fcchner Prize]]|1965}} {{awd|Honorary Fellow of the [[Royal Society of Literature]]|1993}} {{awd|[[Nobel Prize in Literature]]|1999}} {{awd|[[Prince of Asturias Awards]]|1999}}\n| signature    = G\u00fcnter Grass signature new.svg\n}}\n'''G\u00fcnter Wilhelm Grass'''<ref>{{cite book|chapter-url=https://books.google.de/books?id=Yv0yc2pHDnIC&pg=PA1997-IA14|chapter=Grass, G\u00fcnter|title=Who's Who of Twentieth Century Novelists|first=Tim|last=Woods|publisher=Routledge|year=2008}}</ref> ({{IPA-de|\u02c8\u0261\u028fnt\u0250 \u02c8\u0261\u0281as|lang}}; 16 October 1927&nbsp;\u2013 13 April 2015) was a German novelist, poet, playwright, illustrator, graphic artist, sculptor, and recipient of the 1999 [[Nobel Prize in Literature]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.smh.com.au/world/gunter-grass-tries-to-hose-down-row-over-israel-20120407-1wi8c.html|title=Gunter Grass tries to hose down row over Israel|work=The Sydney Morning Herald|date=8 April 2012|accessdate=8 April 2012|first1=Nicholas|last1=Kulish|first2=Ethan|last2=Bronner|quote=GUNTER Grass, Germany's most famous living writer, has tried to quell the growing controversy...}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.spiegel.de/international/germany/0,1518,825712,00.html|title=Outrage in Germany|work=Der Spiegel|date=4 April 2012|accessdate=4 April 2012|quote=G\u00fcnter Grass, Germany's most famous living author and the 1999 recipient of the Nobel Prize in literature...}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.jpost.com/DiplomacyAndPolitics/Article.aspx?id=265259|title=Yishai: G\u00fcnter Grass not welcome in Israel|work=The Jerusalem Post|date=4 April 2012|accessdate=4 April 2012|quote=Germany's most famous living writer, the Nobel literature laureate G\u00fcnter Grass...}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thehindu.com/news/international/article3291242.ece|title=Outcry as Gunter Grass poem strongly criticises Israel|work=The Hindu|date=8 April 2012|accessdate=8 April 2012|quote=During his long literary career, Gunter Grass has been many things. Author, playwright, sculptor and, unquestionably, Germany's most famous living writer. There is the 1999 Nobel Prize and Mr. Grass's broader post-war role as the country's moral conscience...|location=Chennai, India|first1=Luke|last1=Harding|first2=Harriet|last2=Sherwood}}</ref>\n\nHe was born in the [[Free City of Danzig]] (now [[Gda\u0144sk]], Poland). As a teenager, he served as a [[conscription|drafted]] soldier from late 1944 in the ''[[Waffen-SS]]'' and was taken as a [[prisoner of war]] by US forces at the end of the war in May 1945. He was released in April 1946. Trained as a stonemason and sculptor, Grass began writing in the 1950s. In his fiction, he frequently returned to the Danzig of his childhood.\n\nGrass is best known for his first novel, ''[[The Tin Drum]]'' (1959), a key text in European [[magic realism]]. It was the first book of his [[Danzig Trilogy]], the other two being ''[[Cat and Mouse (novella)|Cat and Mouse]]'' and ''[[Dog Years (novel)|Dog Years]]''. His works are frequently considered to have a [[Left-wing politics|left-wing]] political dimension, and Grass was an active supporter of the [[Social Democratic Party of Germany]] (SPD). ''The Tin Drum'' was [[The Tin Drum (film)|adapted as a film]] of the same name, which won both the 1979 [[Palme d'Or]] and the [[Academy Award for Best International Feature Film|Academy Award for Best Foreign Language Film]]. In 1999, the [[Swedish Academy]] awarded him the [[Nobel Prize in Literature]], praising him as a writer \"whose frolicsome black fables portray the forgotten face of history\".<ref name=\"nobelweb\"/>\n\n==Early life==\nGrass was born in the [[Free City of Danzig]] on 16 October 1927, to Wilhelm Grass (1899\u20131979), a [[Lutheranism|Lutheran]] [[Protestantism|Protestant]] of German origin, and Helene Grass (n\u00e9e Knoff, 1898\u20131954), a [[Catholic Church|Roman Catholic]] of [[Kashubians|Kashubian]]-[[Poles|Polish]] origin.<ref>Garland, ''The Oxford Companion to German Literature'', p. 302.</ref><ref>\"The Literary Encyclopedia\", [http://www.litencyc.com/php/speople.php?rec=true&UID=4990 G\u00fcnter Grass (b. 1927)]. Retrieved on 16 August 2006.</ref> He referred to himself as [[Kashubians|Kashubian]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://wyborcza.pl/1,75475,17744558,Gunter_Grass_nie_zyje__Noblista_mial_87_lat.html#ixzz3XDIG5oiR|title=G\u00fcnter Grass nie \u017cyje. Noblista mia\u0142 87 lat|work=Gazeta Wyborcza|date=13 April 2015|accessdate=13 April 2014|quote=Pytany o to\u017csamo\u015b\u0107 narodow\u0105, m\u00f3wi\u0142, \u017ce jest Kaszub\u0105. (Asking about his ethnicity, he always said that he's Kashubian)}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.focus.de/tagesthema/literatur-portraet-der-unbequeme-nationaldichter_id_4608522.html|title=Portr\u00e4t: Der unbequeme Nationaldichter|work=Focus|date=13 April 2015|accessdate=13 April 2014|quote=Aber wenige haben auch soviel einstecken m\u00fcssen wie der Kaschube aus Danzig. But, just few people had to take flak like the mustachioed Kashubian from Danzig}} (now Gda\u0144sk, Poland)</ref><ref name=\"ethnDEbook\">{{cite news|url=https://books.google.de/books?id=VmV2M05xxiEC&pg=PA61&lpg=PA61&dq=%22g%C3%BCnter+grass%22+%22kaschube%22&source=bl&ots=Rlr7HNFlXk&sig=-MUoexknLdb1j4vq2EL3PCJ6yYA&hl=de&sa=X&ei=osovVYu0BoOsPYLEgeAC&ved=0CCMQ6AEwATgK#v=onepage&q=%22g%C3%BCnter%20grass%22%20%22kaschube%22&f=false|title=Polnische Ostseek\u00fcste, Danzig, Masuren|work=Klaus Kl\u00f6ppel, Olaf Matthei|quote=Er bezeichnet sich selbst gerne als Kaschube}}</ref> Grass was raised a Catholic and served as an altar boy when he was a child.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tagesspiegel.de/zeitung/wer-ist-guenter-grass/739946.html|title=Wer ist G\u00fcnter Grass?|work=Der Tagesspiegel}}</ref> His parents had a grocery store with an attached apartment in Danzig-Langfuhr (now Gda\u0144sk-[[Wrzeszcz]]). He had a sister, Waltraud, born in 1930.<ref>{{cite book|author=Mayer, Claudia |year=2002|title=G\u00fcnter Grass|publisher=Deutscher Taschenbuch Verlag|page=16}}</ref>\n\n[[File:G\u00fcnter Grass pre-war house in Gda\u0144sk during a small snowstorm.jpg|left|thumb|upright|Grass's childhood home in Danzig (now Gda\u0144sk, Poland)]]\nGrass attended the Danzig [[Gymnasium (school)|gymnasium]] ''Conradinum''. In 1943, at age 16, he became a ''[[Luftwaffenhelfer]]'' (Air Force \"helper\"). Soon thereafter, he was conscripted into the ''[[Reich Labour Service|Reichsarbeitsdienst]]'' (National Labour Service). In November 1944, shortly after his 17th birthday, Grass volunteered for [[submarine]] service with [[Nazi Germany]]'s ''[[Kriegsmarine]]'', \"to get out of the confinement felt as a teenager in his parents' house\", which he considered stuffy Catholic lower middle-class.<ref>\"Katholischen Mief\".{{cite news|url=http://www.zeit.de/2006/34/Leiter-1-34|title=Und Grass wundert sich: Die \u00f6ffentliche Selbstrechtfertigung des gro\u00dfen Schriftstellers ist so unn\u00f6tig wie \u00e4rgerlich|work=Die Zeit|year=2006}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://edition.cnn.com/2006/WORLD/europe/08/11/germany.grass.ap/index.html|title=Nobel prize winner Grass admits serving in SS|work=Reuters|date=11 August 2006|accessdate=11 August 2006|archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20060825044934/http://edition.cnn.com/2006/WORLD/europe/08/11/germany.grass.ap/index.html|archivedate=25 August 2006}}</ref>\n\nThe Navy refused him and he was instead called up for the [[10th SS Panzer Division Frundsberg]] in late 1944.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.spiegel.de/kultur/literatur/0,1518,431333,00.html|title=Autor G\u00fcnter Grass: \"Ich war Mitglied der Waffen-SS\"|work=[[Der Spiegel]]|date=11 August 2006|accessdate=11 August 2006}}</ref><ref>[http://www.signandsight.com/features/899.html \"G\u00fcnter Grass was in the Waffen SS\"] \u2013 Survey of reactions to disclosure of time in the ''Waffen-SS'' from the German and international press</ref> Grass did not reveal until 2006 that he was drafted into the ''[[Waffen-SS]]'' at that time.<ref name=\"Feuilleton\">{{cite web|url=http://www.faz.net/s/RubCF3AEB154CE64960822FA5429A182360/Doc~ED1E99E51572441E696FB0443CA308A56~ATpl~Ecommon~Scontent.html|title=G\u00fcnter Grass im Interview: ''\"Warum ich nach sechzig Jahren mein Schweigen breche''\"|publisher=Feuilleton|date=|accessdate=31 October 2010}}</ref> His unit functioned as a regular ''Panzer'' Division, and he served with them from February 1945 until he was wounded on 20 April 1945. He was captured in [[Mari\u00e1nsk\u00e9 L\u00e1zn\u011b|Marienbad]] (now Mari\u00e1nsk\u00e9 L\u00e1zn\u011b, Czech Republic) and sent to a U.S. [[prisoner-of-war camp]] in [[Bad Aibling]], Bavaria.<ref name=Chronology>{{cite book|editor=Taberner, S. (Ed.). |year=2009|title=The Cambridge Companion to G\u00fcnter Grass|publisher=Cambridge University Presses|pages=xiv\u2013xviii}}</ref>\n\nFrom 1946 to 1947, Grass worked in a [[Mining|mine]] and received training in [[stonemasonry]]. He studied sculpture and graphics at the ''[[Kunstakademie D\u00fcsseldorf]]''. He also was a co-founder of [[Group 47]], organized by [[Hans Werner Richter]]. Grass worked as a writer, [[graphic designer]], and sculptor, travelling frequently. In 1953 he moved to West Berlin and studied at the [[Berlin University of the Arts]]. From 1960, he lived in Berlin as well as part-time in [[Schleswig-Holstein]].<ref>{{cite news|title=After many years spent living in Berlin's Friedenau district and a sojourn in the Algarve, Portugal, Grass settled in Behlendorf in Schleswig-Holstein|work=Der Spiegel|publisher=Spiegel Online GmbH|date=13 April 2015|url=http://www.spiegel.de/international/zeitgeist/a-1028399.html|accessdate=4 May 2015|location=Hamburg|first=Sebastian|last=Hammelehle}}</ref> In 1961 he publicly objected to the erection of the [[Berlin Wall]].\n\nFrom 1983 to 1986, he held the presidency of the [[Academy of Arts, Berlin]].<ref name=Chronology />\n\n==Personal life==\nGrass's 1954 marriage to Anna Margareta Schwarz - a Swiss dancer - ended in divorce in 1978. He and Schwarz had four children: Franz (born 1957), Raoul (1957), Laura (1961), and Bruno (1965). Separated in 1972, he began a relationship with Veronika Schr\u00f6ter and had a child with her, Helene (1974). He also had a child with Ingrid Kruger, Nele (1979). In 1979 he married Ute Grunert, an organist, to whom he was still married at his death.<ref name=Chronology /> He had two stepsons from his second marriage, Malte and Hans. He had 18 grandchildren at his death.<ref name=Chronology/><ref>{{cite news|last1=Donahue|first1=Patrick|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2015-04-13/guenter-grass-german-writer-who-took-on-nazi-past-dies-at-87|accessdate=13 April 2015|publisher=Bloomberg|date=April 13, 2005| title = Guenter Grass, German Writer Who Took On Nazism, Dies at 87}}</ref>\n\nGrass was a fan of Bundesliga Club [[SC Freiburg]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.rp-online.de/politik/nobelpreistraeger-drueckt-dem-sc-freiburg-die-daumen-aid-1.2263002|title=Nobelpreistr\u00e4ger dr\u00fcckt dem SC Freiburg die Daumen|date=20 February 2000|accessdate=13 April 2015|agency=RP Online}}</ref>\n\n==Major works==\n===Danzig Trilogy===\n{{main|Danzig Trilogy}}\n[[File:Danzig Partie am Krahnthor (1890-1900).jpg|thumb|300px|Danzig ''Krahntor'' waterfront (postcard, c. 1900)]]\nGrass's best-known work is ''[[The Tin Drum]]'' (German: ''Die Blechtrommel''), published in 1959 (and adapted as a [[The Tin Drum (film)|film]] of the same name by director [[Volker Schl\u00f6ndorff]] in 1979). It was followed in 1961 by ''[[Cat and Mouse (novella)|Cat and Mouse]]'' (German: ''Katz und Maus''), a [[novella]], and in 1963 by the novel ''[[Dog Years (novel)|Dog Years]]'' (German: ''Hundejahre'').\n\nThe books are collectively called the [[Danzig Trilogy]] and focus on the rise of [[Nazism]] and how [[World War II]] affected Danzig (now Gda\u0144sk, Poland), which was separated from Germany after World War I and became the [[Free City of Danzig]] (German: ''Freie Stadt Danzig'').<ref>''International Law Reports'' (1948) by [[Elihu Lauterpacht]], p. 207</ref> [[Dog Years (novel)|''Dog Years'']] (1965) is considered a sequel of sorts to ''The Tin Drum'', as it features some of the same characters.<ref>''The Thomas Mann Handbook'' (2013) by Emily Smith, page 168</ref> It portrays the area's mixed ethnicities and complex historical background in lyrical prose that is highly evocative.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://english.dcbooks.com/author-of-tin-drum-gunter-grass-died.html|title=Author of ''Tin Drum'', G\u00fcnter Grass died|publisher=DC Books|accessdate=April 15, 2015}}</ref>\n\n''The Tin Drum'' established Grass as one of the leading authors of Germany, and also set a high bar of comparison for all of his subsequent works, which were often compared unfavorably to this early work by critics.<ref>{{cite book|author=Mews, S. |year=2008|title=G\u00fcnter Grass and His Critics: From ''The Tin Drum'' to ''Crabwalk''|publisher=Camden House|pages=[[passim]]}}</ref> Nonetheless, in the West Germany of the late '50s and early '60s the book could be controversial, and its \"immorality\" prompted the city of [[Bremen]] to revoke a prize it had bestowed upon him.<ref name=Chronology /> When Grass received the Nobel Prize in literature in 1999 the Nobel Committee stated that the publication of ''The Tin Drum'' \"was as if German literature had been granted a new beginning after decades of linguistic and moral destruction\"<ref>{{cite book|author=Mews, S. |year=2008|title=G\u00fcnter Grass and His Critics: From ''The Tin Drum'' to ''Crabwalk''|publisher=Camden House|page=1}}</ref>\n\n===''The Flounder''===\nThe 1977 novel ''[[The Flounder]]'' (German: ''Der Butt'') is based on the folktale of \"[[The Fisherman and His Wife]]\", and deals with the struggle between the sexes. It has been read as an anti-feminist novel, since in the novel the magical flounder of the folk tale, now representing male triumphalism and the patriarchy is caught by a group of 1970s feminists, who put it on trial. The book interrogates male-female relations from the past and the present through the relationship between the narrator and his wife, who as the wife in the folk tale, insatiably craves more.<ref>{{cite book|author=O'Neill, Patrick |chapter=The Exploratory Fiction of G\u00fcnter Grass|editor=Taberner, S. (Ed.). |year=2009|title=The Cambridge Companion to G\u00fcnter Grass|publisher=Cambridge University Press}}</ref> In spite of the fact that the book could be read as a defense of women and a denouncement of male chauvinism, the book was harshly critiqued and rejected by feminists, partly due to its portrayal of violence, sexualization and objectification, and what the feminists perceived as [[Sex differences in narcissism|male narcissism]] and [[gender essentialism]].<ref>{{cite book|author=Finch, Helen|chapter=G\u00fcnter Grass and Gender|editor=Taberner, S. (Ed.). |year=2009|title=The Cambridge Companion to G\u00fcnter Grass|publisher=Cambridge University Press}}</ref>\n\n===''My Century'' and ''Crabwalk''===\nThe 1999 book ''[[My Century]]'' (German: ''Mein Jahrhundert'') was an overview of the 20th-century's many brutal historic events, conveyed in short pieces, a mosaic of expression. In 2002, Grass returned to the forefront of world literature with ''[[Crabwalk]]'' (German: ''Im Krebsgang''). This novella, one of whose main characters first appeared in ''Cat and Mouse'', was Grass's most successful work in decades. It dealt with the events of a refugee ship, full of thousands of Germans, being sunk by a Russian submarine, killing most on board. It was one of a number of works since the late 20th century that have explored the victimization of Germans in World War II.<ref>{{cite journal|author=Krimmer, E.|year=2008|title='Ein Volk von Opfern?' Germans as Victims in G\u00fcnter Grass's ''Die Blechtrommel'' and ''Im Krebsgang''|journal=Seminar: A Journal of Germanic Studies|volume=44|issue=2|pages=272\u2013290|publisher=University of Toronto Press.}}</ref>\n\n===Memoir trilogy===\nIn 2006, Grass published the first volume in a trilogy of autobiographic memoirs. Titled ''[[Peeling the Onion]]'' (German: ''Beim H\u00e4uten der Zwiebel''), it dealt with his childhood, war years, early efforts as a sculptor and poet, and finally his literary success with the publication of ''The Tin Drum''. In a prepublication interview Grass for the first time revealed that he had been a member of the [[Waffen-SS]], and not only a ''Flakhelfer'' (anti-aircraft assistant) as he had long said. On being asked what caused the need for public confession and revelation of his past in the book he answered: \"It was a weight on me, my silence over all these years is one of the reasons I wrote the book. It had to come out in the end.\"<ref name=NYT />\n\nThe interview and the book caused critics to accuse him of hypocrisy for having hidden this part of his past, while simultaneously being a strong voice for ethics and morality in the public debate.<ref name=NYT /> The book itself was also praised for its depictions of [[History of Germany (1945\u20131990)|the German postwar generation]] and the social and moral development of a nation burdened simultaneously by destruction and a deep sense of guilt.<ref>{{cite web|title=Book Review: G\u00fcnter Grass' ''Peeling the Onion'' \u2013 G\u00fcnter Grass articulates his life, eloquently describing the troubles of the post-war generation and the desperate attempt to rebuild a life out of ruins while coming to terms with one's own guilt.|author=Izvor Moralic|date=October 1, 2006|publisher=Viennareview.net|url=http://www.viennareview.net/vienna-review-book-reviews/upcoming-literary-events/peeling-the-onion|access-date=April 13, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160128133743/http://www.viennareview.net/vienna-review-book-reviews/upcoming-literary-events/peeling-the-onion|archive-date=January 28, 2016|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Throughout the memoir Grass plays with the frailty of memory, for which the layers of the onion are a metaphor. Grass second-guesses his own memories, throws his own autobiographical statements into doubt and questions whether the person inhabiting his past was really him. This struggle with memory comes to represent the struggle of the German people during the same period with Germany's Nazi past.<ref>{{cite book|quote=Peeled, it renews itself; chopped, it brings tears; only during peeling does it speak the truth.|title=Confessions of a super Grass|publisher=The Guardian.com|author=Tim Gardan|url=https://www.theguardian.com/books/2007/jun/24/biography.guntergrass}}</ref>\n\n==Main themes and literary style==\nA main theme in Grass's work is World War II and its effects on Germany and the German people, including a critique of the forms of ideological reasoning that undergirded the Nazi regime. The place of the city of Danzig/Gda\u0144sk and its ambiguous historical status in between Germany and Poland often stands as a symbol of the ambiguity between ethnic groups, also found in Grass's own heritage which includes both German and Slavic family members who fought on opposite sides of the war. His works also show a sustained concern for the marginal and marginalized subjects, such as Oskar Matzerath, the dwarf in ''The Tin Drum'' whose body was considered an aberration unworthy of life in the Nazi ideology, or with [[Romani people|Roma]] and [[Sinti]] people who were also deemed impure and unworthy and subjected to eugenics and genocide.<ref>{{cite book|author=Arnds, P. O. |year=2004|title=Representation, subversion, and eugenics in G\u00fcnter Grass's ''The Tin Drum''|publisher=Camden House}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|editor=Taberner, S. (Ed.). |year=2009|title=The Cambridge Companion to G\u00fcnter Grass|publisher=Cambridge University Press}}</ref>\n\nHis literary style combines elements of [[magic realism]], with a penchant for questioning and complicating questions of authorship by intermingling realistic autobiographical elements with [[unreliable narrator]]s and fantastic events or happenings that creates irony or satirizes events to form social critiques.<ref>{{cite book|author=Braun, R. |year=2008|title=Constructing Authorship in the Work of G\u00fcnter Grass|publisher= Oxford University Press}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|author=Arnds, P. O.|chapter=G\u00fcnter Grass and Magical Realism|editor=Taberner, S. (Ed.). |year=2009|title=The Cambridge Companion to G\u00fcnter Grass|publisher=Cambridge University Press}}</ref>\n\n==Reception by critics and colleagues==\nGrass's work has tended to divide the critics into those who have considered his experiments and style to be sublime and those who have found it to be tied down by his political posturing. Particularly American critics such as [[John Updike]] have found the mixture of politics and social critique in his works to diminish its artistic qualities.<ref>{{cite book|author=Mews, S. |year=2008|title=G\u00fcnter Grass and His Critics: From ''The Tin Drum'' to ''Crabwalk''|publisher=Camden House}}</ref> In his various critiques of Grass's works, Updike wrote that Grass had been consumed by his \"strenuous career as celebrity-author-artist-Socialist\" and about one of his later novels that \"he can't be bothered to write a novel; he just sends dispatches ... from the front lines of his engagement\". Even if frequently critical of Grass, Updike considered him to be \"one of the very, very few authors whose next novel one has no intention of missing\".<ref>{{cite book|author=Mews, S. |year=2008|title=G\u00fcnter Grass and His Critics: From ''The Tin Drum'' to ''Crabwalk''|publisher=Camden House|pages=107, 146, 195}}</ref>\n\nGrass's literary style has been widely influential. [[John Irving]] called Grass \"simply the most original and versatile writer alive\". And many have noted parallels between Irving's ''A Prayer for Owen Meany'' and ''The Tin Drum''.<ref>{{cite book|author=Mews, S. |year=2008|title=G\u00fcnter Grass and His Critics: From ''The Tin Drum'' to ''Crabwalk''|publisher=Camden House|page=53}}</ref> Similarly, [[Salman Rushdie]] has acknowledged a debt to Grass's work, particularly ''The Tin Drum'', and many parallels to Grass's work have been pointed out in his own oeuvre.<ref>{{cite book|author=Mews, S. |year=2008|title=G\u00fcnter Grass and His Critics: From ''The Tin Drum'' to ''Crabwalk''|publisher=Camden House|page=55}}</ref>\n\n==Social and political activism==\n[[File:G\u00fcnter Grass (1986) by Erling Mandelmann.jpg|thumb|upright|Grass in 1986]]\nGrass was for several decades a supporter of the [[Social Democratic Party of Germany]] and its policies. He took part in German and international political debate on several occasions. During [[Willy Brandt]]'s chancellorship, Grass was an active supporter. Grass criticised left-wing radicals and instead argued in favour of the \"snail's pace\", as he put it, of [[Reformism|democratic reform]] (''Aus dem Tagebuch einer Schnecke''). Books containing his speeches and essays were released throughout his literary career.<ref name=Chronology/>\n\nIn the 1980s, he became active in the [[peace movement]] and visited [[Kolkata|Calcutta]] for six months.<ref name=Chronology/> A diary with drawings was published as ''Zunge zeigen'', an allusion to [[Kali]]'s tongue.\n\nDuring the events leading up to the [[German reunification|reunification of Germany]] in 1989\u201390, Grass argued for the continued separation of the two German states. He asserted that a unified Germany would be likely to resume its role as belligerent nation-state. This argument estranged many Germans, who came to see him as too much of a moralizing figure.<ref name=NYT>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/04/14/world/europe/gunter-grass-german-novelist-dies-at-87.html?_r=0|work=[[The New York Times]]|author=Stephen Kinzer|authorlink=Stephen Kinzer|title=G\u00fcnter Grass, German Novelist and Social Critic, Dies at 87}}</ref>\n\nIn 2001, Grass proposed the creation of a German-Polish museum for art lost to other countries during the War. The [[Hague Conventions of 1899 and 1907|Hague Convention of 1907]] requires the return of art that had been evacuated, stolen or seized. Some countries refused to repatriate some of the [[looted art]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.faz.net/s/RubEBED639C476B407798B1CE808F1F6632/Doc~E73D9568D79A14F7CB8686D42EC8ACD04~ATpl~Ecommon~Scontent.html |title=R\u00fcckgabe von Beutekunst: Die letzten deutschen Kriegsgefangenen|publisher=Feuilleton|date=26 October 2010|accessdate=31 October 2010}}</ref><ref>[http://www.spiegel.de/kultur/gesellschaft/0,1518,498915,00.html ''Der Spiegel''].</ref>\n\nOn 4 April 2012, Grass's poem \"[[What Must Be Said]]\" (German: ''Was gesagt werden muss'') was published in several European newspapers. Grass expressed his concern about the hypocrisy of German military support (the delivery of a submarine) for an [[Israel]] that might use such equipment to launch nuclear warheads against Iran, which \"could wipe out the Iranian people\". And he hoped that many would demand \"that the governments of both Iran and Israel allow an international authority free and open inspection of the nuclear potential and capability of both.\" In response, Israel declared him ''[[persona non grata]]'' in that country.<ref name=haaretz_persona_non_grata>{{cite news|first1=Ophir|last1=Bar-Zohar|first2=Barak|last2=Ravid|url=http://www.haaretz.com/news/diplomacy-defense/interior-minister-declares-gunter-grass-persona-non-grata-in-israel-1.423239|title=Interior Minister declares Gunter Grass persona non grata in Israel|work=[[Haaretz]]|date=8 April 2012|accessdate=8 April 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|author=G\u00fcnter Grass |url=https://www.theguardian.com/books/2012/apr/05/gunter-grass-what-must-be-said?intcmp=239|title=What Must Be Said|work=The Guardian|date=5 April 2012|accessdate=15 January 2013|location=London}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Weinthal |first=Benjamin |url=http://www.jpost.com/International/Article.aspx?id=265415|title=Benjamin Weinthal: Berlin politicians split over Grass travel ban|work=The Jerusalem Post|date=3 January 2013|accessdate=15 January 2013}}</ref>\n\nAccording to [[Avi Primor]], president of the [[Israel Council on Foreign Relations]], Grass was the only important German cultural figure who had refused to meet with him when he served as [[List of ambassadors of Israel to Germany|Israeli ambassador to Germany]]. Primor noted: \"One explanation for [Grass']s strange behaviour might be found in the fact that Grass (who despite his poem is probably not the bitter enemy of Israel that one would imagine) had certain personal difficulties with Israel.\" Primor said that during Grass's earlier visit to Israel, he \"was confronted with the anger of an Israeli public that booed him in successive public appearances. To be sure, the Israeli protestors were not targeting Grass personally and their anger had nothing at all to do with his literature. It was the German effort to establish cultural relations with Israel to which they objected. Grass, however, did not see it that way and may well have felt personally slighted.\"<ref>[[Avi Primor]], \"Peeling G\u00fcnter Grass' Israeli Onion\", ''Israel Journal of Foreign Affairs,'' Vol. 6, No. 2 (2012), p. 103 [http://israelcfr.com/documents/6-2/6-2-8-AviPrimor.pdf (PDF)] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140825153611/http://www.israelcfr.com/documents/6-2/6-2-8-AviPrimor.pdf |date=2014-08-25 }}</ref>\n\nGrass was a supporter of the [[Campaign for the Establishment of a United Nations Parliamentary Assembly]], an organisation which campaigns for democratic reformation of the United Nations, and the creation of a more accountable international political system.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://en.unpacampaign.org/supporters/overview/?mapcountry=allhea&mapgroup=hea|title=Overview|date=|work=Campaign for a UN Parliamentary Assembly|access-date=2017-09-26}}</ref>\n\nOn 26 April 2012, Grass wrote a poem criticizing European policy for the treatment of Greece in the [[European debt crisis]]. In \"Europe's Disgrace\", Grass accuses Europe of condemning Greece to poverty, a country \"whose mind conceived Europe.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://newsticker.sueddeutsche.de/list/id/1319034|title=Newsticker|work=[[S\u00fcddeutsche Zeitung]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ekathimerini.com/4dcgi/_w_articles_wsite1_1_27/05/2012_444146 |title=Gunter Grass stands by poem about Greece and Europe|work=Ekathimerini|date=27 May 2012|accessdate=15 January 2013}}</ref>\n\nJust a few days before he died Grass completed his last book, ''Vonne Endlichkait''. The title is in [[East Prussia]]n dialect, the native dialect of Grass, and it means \"About Finitude.\" According to his publisher Gerhard Steidl, the book was \"a literary experiment\", combining short prose texts, poems and a pencil drawings by the writer.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dw.com/en/g%C3%BCnter-grass-leaves-a-last-farewell-book/a-18671538|title=G\u00fcnter Grass leaves a last farewell book {{!}} Books {{!}} DW.COM {{!}} 26.08.2015|last=(www.dw.com)|first=Deutsche Welle|website=DW.COM|access-date=2016-10-17}}</ref> The book was published in August 2015.\n\n==Awards and honours==\n[[File:G\u00fcnter Grass and Willy Brandt.jpg|thumb|Grass with the West German Chancellor [[Willy Brandt]], 1972]]\nGrass received dozens of international awards; in 1999, he was awarded the highest literary honour: the [[Nobel Prize in Literature]]. The [[Swedish Academy]] noted him as a writer \"whose frolicsome black fables portray the forgotten face of history\".<ref name=\"nobelweb\">{{cite web|url=http://nobelprize.org/nobel_prizes/literature/laureates/1999/|title=The Nobel Prize in Literature 1999|accessdate=8 October 2009|publisher=Nobelprize.org}}</ref> His literature is commonly categorised as part of the German artistic movement known as ''[[Vergangenheitsbew\u00e4ltigung]]'', roughly translated as \"coming to terms with the past.\"\n\nIn 1965, Grass received the [[Georg B\u00fcchner Prize]]; in 1993 he was elected an Honorary Fellow of the [[Royal Society of Literature]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rslit.org/content/fellows|title=Royal Society of Literature All Fellows|work=Royal Society of Literature|accessdate=8 August 2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100305070326/http://www.rslit.org/content/fellows|archivedate=5 March 2010}}</ref> In 1995, he received the [[Hermann Kesten Prize]].\n\nRepresentatives of the city of [[Bremen]] joined together to establish the G\u00fcnter Grass Foundation with the aim of establishing a centralized collection of his numerous works, especially his many personal readings, videos and films. The G\u00fcnter Grass House in [[L\u00fcbeck]] houses exhibitions of his drawings and sculptures, an archive and a library.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.luebeck-tourism.de/culture/museums/guenter-grass-house.html|title=Gunter Grass House Lubeck}}</ref>\n\nIn 2012, Grass received the award European of the Year from the European Movement Denmark (Europabev\u00e6gelsen) honoring his political debates in European affairs.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://jyllands-posten.dk/international/europa/ECE4945915/G%C3%BCnter+Grass+bliver+%C3%A5rets+europ%C3%A6er+/|title=Gunter Grass bliver \u00e5rets Europ\u00e6er| publisher=Jyllandsposten}}</ref>\n\n==''Waffen-SS'' revelations==\nIn August 2006, in an interview about his forthcoming book, ''Peeling the Onion'', Grass said that he had been a member of the ''[[Waffen-SS]]'' in World War II.<ref name=\"Feuilleton\" /> Prior to that, he had been considered a typical member of the \"[[Luftwaffenhelfer|Flakhelfer]] generation\", one of those too young to see much fighting or to be involved with the Nazi regime beyond its youth organizations.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.faz.net/aktuell/gesellschaft/menschen/guenter-grass-enthuellt-ich-war-mitglied-der-waffen-ss-1354882.html|agency=Frankfurter Allgemeine Gesellschaft|title=Ich war Mitglied der Waffen-SS|date=11 August 2006|accessdate=13 April 2015|language=German}}</ref>\n\nOn 15 August 2006, the online edition of ''[[Der Spiegel]]'', [[Spiegel Online]], published three 1946 documents from U.S. forces verifying Grass's ''Waffen-SS'' membership.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.spiegel.de/kultur/gesellschaft/0,1518,431823,00.html|title=Grass r\u00e4umte als Kriegsgefangener Waffen-SS-Mitgliedschaft ein|work=Der Spiegel|accessdate=31 October 2010}}</ref>\n\nAfter an unsuccessful attempt to volunteer for the [[U-boat]] fleet in 1942, at age 15, Grass was conscripted into the ''[[Reichsarbeitsdienst]]'' (Reich Labor Service). He was called up for the ''Waffen-SS'' in 1944. Grass was trained as a tank gunner and fought with the [[10th SS Panzer Division Frundsberg]] until its surrender to U.S. forces at [[Mari\u00e1nsk\u00e9 L\u00e1zn\u011b|Marienbad]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://nypost.com/2015/04/13/noble-laureate-gunter-grass-dead-at-87/|work=[[New York Post]]|title=Noble laureate G\u00fcnter Grass dead at 87|date=13 April 2015|accessdate=13 April 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"nyer\">{{cite news|last=Grass|first=G\u00fcnter|title=How I Spent the War: A recruit in the Waffen S.S.|work=[[The New Yorker]]|date=4 June 2007|url=http://www.newyorker.com/reporting/2007/06/04/070604fa_fact_grass?currentPage=all|accessdate=24 May 2007}}</ref>\n\nIn 2007, Grass published an account of his wartime experience in ''[[The New Yorker]]'', including an attempt to \"string together the circumstances that probably triggered and nourished my decision to enlist.\"<ref name=\"nyer\" /> To the [[BBC]], Grass said in 2006: \"It happened as it did to many of my age. We were in the labour service and all at once, a year later, the call-up notice lay on the table. And only when I got to Dresden did I learn it was the Waffen-SS.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/4785851.stm|title=Guenter Grass served in Waffen SS|work=BBC News|date=11 August 2006|accessdate=11 August 2006}}</ref>\n\n[[Joachim Fest]] \u2013 German journalist, historian and biographer of [[Adolf Hitler]] \u2013 remarked, to the German weekly ''[[Der Spiegel]]'', on Grass's disclosure: \"After 60 years, this confession comes a bit too late. I can't understand how someone who for decades set himself up as a moral authority, a rather smug one, could pull this off.\"<ref>{{cite news|title=Grass admits serving in Waffen SS|work=Reuters|date=13 August 2006|url=http://www.iht.com/articles/2006/08/13/news/grass.php|accessdate=13 August 2006}}</ref>\n\nAs Grass was for many decades an outspoken left-leaning critic of Germany's failure to deal with its Nazi past, his statement caused a great stir in the press. [[Rolf Hochhuth]] said it was \"disgusting\" that this same \"politically correct\" Grass had publicly criticized [[Helmut Kohl]] and [[Ronald Reagan]]'s visit to a military cemetery at [[Bitburg]] in 1985, because it contained graves of ''Waffen-SS'' soldiers.<ref name=NYT /> In the same vein, the historian [[Michael Wolffsohn]] accused Grass of hypocrisy in not earlier disclosing his SS membership.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.dw.de/nobel-prize-winner-grass-under-fire-for-belated-ss-confession/a-2132108|agency=Deutsche Welle|title=Nobel Prize Winner Grass Under Fire for Belated SS Confession|date=14 August 2006|accessdate=13 April 2015}}</ref>\n\nOthers defended Grass, saying his involuntary ''Waffen-SS'' membership came very early in his life, resulting from his being drafted shortly after his seventeenth birthday. They noted he had always \u2013 after the war was lost \u2013 been publicly critical of Germany's Nazi past. For example, novelist [[John Irving]] criticised those who would dismiss the achievements of a lifetime because of a mistake made as a teenager.<ref>{{cite news\n| title = G\u00fcnter Grass is my hero, as a writer and a moral compass\n| work = The Guardian\n| publisher = Guardian Media Group\n| date = 19 August 2006\n| url = https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/story/0,,1853745,00.html\n| accessdate = 19 August 2006\n| location = London\n| first = John\n| last = Irving|authorlink=John Irving}}</ref>\n\nGrass's biographer {{Interlanguage link multi|Michael J\u00fcrgs|de}} described the controversy as resulting in \"the end of a moral institution\".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.spiegel.de/kultur/literatur/0,1518,431412,00.html|title=Echo auf Grass' SS-Vergangenheit: \"Ende einer moralischen Instanz\"|work=Der Spiegel|date=12 August 2006|accessdate=31 October 2010}}</ref> [[Lech Wa\u0142\u0119sa]] initially criticized Grass for keeping silent about his ''Waffen-SS'' membership for 60 years. He later withdrew his criticism after reading Grass's letter to the mayor of Gda\u0144sk, saying that Grass \"set the good example for the others.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.spiegel.de/kultur/literatur/0,1518,431491,00.html|title=SS-Vergangenheit: Walesa macht Grass Ehrenb\u00fcrgerw\u00fcrde streitig|work=Der Spiegel|date=|accessdate=31 October 2010}}</ref>\nOn 14 August 2006, the ruling party of Poland, [[Law and Justice]], called on Grass to relinquish his honorary citizenship of Gda\u0144sk. [[Jacek Kurski]], a Law and Justice politician said, \"It is unacceptable for a city where the first blood was shed, where World War II began, to have a Waffen-SS member as an honorary citizen.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://wiadomosci.wp.pl/kat,1342,title,Kurski-Grass-nie-rozumie-czym-zranil-Polakow,wid,8466747,wiadomosc.html?ticaid=114af2|agency=Wiadomo\u015bci|date=17 August 2006|accessdate=13 April 2015|title=Kurski: Grass nie rozumie, czym zrani\u0142 Polak\u00f3w|language=Polish}}</ref> But, according to a 2010 poll<ref>{{cite news|url=http://serwisy.gazeta.pl/kraj/1,34317,3560655.html|title=Kraj \u2013 Gazeta.pl|work=Serwisy.gazeta.pl|accessdate=31 October 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081009210534/http://serwisy.gazeta.pl/kraj/1,34317,3560655.html|archive-date=9 October 2008|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>http://bi.gazeta.pl/im/4/3561/m3561294.jpg</ref> ordered by city's authorities, the vast majority of Gda\u0144sk citizens did not support Kurski's position. The mayor of Gda\u0144sk, [[Pawe\u0142 Adamowicz]], said that he opposed submitting the affair to the municipal council because it was not for the council to judge history.<ref>\n{{cite news\n| last = Rakowiec\n| first = Ma\u0142gorzata\n| title = Grass asked to give up Polish title\n| work = Reuters\n| date = 14 August 2006\n| url = http://news.scotsman.com/latest.cfm?id=1185192006\n| accessdate = 14 August 2006\n| location=Edinburgh}}{{Dead link|date=October 2010|bot=H3llBot}}</ref>\n\n==Death==\n[[File:Grave Guenter Grass in Behlendorf.jpg|thumb|Grave of G\u00fcnter Grass in Behlendorf]]\nAn avid pipe smoker for most of his adult life, Grass died of a lung infection on 13 April 2015 in a [[L\u00fcbeck]] hospital at the age of 87.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dw.de/renowned-german-author-g%C3%BCnter-grass-dies-aged-87/a-18377707|title=Renowned German author G\u00fcnter Grass dies, aged 87|publisher=DW.de|accessdate=April 14, 2015}}</ref><ref name=bbc-obit>[https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-32285705 German author Guenter Grass dies], ''BBC News'', 13 April 2015.</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/books/2015/apr/13/gunter-grass-german-nobel-laureate-dies-aged-87|title=G\u00fcnter Grass, Nobel-winning German novelist, dies aged 87|author=Richard Lea|work=the Guardian}}</ref> He was buried in a private family observance on 25 April in [[Behlendorf]], 15 miles south of L\u00fcbeck, where he had lived since 1995.\n\nU.S. novelist [[John Irving]] delivered the main eulogy at a memorial service for Grass on 10 May in the [[Theater L\u00fcbeck]]. Among those who attended were German President [[Joachim Gauck]], federal Commissioner for Culture [[Monika Gr\u00fctters]], and [[Pawe\u0142 Adamowicz]], mayor of Gda\u0144sk.<ref>[http://www.spiegel.de/kultur/literatur/guenter-grass-trauerfeier-in-luebeck-a-1033062.html \"Abschied von G\u00fcnter Grass: 'Der K\u00f6nig der Spielzeugh\u00e4ndler'&thinsp;\"], ''[[Der Spiegel]]'', 10 May 2015 {{in lang|de}}</ref> Gr\u00fctters, in remarks to mourners, noted that Grass through his work championed the independence of artists and of art itself.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ln-online.de/Nachrichten/Kultur/Bewegende-Gedenkfeier-fuer-Guenter-Grass|title=Bewegende Gedenkfeier f\u00fcr G\u00fcnter Grass|work=[[L\u00fcbecker Nachrichten]]|accessdate=May 10, 2015}}</ref> Adamowicz said Grass had \"bridged the chasm between Germany and Poland,\" and praised the novelist's \"unwillingness to compromise.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.express.de/news/gedenkfeier-fuer-guenter-grass--koenig-der-spielzeughaendler-ist-gegangen--1723388|title=Gedenkfeier f\u00fcr G\u00fcnter Grass \u2013 'K\u00f6nig der Spielzeugh\u00e4ndler ist gegangen'&thinsp;|author=J\u00fcrgen Kowallik|work=[[Express (Cologne newspaper)|Express]]|date=10 May 2015|location=Cologne|access-date=29 September 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Bibliography==\n* ''Die Vorz\u00fcge der Windh\u00fchner'' (poems, 1956); Steidl, 2007, {{ISBN|9783865215697}}\n* ''Die b\u00f6sen K\u00f6che. Ein Drama'' (play, 1956) ISSN 0722-8511 translated as ''The Wicked Cooks'' in ''Four Plays'' (1967)\n* ''Hochwasser. Ein St\u00fcck in zwei Akten'' (play, 1957) ''The Flood''\n* ''Onkel, Onkel. Ein Spiel in vier Akten'' (play, 1958) ''Mister, Mister''\n* ''[[Danzig Trilogy|Danziger Trilogie]]''\n** ''Die Blechtrommel'' (novel, 1959) trans. ''[[The Tin Drum]]'' (1959) {{ISBN|978-0-679-72575-6}}.\n** ''Katz und Maus'' (novella, 1961) trans. ''[[Cat and Mouse (novella)|Cat and Mouse]]'' (1963) {{ISBN|9780156155519}}\n** ''Hundejahre'' (novel, 1963) trans. ''[[Dog Years (novel)|Dog Years]]'' (1965) {{ISBN|9780749394509}}\n* ''Gleisdreieck'' (poems, 1960)\n* ''Die Plebejer proben den Aufstand'' (play, 1966) trans. ''The Plebeians Rehearse the Uprising'' (1966)\n* ''Ausgefragt'' (poems, 1967)\n* ''\u00dcber das Selbstverst\u00e4ndliche. Reden \u2013 Aufs\u00e4tze \u2013 Offene Briefe \u2013 Kommentare'' (speeches, essays, 1968) trans. ''Speak out! Speeches, Open Letters, Commentaries'' (1969) with 3 additional pieces\n* ''\u00d6rtlich bet\u00e4ubt'' (novel, 1969) trans. ''[[Local Anaesthetic (novel)|Local Anaesthetic]]'' (1970) {{ISBN|9780449242575}}\n* ''Davor'' (play, 1970) trans. ''Max'' (1972) on a plot from ''Local Anaesthetic''\n* ''Aus dem Tagebuch einer Schnecke'' (political reportage, 1972) trans. ''[[From the Diary of a Snail]]'' (1973) {{ISBN|9780749394554}}\n* ''Der B\u00fcrger und seine Stimme. Reden Aufs\u00e4tze Kommentare'' (speeches, essays, 1974)\n* ''Denkzettel. Politische Reden und Aufs\u00e4tze 1965\u20131976'' (political essays and speeches, 1978)\n* ''Der Butt'' (novel, 1977) trans. ''[[The Flounder]]'' (1978) {{ISBN|9780156319355}}\n* ''Das Treffen in Telgte'' (novel, 1979) trans. ''[[The Meeting at Telgte]]'' (1981)\n* ''Kopfgeburten oder Die Deutschen sterben aus'' (novel, 1980) trans. ''[[Headbirths, or, the Germans are Dying Out]]'' (1982)\n* ''Widerstand lernen. Politische Gegenreden 1980\u20131983'' (political speeches, 1984)\n* ''Die R\u00e4ttin'' (novel, 1986) trans. ''[[The Rat (novel)|The Rat]]'' (1987) {{ISBN|9780156758307}}\n* ''Zunge zeigen. Ein Tagebuch in Zeichnungen'' (political diary, 1988) trans. ''[[Show Your Tongue]]'' (1989)\n* ''Unkenrufe'' (novel, 1992) trans. ''[[The Call of the Toad]]'' (1992) {{ISBN|9780156153409}}\n* ''Ein weites Feld'' (novel, 1995) trans. ''[[Too Far Afield]]'' (2000) {{ISBN|9780156014168}}\n* ''Mein Jahrhundert'' (novel, 1999) trans. ''[[My Century]]'' (1999) {{ISBN|9780156011419}}\n* ''Im Krebsgang'' (novel, 2002) trans. ''[[Crabwalk]]'' (2002) {{ISBN|9780156029704}}\n* ''Letzte T\u00e4nze'' (poems, 2003)\n* ''Beim H\u00e4uten der Zwiebel'' (memoir, 2006) trans. ''[[Peeling the Onion]]'' (2007) {{ISBN|9780156035347}} \u2013 first volume of memoir\n* ''Dummer August'' (poems, 2007)\n* ''Die Box'' (memoir, 2008) trans. ''[[The Box (Grass book)|The Box]]'' (2010) {{ISBN|9780099539759}} \u2013 second volume of memoir\n* ''Unterwegs von Deutschland nach Deutschland. Tagebuch 1990.'' (political diary, 2009) trans. ''From Germany to Germany: Diary 1990'' (2012) {{ISBN|9780547364605}}\n* ''Grimms W\u00f6rter'' (memoir, 2010) Third volume of memoir.<ref name=\"bibliography\">{{cite web|url=https://www.nobelprize.org/nobel_prizes/literature/laureates/1999/grass-bibl.html|publisher=Nobelprize.org|title=The Nobel Prize in Literature 1999: G\u00fcnter Grass \u2013 Bibliography|accessdate=13 April 2015}}</ref>\n* ''Vonne Endlichkait'' (collection of prose, poetry, and drawings, 2015) {{ISBN|9783958290426}}\n\n'''Collections in English translation'''\n* ''Four Plays'' (1967) including ''Ten Minutes to Buffalo''\n* ''In the Egg and Other Poems'' (1977)\n* ''Two States One Nation?'' (1990)<ref name=\"bibliography\" />\n* ''Of All That Ends'' (poetry and prose) (6 December 2016) {{ISBN|978-0544785380}}\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of Nobel laureates in Literature]]\n* [[List of people declared persona non grata]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|G\u00fcnter Grass}}\n{{Wikiquote}}\n* {{worldcat id|id=lccn-n80-85270}}\n* {{Perlentaucher|guenter-grass}}\n* [http://www.gdansk-life.com/poland/gunter-grass G\u00fcnter Grass] at gdansk-life.com {{in lang|en}}\n* [https://www.theguardian.com/secondworldwar/story/0,,1843187,00.html \"Grass admits serving with Waffen-SS\"], ''[[The Guardian]]''\n* {{cite journal|url=http://www.theparisreview.org/interviews/2191/the-art-of-fiction-no-124-gunter-grass|title=Gunter Grass, The Art of Fiction No. 124|journal=[[The Paris Review]]|date=Summer 1991|first=Elizabeth|last=Gaffney|authorlink=Elizabeth Gaffney}}\n* {{cite interview|url=http://www.nypl.org/events/programs/2007/06/27/20th-century-trial-g%C3%BCnter-grass-norman-mailer-interviewed-and-conversatio|title=The 20th Century on Trial|subject=G\u00fcnter Grass|subject2=Norman Mailer|subject-link2=Norman Mailer|interviewer=[[Andrew O'Hagan]]|publisher=[[New York Public Library]]|year=2007}}\n* {{cite news|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/p004d1b6|title=G\u00fcnter Grass talking about ''The Tin Drum''|work=[[World Book Club]]|publisher=BBC|date=3 October 2009}}\n*{{C-SPAN|Gunter Grass}}\n{{s-start}}\n{{S-ach}}\n{{succession box\n|before = {{flagicon|Denmark}} [[Henrik, Prince Consort of Denmark]]\n|title = European of the Year<br/><small>(by the Danish European Movement)</small>\n|years = 2012\n|after = {{flagicon|Denmark}} [[Emmelie de Forest]]\n}}\n{{s-end}}\n{{G\u00fcnter Grass}}\n{{Navboxes\n|title= Awards received by G\u00fcnter Grass\n|list1=\n{{Georg B\u00fcchner Prize}}\n{{Sonning Prize laureates}}\n{{Nobel Prize in Literature}}\n{{1999 Nobel Prize winners}}\n{{Prince of Asturias Award for Literature}}\n}}\n{{German literature}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Grass, Gunter}}\n[[Category:1927 births]]\n[[Category:2015 deaths]]\n[[Category:Catholic socialists]]\n[[Category:Fellows of the Royal Society of Literature]]\n[[Category:Georg B\u00fcchner Prize winners]]\n[[Category:German autobiographers]]\n[[Category:German essayists]]\n[[Category:German-language poets]]\n[[Category:German male novelists]]\n[[Category:German male dramatists and playwrights]]\n[[Category:German male sculptors]]\n[[Category:German memoirists]]\n[[Category:German Nobel laureates]]\n[[Category:German people of Slavic descent]]\n[[Category:German prisoners of war in World War II held by the United States]]\n[[Category:German Roman Catholics]]\n[[Category:German socialists]]\n[[Category:Kunstakademie D\u00fcsseldorf alumni]]\n[[Category:Magic realism writers]]\n[[Category:Members of the Academy of the Arts, Berlin]]\n[[Category:Nobel laureates in Literature]]\n[[Category:People from the Free City of Danzig]]\n[[Category:Waffen-SS personnel]]\n[[Category:Writers who illustrated their own writing]]\n[[Category:20th-century essayists]]\n[[Category:20th-century German dramatists and playwrights]]\n[[Category:20th-century German novelists]]\n[[Category:20th-century German poets]]\n[[Category:20th-century German sculptors]]\n[[Category:21st-century essayists]]\n[[Category:21st-century German novelists]]\n[[Category:21st-century German poets]]\n[[Category:21st-century German male writers]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox writer <!-- for more information see [[:Template:Infobox writer/doc]] -->\n| name         = G\u00fcnter Grass\n| image        = G\u00fcnter Grass auf dem Blauen Sofa.jpg\n| caption      = G\u00fcnter Grass in 2006\n|birth_name=G\u00fcnter Wilhelm Gra\u00df <ref name=\"birthname\">{{cite news|url=http://www.spiegel.de/spiegel/print/d-46171737.html|title=Zunge heraus|work=Der Spiegel|date=4 September 1963|quote=(...) wurde G\u00fcnter Wilhelm Gra\u00df am 16. Oktober 1927 geboren.}}</ref>\n| birth_date   = {{Birth date|1927|10|16|df=y}}\n| birth_place  = [[Wrzeszcz|Danzig-Langfuhr]],<br />[[Free City of Danzig]]\n| death_date   = {{Death date and age|2015|04|13|1927|10|16|df=y}}\n| death_place  = [[L\u00fcbeck]], Germany\n| occupation   = Novelist, poet, playwright, sculptor, graphic designer\n| language     = German\n| period       = 1956\u20132013\n| genre        =\n| subject      =\n| movement     = [[Vergangenheitsbew\u00e4ltigung]]\n| notableworks = {{plainlist|\n*''[[The Tin Drum]]'' (1959)\n*''[[Cat and Mouse (novella)|Cat and Mouse]]'' (1961)\n*''[[Dog Years (novel)|Dog Years]]'' (1963)\n*''[[Crabwalk]]'' (2002)\n*''[[What Must Be Said]]'' (2012)\n}}\n| awards       = {{awd|[[Georg B\u00fcchner Prize]]|1965}} {{awd|Honorary Fellow of the [[Royal Society of Literature]]|1993}} {{awd|[[Nobel Prize in Literature]]|1999}} {{awd|[[Prince of Asturias Awards]]|1999}}\n| signature    = G\u00fcnter Grass signature new.svg\n}}\n'''G\u00fcnter Wilhelm Grass'''<ref>{{cite book|chapter-url=https://books.google.de/books?id=Yv0yc2pHDnIC&pg=PA1997-IA14|chapter=Grass, G\u00fcnter|title=Who's Who of Twentieth Century Novelists|first=Tim|last=Woods|publisher=Routledge|year=2008}}</ref> ({{IPA-de|\u02c8\u0261\u028fnt\u0250 \u02c8\u0261\u0281as|lang}}; 16 October 1927&nbsp;\u2013 13 April 2015) was a German novelist, poet, playwright, illustrator, graphic artist, sculptor, and recipient of the 1999 [[Nobel Prize in Literature]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.smh.com.au/world/gunter-grass-tries-to-hose-down-row-over-israel-20120407-1wi8c.html|title=Gunter Grass tries to hose down row over Israel|work=The Sydney Morning Herald|date=8 April 2012|accessdate=8 April 2012|first1=Nicholas|last1=Kulish|first2=Ethan|last2=Bronner|quote=GUNTER Grass, Germany's most famous living writer, has tried to quell the growing controversy...}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.spiegel.de/international/germany/0,1518,825712,00.html|title=Outrage in Germany|work=Der Spiegel|date=4 April 2012|accessdate=4 April 2012|quote=G\u00fcnter Grass, Germany's most famous living author and the 1999 recipient of the Nobel Prize in literature...}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.jpost.com/DiplomacyAndPolitics/Article.aspx?id=265259|title=Yishai: G\u00fcnter Grass not welcome in Israel|work=The Jerusalem Post|date=4 April 2012|accessdate=4 April 2012|quote=Germany's most famous living writer, the Nobel literature laureate G\u00fcnter Grass...}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thehindu.com/news/international/article3291242.ece|title=Outcry as Gunter Grass poem strongly criticises Israel|work=The Hindu|date=8 April 2012|accessdate=8 April 2012|quote=During his long literary career, Gunter Grass has been many things. Author, playwright, sculptor and, unquestionably, Germany's most famous living writer. There is the 1999 Nobel Prize and Mr. Grass's broader post-war role as the country's moral conscience...|location=Chennai, India|first1=Luke|last1=Harding|first2=Harriet|last2=Sherwood}}</ref>\n\nHe was born in the [[Free City of Danzig]] (now [[Gda\u0144sk]], Poland). As a teenager, he served as a [[conscription|drafted]] soldier from late 1944 in the ''[[Waffen-SS]]'' and was taken as a [[prisoner of war]] by US forces at the end of the war in May 1945. He was released in April 1946. Trained as a stonemason and sculptor, Grass began writing in the 1950s. In his fiction, he frequently returned to the Danzig of his childhood.\n\nGrass is best known for his first novel, ''[[The Tin Drum]]'' (1959), a key text in European [[magic realism]]. It was the first book of his [[Danzig Trilogy]], the other two being ''[[Cat and Mouse (novella)|Cat and Mouse]]'' and ''[[Dog Years (novel)|Dog Years]]''. His works are frequently considered to have a [[Left-wing politics|left-wing]] political dimension, and Grass was an active supporter of the [[Social Democratic Party of Germany]] (SPD). ''The Tin Drum'' was [[The Tin Drum (film)|adapted as a film]] of the same name, which won both the 1979 [[Palme d'Or]] and the [[Academy Award for Best International Feature Film|Academy Award for Best Foreign Language Film]]. In 1999, the [[Swedish Academy]] awarded him the [[Nobel Prize in Literature]], praising him as a writer \"whose frolicsome black fables portray the forgotten face of history\".<ref name=\"nobelweb\"/>\n\n==Early life==\nGrass was born in the [[Free City of Danzig]] on 16 October 1927, to Wilhelm Grass (1899\u20131979), a [[Lutheranism|Lutheran]] [[Protestantism|Protestant]] of German origin, and Helene Grass (n\u00e9e Knoff, 1898\u20131954), a [[Catholic Church|Roman Catholic]] of [[Kashubians|Kashubian]]-[[Poles|Polish]] origin.<ref>Garland, ''The Oxford Companion to German Literature'', p. 302.</ref><ref>\"The Literary Encyclopedia\", [http://www.litencyc.com/php/speople.php?rec=true&UID=4990 G\u00fcnter Grass (b. 1927)]. Retrieved on 16 August 2006.</ref> He referred to himself as [[Kashubians|Kashubian]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://wyborcza.pl/1,75475,17744558,Gunter_Grass_nie_zyje__Noblista_mial_87_lat.html#ixzz3XDIG5oiR|title=G\u00fcnter Grass nie \u017cyje. Noblista mia\u0142 87 lat|work=Gazeta Wyborcza|date=13 April 2015|accessdate=13 April 2014|quote=Pytany o to\u017csamo\u015b\u0107 narodow\u0105, m\u00f3wi\u0142, \u017ce jest Kaszub\u0105. (Asking about his ethnicity, he always said that he's Kashubian)}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.focus.de/tagesthema/literatur-portraet-der-unbequeme-nationaldichter_id_4608522.html|title=Portr\u00e4t: Der unbequeme Nationaldichter|work=Focus|date=13 April 2015|accessdate=13 April 2014|quote=Aber wenige haben auch soviel einstecken m\u00fcssen wie der Kaschube aus Danzig. But, just few people had to take flak like the mustachioed Kashubian from Danzig}} (now Gda\u0144sk, Poland)</ref><ref name=\"ethnDEbook\">{{cite news|url=https://books.google.de/books?id=VmV2M05xxiEC&pg=PA61&lpg=PA61&dq=%22g%C3%BCnter+grass%22+%22kaschube%22&source=bl&ots=Rlr7HNFlXk&sig=-MUoexknLdb1j4vq2EL3PCJ6yYA&hl=de&sa=X&ei=osovVYu0BoOsPYLEgeAC&ved=0CCMQ6AEwATgK#v=onepage&q=%22g%C3%BCnter%20grass%22%20%22kaschube%22&f=false|title=Polnische Ostseek\u00fcste, Danzig, Masuren|work=Klaus Kl\u00f6ppel, Olaf Matthei|quote=Er bezeichnet sich selbst gerne als Kaschube}}</ref> Grass was raised a Catholic and served as an altar boy when he was a child.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tagesspiegel.de/zeitung/wer-ist-guenter-grass/739946.html|title=Wer ist G\u00fcnter Grass?|work=Der Tagesspiegel}}</ref> His parents had a grocery store with an attached apartment in Danzig-Langfuhr (now Gda\u0144sk-[[Wrzeszcz]]). He had a sister, Waltraud, born in 1930.<ref>{{cite book|author=Mayer, Claudia |year=2002|title=G\u00fcnter Grass|publisher=Deutscher Taschenbuch Verlag|page=16}}</ref>\n\n[[File:G\u00fcnter Grass pre-war house in Gda\u0144sk during a small snowstorm.jpg|left|thumb|upright|Grass's childhood home in Danzig (now Gda\u0144sk, Poland)]]\nGrass attended the Danzig [[Gymnasium (school)|gymnasium]] ''Conradinum''. In 1943, at age 16, he became a ''[[Luftwaffenhelfer]]'' (Air Force \"helper\"). Soon thereafter, he was conscripted into the ''[[Reich Labour Service|Reichsarbeitsdienst]]'' (National Labour Service). In November 1944, shortly after his 17th birthday, Grass volunteered for [[submarine]] service with [[Nazi Germany]]'s ''[[Kriegsmarine]]'', \"to get out of the confinement felt as a teenager in his parents' house\", which he considered stuffy Catholic lower middle-class.<ref>\"Katholischen Mief\".{{cite news|url=http://www.zeit.de/2006/34/Leiter-1-34|title=Und Grass wundert sich: Die \u00f6ffentliche Selbstrechtfertigung des gro\u00dfen Schriftstellers ist so unn\u00f6tig wie \u00e4rgerlich|work=Die Zeit|year=2006}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://edition.cnn.com/2006/WORLD/europe/08/11/germany.grass.ap/index.html|title=Nobel prize winner Grass admits serving in SS|work=Reuters|date=11 August 2006|accessdate=11 August 2006|archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20060825044934/http://edition.cnn.com/2006/WORLD/europe/08/11/germany.grass.ap/index.html|archivedate=25 August 2006}}</ref>\n\nThe Navy refused him and he was instead called up for the [[10th SS Panzer Division Frundsberg]] in late 1944.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.spiegel.de/kultur/literatur/0,1518,431333,00.html|title=Autor G\u00fcnter Grass: \"Ich war Mitglied der Waffen-SS\"|work=[[Der Spiegel]]|date=11 August 2006|accessdate=11 August 2006}}</ref><ref>[http://www.signandsight.com/features/899.html \"G\u00fcnter Grass was in the Waffen SS\"] \u2013 Survey of reactions to disclosure of time in the ''Waffen-SS'' from the German and international press</ref> Grass did not reveal until 2006 that he was drafted into the ''[[Waffen-SS]]'' at that time.<ref name=\"Feuilleton\">{{cite web|url=http://www.faz.net/s/RubCF3AEB154CE64960822FA5429A182360/Doc~ED1E99E51572441E696FB0443CA308A56~ATpl~Ecommon~Scontent.html|title=G\u00fcnter Grass im Interview: ''\"Warum ich nach sechzig Jahren mein Schweigen breche''\"|publisher=Feuilleton|date=|accessdate=31 October 2010}}</ref> His unit functioned as a regular ''Panzer'' Division, and he served with them from February 1945 until he was wounded on 20 April 1945. He was captured in [[Mari\u00e1nsk\u00e9 L\u00e1zn\u011b|Marienbad]] (now Mari\u00e1nsk\u00e9 L\u00e1zn\u011b, Czech Republic) and sent to a U.S. [[prisoner-of-war camp]] in [[Bad Aibling]], Bavaria.<ref name=Chronology>{{cite book|editor=Taberner, S. (Ed.). |year=2009|title=The Cambridge Companion to G\u00fcnter Grass|publisher=Cambridge University Presses|pages=xiv\u2013xviii}}</ref>\n\nFrom 1946 to 1947, Grass worked in a [[Mining|mine]] and received training in [[stonemasonry]]. He studied sculpture and graphics at the ''[[Kunstakademie D\u00fcsseldorf]]''. He also was a co-founder of [[Group 47]], organized by [[Hans Werner Richter]]. Grass worked as a writer, [[graphic designer]], and sculptor, travelling frequently. In 1953 he moved to West Berlin and studied at the [[Berlin University of the Arts]]. From 1960, he lived in Berlin as well as part-time in [[Schleswig-Holstein]].<ref>{{cite news|title=After many years spent living in Berlin's Friedenau district and a sojourn in the Algarve, Portugal, Grass settled in Behlendorf in Schleswig-Holstein|work=Der Spiegel|publisher=Spiegel Online GmbH|date=13 April 2015|url=http://www.spiegel.de/international/zeitgeist/a-1028399.html|accessdate=4 May 2015|location=Hamburg|first=Sebastian|last=Hammelehle}}</ref> In 1961 he publicly objected to the erection of the [[Berlin Wall]].\n\nFrom 1983 to 1986, he held the presidency of the [[Academy of Arts, Berlin]].<ref name=Chronology />\n\n==Personal life==\nGrass's 1954 marriage to Anna Margareta Schwarz - a Swiss dancer - ended in divorce in 1978. He and Schwarz had four children: Franz (born 1957), Raoul (1957), Laura (1961), and Bruno (1965). Separated in 1972, he began a relationship with Veronika Schr\u00f6ter and had a child with her, Helene (1974). He also had a child with Ingrid Kruger, Nele (1979). In 1979 he married Ute Grunert, an organist, to whom he was still married at his death.<ref name=Chronology /> He had two stepsons from his second marriage, Malte and Hans. He had 18 grandchildren at his death.<ref name=Chronology/><ref>{{cite news|last1=Donahue|first1=Patrick|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2015-04-13/guenter-grass-german-writer-who-took-on-nazi-past-dies-at-87|accessdate=13 April 2015|publisher=Bloomberg|date=April 13, 2005| title = Guenter Grass, German Writer Who Took On Nazism, Dies at 87}}</ref>\n\nGrass was a fan of Bundesliga Club [[SC Freiburg]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.rp-online.de/politik/nobelpreistraeger-drueckt-dem-sc-freiburg-die-daumen-aid-1.2263002|title=Nobelpreistr\u00e4ger dr\u00fcckt dem SC Freiburg die Daumen|date=20 February 2000|accessdate=13 April 2015|agency=RP Online}}</ref>\n\n==Major works==\n===Danzig Trilogy===\n{{main article|Danzig Trilogy}}\n[[File:Danzig Partie am Krahnthor (1890-1900).jpg|thumb|300px|Danzig ''Krahntor'' waterfront (postcard, c. 1900)]]\nGrass's best-known work is ''[[The Tin Drum]]'' (German: ''Die Blechtrommel''), published in 1959 (and adapted as a [[The Tin Drum (film)|film]] of the same name by director [[Volker Schl\u00f6ndorff]] in 1979). It was followed in 1961 by ''[[Cat and Mouse (novella)|Cat and Mouse]]'' (German: ''Katz und Maus''), a [[novella]], and in 1963 by the novel ''[[Dog Years (novel)|Dog Years]]'' (German: ''Hundejahre'').\n\nThe books are collectively called the [[Danzig Trilogy]] and focus on the rise of [[Nazism]] and how [[World War II]] affected Danzig (now Gda\u0144sk, Poland), which was separated from Germany after World War I and became the [[Free City of Danzig]] (German: ''Freie Stadt Danzig'').<ref>''International Law Reports'' (1948) by [[Elihu Lauterpacht]], p. 207</ref> [[Dog Years (novel)|''Dog Years'']] (1965) is considered a sequel of sorts to ''The Tin Drum'', as it features some of the same characters.<ref>''The Thomas Mann Handbook'' (2013) by Emily Smith, page 168</ref> It portrays the area's mixed ethnicities and complex historical background in lyrical prose that is highly evocative.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://english.dcbooks.com/author-of-tin-drum-gunter-grass-died.html|title=Author of ''Tin Drum'', G\u00fcnter Grass died|publisher=DC Books|accessdate=April 15, 2015}}</ref>\n\n''The Tin Drum'' established Grass as one of the leading authors of Germany, and also set a high bar of comparison for all of his subsequent works, which were often compared unfavorably to this early work by critics.<ref>{{cite book|author=Mews, S. |year=2008|title=G\u00fcnter Grass and His Critics: From ''The Tin Drum'' to ''Crabwalk''|publisher=Camden House|pages=[[passim]]}}</ref> Nonetheless, in the West Germany of the late '50s and early '60s the book could be controversial, and its \"immorality\" prompted the city of [[Bremen]] to revoke a prize it had bestowed upon him.<ref name=Chronology /> When Grass received the Nobel Prize in literature in 1999 the Nobel Committee stated that the publication of ''The Tin Drum'' \"was as if German literature had been granted a new beginning after decades of linguistic and moral destruction\"<ref>{{cite book|author=Mews, S. |year=2008|title=G\u00fcnter Grass and His Critics: From ''The Tin Drum'' to ''Crabwalk''|publisher=Camden House|page=1}}</ref>\n\n===''The Flounder''===\nThe 1977 novel ''[[The Flounder]]'' (German: ''Der Butt'') is based on the folktale of \"[[The Fisherman and His Wife]]\", and deals with the struggle between the sexes. It has been read as an anti-feminist novel, since in the novel the magical flounder of the folk tale, now representing male triumphalism and the patriarchy is caught by a group of 1970s feminists, who put it on trial. The book interrogates male-female relations from the past and the present through the relationship between the narrator and his wife, who as the wife in the folk tale, insatiably craves more.<ref>{{cite book|author=O'Neill, Patrick |chapter=The Exploratory Fiction of G\u00fcnter Grass|editor=Taberner, S. (Ed.). |year=2009|title=The Cambridge Companion to G\u00fcnter Grass|publisher=Cambridge University Press}}</ref> In spite of the fact that the book could be read as a defense of women and a denouncement of male chauvinism, the book was harshly critiqued and rejected by feminists, partly due to its portrayal of violence, sexualization and objectification, and what the feminists perceived as [[Sex differences in narcissism|male narcissism]] and [[gender essentialism]].<ref>{{cite book|author=Finch, Helen|chapter=G\u00fcnter Grass and Gender|editor=Taberner, S. (Ed.). |year=2009|title=The Cambridge Companion to G\u00fcnter Grass|publisher=Cambridge University Press}}</ref>\n\n===''My Century'' and ''Crabwalk''===\nThe 1999 book ''[[My Century]]'' (German: ''Mein Jahrhundert'') was an overview of the 20th-century's many brutal historic events, conveyed in short pieces, a mosaic of expression. In 2002, Grass returned to the forefront of world literature with ''[[Crabwalk]]'' (German: ''Im Krebsgang''). This novella, one of whose main characters first appeared in ''Cat and Mouse'', was Grass's most successful work in decades. It dealt with the events of a refugee ship, full of thousands of Germans, being sunk by a Russian submarine, killing most on board. It was one of a number of works since the late 20th century that have explored the victimization of Germans in World War II.<ref>{{cite journal|author=Krimmer, E.|year=2008|title='Ein Volk von Opfern?' Germans as Victims in G\u00fcnter Grass's ''Die Blechtrommel'' and ''Im Krebsgang''|journal=Seminar: A Journal of Germanic Studies|volume=44|issue=2|pages=272\u2013290|publisher=University of Toronto Press.}}</ref>\n\n===Memoir trilogy===\nIn 2006, Grass published the first volume in a trilogy of autobiographic memoirs. Titled ''[[Peeling the Onion]]'' (German: ''Beim H\u00e4uten der Zwiebel''), it dealt with his childhood, war years, early efforts as a sculptor and poet, and finally his literary success with the publication of ''The Tin Drum''. In a prepublication interview Grass for the first time revealed that he had been a member of the [[Waffen-SS]], and not only a ''Flakhelfer'' (anti-aircraft assistant) as he had long said. On being asked what caused the need for public confession and revelation of his past in the book he answered: \"It was a weight on me, my silence over all these years is one of the reasons I wrote the book. It had to come out in the end.\"<ref name=NYT />\n\nThe interview and the book caused critics to accuse him of hypocrisy for having hidden this part of his past, while simultaneously being a strong voice for ethics and morality in the public debate.<ref name=NYT /> The book itself was also praised for its depictions of [[History of Germany (1945\u20131990)|the German postwar generation]] and the social and moral development of a nation burdened simultaneously by destruction and a deep sense of guilt.<ref>{{cite web|title=Book Review: G\u00fcnter Grass' ''Peeling the Onion'' \u2013 G\u00fcnter Grass articulates his life, eloquently describing the troubles of the post-war generation and the desperate attempt to rebuild a life out of ruins while coming to terms with one's own guilt.|author=Izvor Moralic|date=October 1, 2006|publisher=Viennareview.net|url=http://www.viennareview.net/vienna-review-book-reviews/upcoming-literary-events/peeling-the-onion|access-date=April 13, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160128133743/http://www.viennareview.net/vienna-review-book-reviews/upcoming-literary-events/peeling-the-onion|archive-date=January 28, 2016|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Throughout the memoir Grass plays with the frailty of memory, for which the layers of the onion are a metaphor. Grass second-guesses his own memories, throws his own autobiographical statements into doubt and questions whether the person inhabiting his past was really him. This struggle with memory comes to represent the struggle of the German people during the same period with Germany's Nazi past.<ref>{{cite book|quote=Peeled, it renews itself; chopped, it brings tears; only during peeling does it speak the truth.|title=Confessions of a super Grass|publisher=The Guardian.com|author=Tim Gardan|url=https://www.theguardian.com/books/2007/jun/24/biography.guntergrass}}</ref>\n\n==Main themes and literary style==\nA main theme in Grass's work is World War II and its effects on Germany and the German people, including a critique of the forms of ideological reasoning that undergirded the Nazi regime. The place of the city of Danzig/Gda\u0144sk and its ambiguous historical status in between Germany and Poland often stands as a symbol of the ambiguity between ethnic groups, also found in Grass's own heritage which includes both German and Slavic family members who fought on opposite sides of the war. His works also show a sustained concern for the marginal and marginalized subjects, such as Oskar Matzerath, the dwarf in ''The Tin Drum'' whose body was considered an aberration unworthy of life in the Nazi ideology, or with [[Romani people|Roma]] and [[Sinti]] people who were also deemed impure and unworthy and subjected to eugenics and genocide.<ref>{{cite book|author=Arnds, P. O. |year=2004|title=Representation, subversion, and eugenics in G\u00fcnter Grass's ''The Tin Drum''|publisher=Camden House}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|editor=Taberner, S. (Ed.). |year=2009|title=The Cambridge Companion to G\u00fcnter Grass|publisher=Cambridge University Press}}</ref>\n\nHis literary style combines elements of [[magic realism]], with a penchant for questioning and complicating questions of authorship by intermingling realistic autobiographical elements with [[unreliable narrator]]s and fantastic events or happenings that creates irony or satirizes events to form social critiques.<ref>{{cite book|author=Braun, R. |year=2008|title=Constructing Authorship in the Work of G\u00fcnter Grass|publisher= Oxford University Press}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|author=Arnds, P. O.|chapter=G\u00fcnter Grass and Magical Realism|editor=Taberner, S. (Ed.). |year=2009|title=The Cambridge Companion to G\u00fcnter Grass|publisher=Cambridge University Press}}</ref>\n\n==Reception by critics and colleagues==\nGrass's work has tended to divide the critics into those who have considered his experiments and style to be sublime and those who have found it to be tied down by his political posturing. Particularly American critics such as [[John Updike]] have found the mixture of politics and social critique in his works to diminish its artistic qualities.<ref>{{cite book|author=Mews, S. |year=2008|title=G\u00fcnter Grass and His Critics: From ''The Tin Drum'' to ''Crabwalk''|publisher=Camden House}}</ref> In his various critiques of Grass's works, Updike wrote that Grass had been consumed by his \"strenuous career as celebrity-author-artist-Socialist\" and about one of his later novels that \"he can't be bothered to write a novel; he just sends dispatches ... from the front lines of his engagement\". Even if frequently critical of Grass, Updike considered him to be \"one of the very, very few authors whose next novel one has no intention of missing\".<ref>{{cite book|author=Mews, S. |year=2008|title=G\u00fcnter Grass and His Critics: From ''The Tin Drum'' to ''Crabwalk''|publisher=Camden House|pages=107, 146, 195}}</ref>\n\nGrass's literary style has been widely influential. [[John Irving]] called Grass \"simply the most original and versatile writer alive\". And many have noted parallels between Irving's ''A Prayer for Owen Meany'' and ''The Tin Drum''.<ref>{{cite book|author=Mews, S. |year=2008|title=G\u00fcnter Grass and His Critics: From ''The Tin Drum'' to ''Crabwalk''|publisher=Camden House|page=53}}</ref> Similarly, [[Salman Rushdie]] has acknowledged a debt to Grass's work, particularly ''The Tin Drum'', and many parallels to Grass's work have been pointed out in his own oeuvre.<ref>{{cite book|author=Mews, S. |year=2008|title=G\u00fcnter Grass and His Critics: From ''The Tin Drum'' to ''Crabwalk''|publisher=Camden House|page=55}}</ref>\n\n==Social and political activism==\n[[File:G\u00fcnter Grass (1986) by Erling Mandelmann.jpg|thumb|upright|Grass in 1986]]\nGrass was for several decades a supporter of the [[Social Democratic Party of Germany]] and its policies. He took part in German and international political debate on several occasions. During [[Willy Brandt]]'s chancellorship, Grass was an active supporter. Grass criticised left-wing radicals and instead argued in favour of the \"snail's pace\", as he put it, of [[Reformism|democratic reform]] (''Aus dem Tagebuch einer Schnecke''). Books containing his speeches and essays were released throughout his literary career.<ref name=Chronology/>\n\nIn the 1980s, he became active in the [[peace movement]] and visited [[Kolkata|Calcutta]] for six months.<ref name=Chronology/> A diary with drawings was published as ''Zunge zeigen'', an allusion to [[Kali]]'s tongue.\n\nDuring the events leading up to the [[German reunification|reunification of Germany]] in 1989\u201390, Grass argued for the continued separation of the two German states. He asserted that a unified Germany would be likely to resume its role as belligerent nation-state. This argument estranged many Germans, who came to see him as too much of a moralizing figure.<ref name=NYT>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/04/14/world/europe/gunter-grass-german-novelist-dies-at-87.html?_r=0|work=[[The New York Times]]|author=Stephen Kinzer|authorlink=Stephen Kinzer|title=G\u00fcnter Grass, German Novelist and Social Critic, Dies at 87}}</ref>\n\nIn 2001, Grass proposed the creation of a German-Polish museum for art lost to other countries during the War. The [[Hague Conventions of 1899 and 1907|Hague Convention of 1907]] requires the return of art that had been evacuated, stolen or seized. Some countries refused to repatriate some of the [[looted art]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.faz.net/s/RubEBED639C476B407798B1CE808F1F6632/Doc~E73D9568D79A14F7CB8686D42EC8ACD04~ATpl~Ecommon~Scontent.html |title=R\u00fcckgabe von Beutekunst: Die letzten deutschen Kriegsgefangenen|publisher=Feuilleton|date=26 October 2010|accessdate=31 October 2010}}</ref><ref>[http://www.spiegel.de/kultur/gesellschaft/0,1518,498915,00.html ''Der Spiegel''].</ref>\n\nOn 4 April 2012, Grass's poem \"[[What Must Be Said]]\" (German: ''Was gesagt werden muss'') was published in several European newspapers. Grass expressed his concern about the hypocrisy of German military support (the delivery of a submarine) for an [[Israel]] that might use such equipment to launch nuclear warheads against Iran, which \"could wipe out the Iranian people\". And he hoped that many would demand \"that the governments of both Iran and Israel allow an international authority free and open inspection of the nuclear potential and capability of both.\" In response, Israel declared him ''[[persona non grata]]'' in that country.<ref name=haaretz_persona_non_grata>{{cite news|first1=Ophir|last1=Bar-Zohar|first2=Barak|last2=Ravid|url=http://www.haaretz.com/news/diplomacy-defense/interior-minister-declares-gunter-grass-persona-non-grata-in-israel-1.423239|title=Interior Minister declares Gunter Grass persona non grata in Israel|work=[[Haaretz]]|date=8 April 2012|accessdate=8 April 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|author=G\u00fcnter Grass |url=https://www.theguardian.com/books/2012/apr/05/gunter-grass-what-must-be-said?intcmp=239|title=What Must Be Said|work=The Guardian|date=5 April 2012|accessdate=15 January 2013|location=London}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Weinthal |first=Benjamin |url=http://www.jpost.com/International/Article.aspx?id=265415|title=Benjamin Weinthal: Berlin politicians split over Grass travel ban|work=The Jerusalem Post|date=3 January 2013|accessdate=15 January 2013}}</ref>\n\nAccording to [[Avi Primor]], president of the [[Israel Council on Foreign Relations]], Grass was the only important German cultural figure who had refused to meet with him when he served as [[List of ambassadors of Israel to Germany|Israeli ambassador to Germany]]. Primor noted: \"One explanation for [Grass']s strange behaviour might be found in the fact that Grass (who despite his poem is probably not the bitter enemy of Israel that one would imagine) had certain personal difficulties with Israel.\" Primor said that during Grass's earlier visit to Israel, he \"was confronted with the anger of an Israeli public that booed him in successive public appearances. To be sure, the Israeli protestors were not targeting Grass personally and their anger had nothing at all to do with his literature. It was the German effort to establish cultural relations with Israel to which they objected. Grass, however, did not see it that way and may well have felt personally slighted.\"<ref>[[Avi Primor]], \"Peeling G\u00fcnter Grass' Israeli Onion\", ''Israel Journal of Foreign Affairs,'' Vol. 6, No. 2 (2012), p. 103 [http://israelcfr.com/documents/6-2/6-2-8-AviPrimor.pdf (PDF)] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140825153611/http://www.israelcfr.com/documents/6-2/6-2-8-AviPrimor.pdf |date=2014-08-25 }}</ref>\n\nGrass was a supporter of the [[Campaign for the Establishment of a United Nations Parliamentary Assembly]], an organisation which campaigns for democratic reformation of the United Nations, and the creation of a more accountable international political system.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://en.unpacampaign.org/supporters/overview/?mapcountry=allhea&mapgroup=hea|title=Overview|date=|work=Campaign for a UN Parliamentary Assembly|access-date=2017-09-26}}</ref>\n\nOn 26 April 2012, Grass wrote a poem criticizing European policy for the treatment of Greece in the [[European debt crisis]]. In \"Europe's Disgrace\", Grass accuses Europe of condemning Greece to poverty, a country \"whose mind conceived Europe.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://newsticker.sueddeutsche.de/list/id/1319034|title=Newsticker|work=[[S\u00fcddeutsche Zeitung]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ekathimerini.com/4dcgi/_w_articles_wsite1_1_27/05/2012_444146 |title=Gunter Grass stands by poem about Greece and Europe|work=Ekathimerini|date=27 May 2012|accessdate=15 January 2013}}</ref>\n\nJust a few days before he died Grass completed his last book, ''Vonne Endlichkait''. The title is in [[East Prussia]]n dialect, the native dialect of Grass, and it means \"About Finitude.\" According to his publisher Gerhard Steidl, the book was \"a literary experiment\", combining short prose texts, poems and a pencil drawings by the writer.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dw.com/en/g%C3%BCnter-grass-leaves-a-last-farewell-book/a-18671538|title=G\u00fcnter Grass leaves a last farewell book {{!}} Books {{!}} DW.COM {{!}} 26.08.2015|last=(www.dw.com)|first=Deutsche Welle|website=DW.COM|access-date=2016-10-17}}</ref> The book was published in August 2015.\n\n==Awards and honours==\n[[File:G\u00fcnter Grass and Willy Brandt.jpg|thumb|Grass with the West German Chancellor [[Willy Brandt]], 1972]]\nGrass received dozens of international awards; in 1999, he was awarded the highest literary honour: the [[Nobel Prize in Literature]]. The [[Swedish Academy]] noted him as a writer \"whose frolicsome black fables portray the forgotten face of history\".<ref name=\"nobelweb\">{{cite web|url=http://nobelprize.org/nobel_prizes/literature/laureates/1999/|title=The Nobel Prize in Literature 1999|accessdate=8 October 2009|publisher=Nobelprize.org}}</ref> His literature is commonly categorised as part of the German artistic movement known as ''[[Vergangenheitsbew\u00e4ltigung]]'', roughly translated as \"coming to terms with the past.\"\n\nIn 1965, Grass received the [[Georg B\u00fcchner Prize]]; in 1993 he was elected an Honorary Fellow of the [[Royal Society of Literature]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rslit.org/content/fellows|title=Royal Society of Literature All Fellows|work=Royal Society of Literature|accessdate=8 August 2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100305070326/http://www.rslit.org/content/fellows|archivedate=5 March 2010}}</ref> In 1995, he received the [[Hermann Kesten Prize]].\n\nRepresentatives of the city of [[Bremen]] joined together to establish the G\u00fcnter Grass Foundation with the aim of establishing a centralized collection of his numerous works, especially his many personal readings, videos and films. The G\u00fcnter Grass House in [[L\u00fcbeck]] houses exhibitions of his drawings and sculptures, an archive and a library.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.luebeck-tourism.de/culture/museums/guenter-grass-house.html|title=Gunter Grass House Lubeck}}</ref>\n\nIn 2012, Grass received the award European of the Year from the European Movement Denmark (Europabev\u00e6gelsen) honoring his political debates in European affairs.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://jyllands-posten.dk/international/europa/ECE4945915/G%C3%BCnter+Grass+bliver+%C3%A5rets+europ%C3%A6er+/|title=Gunter Grass bliver \u00e5rets Europ\u00e6er| publisher=Jyllandsposten}}</ref>\n\n==''Waffen-SS'' revelations==\nIn August 2006, in an interview about his forthcoming book, ''Peeling the Onion'', Grass said that he had been a member of the ''[[Waffen-SS]]'' in World War II.<ref name=\"Feuilleton\" /> Prior to that, he had been considered a typical member of the \"[[Luftwaffenhelfer|Flakhelfer]] generation\", one of those too young to see much fighting or to be involved with the Nazi regime beyond its youth organizations.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.faz.net/aktuell/gesellschaft/menschen/guenter-grass-enthuellt-ich-war-mitglied-der-waffen-ss-1354882.html|agency=Frankfurter Allgemeine Gesellschaft|title=Ich war Mitglied der Waffen-SS|date=11 August 2006|accessdate=13 April 2015|language=German}}</ref>\n\nOn 15 August 2006, the online edition of ''[[Der Spiegel]]'', [[Spiegel Online]], published three 1946 documents from U.S. forces verifying Grass's ''Waffen-SS'' membership.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.spiegel.de/kultur/gesellschaft/0,1518,431823,00.html|title=Grass r\u00e4umte als Kriegsgefangener Waffen-SS-Mitgliedschaft ein|work=Der Spiegel|accessdate=31 October 2010}}</ref>\n\nAfter an unsuccessful attempt to volunteer for the [[U-boat]] fleet in 1942, at age 15, Grass was conscripted into the ''[[Reichsarbeitsdienst]]'' (Reich Labor Service). He was called up for the ''Waffen-SS'' in 1944. Grass was trained as a tank gunner and fought with the [[10th SS Panzer Division Frundsberg]] until its surrender to U.S. forces at [[Mari\u00e1nsk\u00e9 L\u00e1zn\u011b|Marienbad]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://nypost.com/2015/04/13/noble-laureate-gunter-grass-dead-at-87/|work=[[New York Post]]|title=Noble laureate G\u00fcnter Grass dead at 87|date=13 April 2015|accessdate=13 April 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"nyer\">{{cite news|last=Grass|first=G\u00fcnter|title=How I Spent the War: A recruit in the Waffen S.S.|work=[[The New Yorker]]|date=4 June 2007|url=http://www.newyorker.com/reporting/2007/06/04/070604fa_fact_grass?currentPage=all|accessdate=24 May 2007}}</ref>\n\nIn 2007, Grass published an account of his wartime experience in ''[[The New Yorker]]'', including an attempt to \"string together the circumstances that probably triggered and nourished my decision to enlist.\"<ref name=\"nyer\" /> To the [[BBC]], Grass said in 2006: \"It happened as it did to many of my age. We were in the labour service and all at once, a year later, the call-up notice lay on the table. And only when I got to Dresden did I learn it was the Waffen-SS.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/4785851.stm|title=Guenter Grass served in Waffen SS|work=BBC News|date=11 August 2006|accessdate=11 August 2006}}</ref>\n\n[[Joachim Fest]] \u2013 German journalist, historian and biographer of [[Adolf Hitler]] \u2013 remarked, to the German weekly ''[[Der Spiegel]]'', on Grass's disclosure: \"After 60 years, this confession comes a bit too late. I can't understand how someone who for decades set himself up as a moral authority, a rather smug one, could pull this off.\"<ref>{{cite news|title=Grass admits serving in Waffen SS|work=Reuters|date=13 August 2006|url=http://www.iht.com/articles/2006/08/13/news/grass.php|accessdate=13 August 2006}}</ref>\n\nAs Grass was for many decades an outspoken left-leaning critic of Germany's failure to deal with its Nazi past, his statement caused a great stir in the press. [[Rolf Hochhuth]] said it was \"disgusting\" that this same \"politically correct\" Grass had publicly criticized [[Helmut Kohl]] and [[Ronald Reagan]]'s visit to a military cemetery at [[Bitburg]] in 1985, because it contained graves of ''Waffen-SS'' soldiers.<ref name=NYT /> In the same vein, the historian [[Michael Wolffsohn]] accused Grass of hypocrisy in not earlier disclosing his SS membership.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.dw.de/nobel-prize-winner-grass-under-fire-for-belated-ss-confession/a-2132108|agency=Deutsche Welle|title=Nobel Prize Winner Grass Under Fire for Belated SS Confession|date=14 August 2006|accessdate=13 April 2015}}</ref>\n\nOthers defended Grass, saying his involuntary ''Waffen-SS'' membership came very early in his life, resulting from his being drafted shortly after his seventeenth birthday. They noted he had always \u2013 after the war was lost \u2013 been publicly critical of Germany's Nazi past. For example, novelist [[John Irving]] criticised those who would dismiss the achievements of a lifetime because of a mistake made as a teenager.<ref>{{cite news\n| title = G\u00fcnter Grass is my hero, as a writer and a moral compass\n| work = The Guardian\n| publisher = Guardian Media Group\n| date = 19 August 2006\n| url = https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/story/0,,1853745,00.html\n| accessdate = 19 August 2006\n| location = London\n| first = John\n| last = Irving|authorlink=John Irving}}</ref>\n\nGrass's biographer {{Interlanguage link multi|Michael J\u00fcrgs|de}} described the controversy as resulting in \"the end of a moral institution\".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.spiegel.de/kultur/literatur/0,1518,431412,00.html|title=Echo auf Grass' SS-Vergangenheit: \"Ende einer moralischen Instanz\"|work=Der Spiegel|date=12 August 2006|accessdate=31 October 2010}}</ref> [[Lech Wa\u0142\u0119sa]] initially criticized Grass for keeping silent about his ''Waffen-SS'' membership for 60 years. He later withdrew his criticism after reading Grass's letter to the mayor of Gda\u0144sk, saying that Grass \"set the good example for the others.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.spiegel.de/kultur/literatur/0,1518,431491,00.html|title=SS-Vergangenheit: Walesa macht Grass Ehrenb\u00fcrgerw\u00fcrde streitig|work=Der Spiegel|date=|accessdate=31 October 2010}}</ref>\nOn 14 August 2006, the ruling party of Poland, [[Law and Justice]], called on Grass to relinquish his honorary citizenship of Gda\u0144sk. [[Jacek Kurski]], a Law and Justice politician said, \"It is unacceptable for a city where the first blood was shed, where World War II began, to have a Waffen-SS member as an honorary citizen.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://wiadomosci.wp.pl/kat,1342,title,Kurski-Grass-nie-rozumie-czym-zranil-Polakow,wid,8466747,wiadomosc.html?ticaid=114af2|agency=Wiadomo\u015bci|date=17 August 2006|accessdate=13 April 2015|title=Kurski: Grass nie rozumie, czym zrani\u0142 Polak\u00f3w|language=Polish}}</ref> But, according to a 2010 poll<ref>{{cite news|url=http://serwisy.gazeta.pl/kraj/1,34317,3560655.html|title=Kraj \u2013 Gazeta.pl|work=Serwisy.gazeta.pl|accessdate=31 October 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081009210534/http://serwisy.gazeta.pl/kraj/1,34317,3560655.html|archive-date=9 October 2008|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>http://bi.gazeta.pl/im/4/3561/m3561294.jpg</ref> ordered by city's authorities, the vast majority of Gda\u0144sk citizens did not support Kurski's position. The mayor of Gda\u0144sk, [[Pawe\u0142 Adamowicz]], said that he opposed submitting the affair to the municipal council because it was not for the council to judge history.<ref>\n{{cite news\n| last = Rakowiec\n| first = Ma\u0142gorzata\n| title = Grass asked to give up Polish title\n| work = Reuters\n| date = 14 August 2006\n| url = http://news.scotsman.com/latest.cfm?id=1185192006\n| accessdate = 14 August 2006\n| location=Edinburgh}}{{Dead link|date=October 2010|bot=H3llBot}}</ref>\n\n==Death==\n[[File:Grave Guenter Grass in Behlendorf.jpg|thumb|Grave of G\u00fcnter Grass in Behlendorf]]\nAn avid pipe smoker for most of his adult life, Grass died of a lung infection on 13 April 2015 in a [[L\u00fcbeck]] hospital at the age of 87.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dw.de/renowned-german-author-g%C3%BCnter-grass-dies-aged-87/a-18377707|title=Renowned German author G\u00fcnter Grass dies, aged 87|publisher=DW.de|accessdate=April 14, 2015}}</ref><ref name=bbc-obit>[https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-32285705 German author Guenter Grass dies], ''BBC News'', 13 April 2015.</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/books/2015/apr/13/gunter-grass-german-nobel-laureate-dies-aged-87|title=G\u00fcnter Grass, Nobel-winning German novelist, dies aged 87|author=Richard Lea|work=the Guardian}}</ref> He was buried in a private family observance on 25 April in [[Behlendorf]], 15 miles south of L\u00fcbeck, where he had lived since 1995.\n\nU.S. novelist [[John Irving]] delivered the main eulogy at a memorial service for Grass on 10 May in the [[Theater L\u00fcbeck]]. Among those who attended were German President [[Joachim Gauck]], federal Commissioner for Culture [[Monika Gr\u00fctters]], and [[Pawe\u0142 Adamowicz]], mayor of Gda\u0144sk.<ref>[http://www.spiegel.de/kultur/literatur/guenter-grass-trauerfeier-in-luebeck-a-1033062.html \"Abschied von G\u00fcnter Grass: 'Der K\u00f6nig der Spielzeugh\u00e4ndler'&thinsp;\"], ''[[Der Spiegel]]'', 10 May 2015 {{in lang|de}}</ref> Gr\u00fctters, in remarks to mourners, noted that Grass through his work championed the independence of artists and of art itself.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ln-online.de/Nachrichten/Kultur/Bewegende-Gedenkfeier-fuer-Guenter-Grass|title=Bewegende Gedenkfeier f\u00fcr G\u00fcnter Grass|work=[[L\u00fcbecker Nachrichten]]|accessdate=May 10, 2015}}</ref> Adamowicz said Grass had \"bridged the chasm between Germany and Poland,\" and praised the novelist's \"unwillingness to compromise.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.express.de/news/gedenkfeier-fuer-guenter-grass--koenig-der-spielzeughaendler-ist-gegangen--1723388|title=Gedenkfeier f\u00fcr G\u00fcnter Grass \u2013 'K\u00f6nig der Spielzeugh\u00e4ndler ist gegangen'&thinsp;|author=J\u00fcrgen Kowallik|work=[[Express (Cologne newspaper)|Express]]|date=10 May 2015|location=Cologne|access-date=29 September 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Bibliography==\n* ''Die Vorz\u00fcge der Windh\u00fchner'' (poems, 1956); Steidl, 2007, {{ISBN|9783865215697}}\n* ''Die b\u00f6sen K\u00f6che. Ein Drama'' (play, 1956) ISSN 0722-8511 translated as ''The Wicked Cooks'' in ''Four Plays'' (1967)\n* ''Hochwasser. Ein St\u00fcck in zwei Akten'' (play, 1957) ''The Flood''\n* ''Onkel, Onkel. Ein Spiel in vier Akten'' (play, 1958) ''Mister, Mister''\n* ''[[Danzig Trilogy|Danziger Trilogie]]''\n** ''Die Blechtrommel'' (novel, 1959) trans. ''[[The Tin Drum]]'' (1959) {{ISBN|978-0-679-72575-6}}.\n** ''Katz und Maus'' (novella, 1961) trans. ''[[Cat and Mouse (novella)|Cat and Mouse]]'' (1963) {{ISBN|9780156155519}}\n** ''Hundejahre'' (novel, 1963) trans. ''[[Dog Years (novel)|Dog Years]]'' (1965) {{ISBN|9780749394509}}\n* ''Gleisdreieck'' (poems, 1960)\n* ''Die Plebejer proben den Aufstand'' (play, 1966) trans. ''The Plebeians Rehearse the Uprising'' (1966)\n* ''Ausgefragt'' (poems, 1967)\n* ''\u00dcber das Selbstverst\u00e4ndliche. Reden \u2013 Aufs\u00e4tze \u2013 Offene Briefe \u2013 Kommentare'' (speeches, essays, 1968) trans. ''Speak out! Speeches, Open Letters, Commentaries'' (1969) with 3 additional pieces\n* ''\u00d6rtlich bet\u00e4ubt'' (novel, 1969) trans. ''[[Local Anaesthetic (novel)|Local Anaesthetic]]'' (1970) {{ISBN|9780449242575}}\n* ''Davor'' (play, 1970) trans. ''Max'' (1972) on a plot from ''Local Anaesthetic''\n* ''Aus dem Tagebuch einer Schnecke'' (political reportage, 1972) trans. ''[[From the Diary of a Snail]]'' (1973) {{ISBN|9780749394554}}\n* ''Der B\u00fcrger und seine Stimme. Reden Aufs\u00e4tze Kommentare'' (speeches, essays, 1974)\n* ''Denkzettel. Politische Reden und Aufs\u00e4tze 1965\u20131976'' (political essays and speeches, 1978)\n* ''Der Butt'' (novel, 1977) trans. ''[[The Flounder]]'' (1978) {{ISBN|9780156319355}}\n* ''Das Treffen in Telgte'' (novel, 1979) trans. ''[[The Meeting at Telgte]]'' (1981)\n* ''Kopfgeburten oder Die Deutschen sterben aus'' (novel, 1980) trans. ''[[Headbirths, or, the Germans are Dying Out]]'' (1982)\n* ''Widerstand lernen. Politische Gegenreden 1980\u20131983'' (political speeches, 1984)\n* ''Die R\u00e4ttin'' (novel, 1986) trans. ''[[The Rat (novel)|The Rat]]'' (1987) {{ISBN|9780156758307}}\n* ''Zunge zeigen. Ein Tagebuch in Zeichnungen'' (political diary, 1988) trans. ''[[Show Your Tongue]]'' (1989)\n* ''Unkenrufe'' (novel, 1992) trans. ''[[The Call of the Toad]]'' (1992) {{ISBN|9780156153409}}\n* ''Ein weites Feld'' (novel, 1995) trans. ''[[Too Far Afield]]'' (2000) {{ISBN|9780156014168}}\n* ''Mein Jahrhundert'' (novel, 1999) trans. ''[[My Century]]'' (1999) {{ISBN|9780156011419}}\n* ''Im Krebsgang'' (novel, 2002) trans. ''[[Crabwalk]]'' (2002) {{ISBN|9780156029704}}\n* ''Letzte T\u00e4nze'' (poems, 2003)\n* ''Beim H\u00e4uten der Zwiebel'' (memoir, 2006) trans. ''[[Peeling the Onion]]'' (2007) {{ISBN|9780156035347}} \u2013 first volume of memoir\n* ''Dummer August'' (poems, 2007)\n* ''Die Box'' (memoir, 2008) trans. ''[[The Box (Grass book)|The Box]]'' (2010) {{ISBN|9780099539759}} \u2013 second volume of memoir\n* ''Unterwegs von Deutschland nach Deutschland. Tagebuch 1990.'' (political diary, 2009) trans. ''From Germany to Germany: Diary 1990'' (2012) {{ISBN|9780547364605}}\n* ''Grimms W\u00f6rter'' (memoir, 2010) Third volume of memoir.<ref name=\"bibliography\">{{cite web|url=https://www.nobelprize.org/nobel_prizes/literature/laureates/1999/grass-bibl.html|publisher=Nobelprize.org|title=The Nobel Prize in Literature 1999: G\u00fcnter Grass \u2013 Bibliography|accessdate=13 April 2015}}</ref>\n* ''Vonne Endlichkait'' (collection of prose, poetry, and drawings, 2015) {{ISBN|9783958290426}}\n\n'''Collections in English translation'''\n* ''Four Plays'' (1967) including ''Ten Minutes to Buffalo''\n* ''In the Egg and Other Poems'' (1977)\n* ''Two States One Nation?'' (1990)<ref name=\"bibliography\" />\n* ''Of All That Ends'' (poetry and prose) (6 December 2016) {{ISBN|978-0544785380}}\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of Nobel laureates in Literature]]\n* [[List of people declared persona non grata]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|G\u00fcnter Grass}}\n{{Wikiquote}}\n* {{worldcat id|id=lccn-n80-85270}}\n* {{Perlentaucher|guenter-grass}}\n* [http://www.gdansk-life.com/poland/gunter-grass G\u00fcnter Grass] at gdansk-life.com {{in lang|en}}\n* [https://www.theguardian.com/secondworldwar/story/0,,1843187,00.html \"Grass admits serving with Waffen-SS\"], ''[[The Guardian]]''\n* {{cite journal|url=http://www.theparisreview.org/interviews/2191/the-art-of-fiction-no-124-gunter-grass|title=Gunter Grass, The Art of Fiction No. 124|journal=[[The Paris Review]]|date=Summer 1991|first=Elizabeth|last=Gaffney|authorlink=Elizabeth Gaffney}}\n* {{cite interview|url=http://www.nypl.org/events/programs/2007/06/27/20th-century-trial-g%C3%BCnter-grass-norman-mailer-interviewed-and-conversatio|title=The 20th Century on Trial|subject=G\u00fcnter Grass|subject2=Norman Mailer|subject-link2=Norman Mailer|interviewer=[[Andrew O'Hagan]]|publisher=[[New York Public Library]]|year=2007}}\n* {{cite news|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/p004d1b6|title=G\u00fcnter Grass talking about ''The Tin Drum''|work=[[World Book Club]]|publisher=BBC|date=3 October 2009}}\n*{{C-SPAN|Gunter Grass}}\n{{s-start}}\n{{S-ach}}\n{{succession box\n|before = {{flagicon|Denmark}} [[Henrik, Prince Consort of Denmark]]\n|title = European of the Year<br/><small>(by the Danish European Movement)</small>\n|years = 2012\n|after = {{flagicon|Denmark}} [[Emmelie de Forest]]\n}}\n{{s-end}}\n{{G\u00fcnter Grass}}\n{{Navboxes\n|title= Awards received by G\u00fcnter Grass\n|list1=\n{{Georg B\u00fcchner Prize}}\n{{Sonning Prize laureates}}\